<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Brite-DecatursCompete     05-24 0342</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Brite-Decaturs Compete,0352</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Decaturs Throughout Country Compete To Help Needy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DECATUR, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Decatur is competing against Decatur and
another Decatur and yet another Decatur.
   And there are eight more Decaturs in the contest for good
measure.
   Cities and counties named Decatur in 12 states are participating
in a Cans Across the County food collection drive to help the needy
in their areas.
   The food will be distributed in the Decaturs in Alabama,
Arkansas, Georgia, Illinois, Indiana, Iowa, Kansas, Michigan,
Mississippi, Nebraska, Tennessee and Texas.
   ``We received our challenge from the mayor of Decatur,
Illinois,'' said Dot Montgomery, contest coordinator here. ``They
are challenging all the other Decaturs of America to see who can
raise the most cans of food based on percentage of population.''
   She said the Alabama community is to collect one can of food for
each of its 42,002 residents.
   The Decaturs are divided into three categories according to
population, with Decatur, Ill., the largest at 94,081 residents and
Decatur, Neb., the smallest at 723. A winner will be announced in
each category after the contest ends Aug. 3.
   In addition to helping feed the hungry, the contest's purpose is
to build community cohesiveness and civic pride, said Ann Lewellen,
public relations director of Decatur Advantage in Decatur, Ill.
   ``We wanted to call attention to the fact that unfortunately,
hunger does exist in America, and that we have to take a certain
amount of personal responsibility to do something about it,'' Ms.
Lewellen said.
   ``The local goal is to stock food banks and agencies who serve
the needy,'' she said.
   Ms. Lewellen said her community is beginning its campaign Friday
with a performance of the musical ``Can Can.'' Admission will
require a can of food in addition to a ticket.
   ``I thought it would be fun if we could do some type of sister
city project with the other Decaturs,'' Ms. Lewellen said. ``This
is a project which we can have a lot of fun with and at the same
time, do some good for our community.'
</TEXT>
