<1ST_LINE>u p AM-IdahoPrimary 2ndLd-Writethru a0861 05-24 0536</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Idaho Primary, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0861,500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Bush, Dukakis Win Low-Key Idaho Primary</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 2 grafs, Bush and Dukakis win, updated returns;
delegate count, picks up 4th graf pvs, bgng: With no</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BOB FICK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOISE, Idaho (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush, who already has
the Republican nomination virtually wrapped up, easily won Idaho's
Republican presidential primary on Tuesday, while Michael Dukakis
cruised to an overwhelming victory in the Democrats' nonbinding
vote.
   With 24 percent of the precincts reporting, Bush had 81 percent
of the vote to 10 percent for Pat Robertson, who is no longer an
active contender. Dukakis was pulling in 77 percent to 14 percent
for Jesse Jackson. Sens. Albert Gore Jr. and Paul Simon, both of
whom have suspended their Democratic presidential campaigns, were
getting 3 percent each.
   Bush was winning 15 of the 18 national convention delegates at
stake in the lackluster primary, with two going to Robertson and
one in the uncommitted column. The Democratic vote was purely a
``beauty contest'' exercise; front-runner Dukakis claimed a
majority of the delegates at caucuses two months ago.
   With no statewide elected offices at stake this year and the
presidential candidates all but formally crowned, there was little
to draw Idaho voters to the polls beyond a handful of heated
legislative and local races. Only about one in three registered
voters were expected to cast ballots.
   ``For various reasons, the presidential election and others,
neither we nor the county clerks are seeing very much intensity in
this one,'' Deputy Secretary of State Ben Ysursa said.
   On the Republican side, Robertson remained on the ballot as a
challenge to the vice president although he suspended his candidacy
earlier this month and returned to his Christian Broadcasting
Network.
   Bush made a 19-hour campaign swing through Idaho earlier this
month to bolster his support in a state that has not given its four
electoral votes to a Democrat since Lyndon Johnson in 1964.
   On the Democratic side, where no delegates were at stake, the
Massachusetts governor was expected to easily win the nonbinding
preference vote over Jackson.
   Democrats allotted 18 of their 24 nominating delegates in Super
Tuesday caucuses held on March 8. Dukakis captured eight of them,
Jackson four and six were uncommitted.
   Since then, however, Gov. Cecil Andrus, one of the six
previously uncommitted ``super delegates,'' has endorsed Dukakis
and urged others to do the same so the party is clearly unified for
the November assault on the White House.
   Although there has been no statewide polling conducted, a
Democratic poll this spring in the conservative 2nd Congressional
District of southern Idaho showed Dukakis only 2 percentage points
behind Bush.
   ``But it's a long time to the finish line,'' said state Senate
President Pro Tem James Risch of Boise, Bush's state chairman.
``The people will have a choice between a person who knows the
issues and a governor of a state that really hasn't done very
well.''
   Former Gov. John Evans, the state chairman for Dukakis, saw the
poll giving Bush 44 percent and Dukakis 42 percent as an indication
Democrats have a chance in Idaho this year.
   ``People are looking for a new leader,'' Evans said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
