<1ST_LINE>u a AM-DrugBoat 1stLd-Writethru a0855 05-24 0434</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drug Boat, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0855,0440</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>45 Tons Of Hashish And Marijuana Seized</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf to CORRECT by deleting Southeast. SUBS 5th graf
to CORRECT by deleting reference to Idaho, which was where Robinson
was acquitted, not where Lompoc prison is located.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto FX4</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CATALINA ORTIZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal agents arrested five men and seized
at least 30 tons of hashish and 15 tons of marijuana in one of the
biggest drug busts of its kind, authorities announced Tuesday.
   The Asian-grown drugs, with a wholesale value of $162 million,
were hidden in welded compartments of an oceangoing barge that was
seized late Monday as it entered San Francisco Bay. Agents also
seized the tug Intrepid Venture.
   ``This drug cargo was very carefully concealed in the barge by
obviously very experienced smugglers,'' said Assistant U.S.
Attorney Steve Graham, head of the Organied Crime Drug Enforcement
Task Force, a multi-agency organization that investigated the case.
   The five arrested were tug skipper, Calvin Robinson, 47; his son
William, 25, of Vacaville; his nephews Frank Robinson, 25, of
Corning and John Robinson, 23, of Santa Rosa; and his stepson,
Wesley Bastin, 25, of Corning, said Assistant U.S. Attorney Eric
Swenson.
   The elder Robinson had been acquitted of harboring a fugitive in
the 1980 prison escape of Christopher Boyce, the convicted spy who
was portrayed in the movie ``The Falcon and the Snowman.'' Robinson
was serving time on escape and counterfeiting charges in Lompoc
prison when he met Boyce.
   The Coast Guard's Pacific commander, Vice Admiral John Castello,
said the drug seizure was ``probably the biggest hashish-Thai
marijuana catch in the history of the United States.''
   The five were charged with large-scale drug smuggling and
conspiracy, punishable by at least 10 years in prison without the
possibility of parole and a possible $4 million fine.
   A bail hearing was set for Friday.
   The elder Robinson owned the tug and barge through his Napa
business, Dredge Master Associates, Swenson said.
   Rollin B. Klink, U.S. Customs Service special agent, said a
piece of ``minor'' information led to the seizure, but he refused
to elaborate. He said the organization behind the operation was
``huge'' and had been going on for a long time.
   The 70-foot tug left San Francisco Bay with the barge in tow in
early May, Graham said.Authorities believe the drugs had been
loaded onto the barge from a ``mother ship'' 1,000 miles offshore.
   The whereabouts of the mother ship remain unknown.
   The tug and barge were taken to Yerba Buena Island, where task
force investators began their search.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880524-0015 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-24-88 0037EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-FarmScene     05-24 0813</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Farm Scene,800</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Grain Sales to Soviets To Reach Three-Year High</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   This year's value of U.S. agriculture exports
to the Soviet Union is expected to climb 50 percent to a three-year
high of $1.4 billion, according to Agriculture Department
economists.
   ``Behind the gain will be much larger wheat shipments at higher
prices and much bigger soybean and soybean meal sales,'' the
department's Economic Research Service said Monday.
   Farm product sales to the Soviets exceeded $1.9 billion in 1985
but plummeted to a 13-year-low of $658 million in 1986 before
rebounding to $938 million in calendar 1987.
   A major factor has been large sales of U.S. wheat at subsidized
prices under the department's Export Enhancement Program.
   ``The U.S. value share of Soviet grain imports may be above 30
percent for the first time since 1984 and (may comprise) over 8
percent of total agricultural imports,'' the report said.
   Although total Soviet agricultural imports may increase 5
percent in 1988 from last year's estimated $16 billion, the value
will still be below the $19 billion average during the first half
of the 1980s.
   ``Grain imports now cost about $3 billion a year instead of $7
billion as in 1981-85,'' the report said. Despite a possible 20
percent rise in the per-ton cost of imported grain in 1988, this
``unit value'' will still be around one-third lower in the early
1980s.
   Kathryn Zeimetz, chief author of the report, said the forecast
of $1.4 billion this year is still far below the $2.9 billion in
the value of U.S. agricultural sales to the Soviets in 1984. The
standing record is $3 billion in 1979, she said.
   Earlier this month, the USDA forecast 1988 grain output at 215
million metric tons, up 2 percent from last year. It also would be
the third consecutive harvest of more than 200 million tons, a
historic first for the Soviet Union.
   ``Crops are off to a much better start than in 1987 following a
good fall sowing, overwintering and spring planting conditions,''
Monday's analysis said. ``Barring unusually severe weather through
the spring and fall, 1988 crop output should increase.''
   Greater output and improved productivity in agriculture are
prerequisites for improvement in the Soviet economy.
   ``The agro-industrial complex accounts for more than 30 percent
of the gross social product, 70 percent of the retail trade sales
and one-third of the productive capital and work force,'' the
report said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A proposed change in Agriculture Department
regulations would hold farmers and others in the marketing chain
financially accountable for livestock carcasses condemned at
slaughter plants because of illegally high traces of drugs.
   B.H. ``Bill'' Jones, administrator of the department's Packers
and Stockyards Administration, said Monday the proposal is intended
to deter the sale of medicated animals for slaughter and shift
economic responsibility for illegal drug residues from the meat
packer to those who cause the violation.
   Under the proposal, a meat packer would be able to ``bill back''
the person from whom the livestock was bought if it is condemned
because of illegal drug residues.
   In order to make the plan work, Jones said, each purchaser or
selling agency in the marketing chain would be permitted to use the
bill-back procedure. If a seller failed to settle up, the buyer or
selling agency would be permitted to deduct from a subsequent
purchase from the same person.
   Jones said that although a small percentage of livestock
producers are selling medicated animals for slaughter, the
illegally high drug residues continue to be a problem, notably in
swine, culled dairy cows and young calves.
   The proposal will be open 60 days for public comment. Those can
be sent to: Packers and Stockyards Administration, Room 3039-S,
USDA, Washington, D.C. 20250.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An additional 3,375,367 acres of highly
erodible cropland will be taken from production under the
Agriculture Department's 10-year Conservation Reserve Program.
   Milton Hertz, administrator of the department's Agricultural
Stabilization and Conservation Program, said Monday the acreage was
accepted from offers, or bids, during the program's sixth signup
held Feb. 1-19. A total of about 4.5 million acres was offered
during the signup.
   In all, counting the earlier signups, more than 25.5 million
acres have been accepted into the program, he said. Another signup
will be held July 18 through Aug. 5.
   Congress in the 1985 farm law set a goal of 40 million to 45
million acres for the program by 1990.
   Under the program, farmers agree to take land from production
for 10 years. In return, based on bids they submit, they get annual
rental payments from the government and one-time assistance pay for
half the cost of planting grass, trees and shrubs to guard against
erosion.
   Hertz said the bids accepted from the latest signup averaged
$47.90 per acre annually, compared with $48.45 for the first five
signups.
</TEXT>
