<HEAD>Zimbabwe Lifts Price Freeze</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HARARE, Zimbabwe (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Robert Mugabe's socialist
government lifted a yearold freeze on prices in a bid to boost the
ailing economy.
   The announcement was made in a special edition of the government
gazette.
   The move means that manufacturers, retailers, utilities and
landowners will be able to immediately raise prices, fees and
commercial rents by 5 percent. Private rents remain under state
control.
   The freeze was lifted three months after the government
suspended controls over wage increases, allowing minimum pay checks
to be boosted by 15 percent.
   Curbs on wage and price increases were imposed a year ago to
check inflation, then running at about 20 percent.
</TEXT>
