<1ST_LINE>u a AM-PatrolmanShot     05-24 0275</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Patrolman Shot,0283</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Patrolman Kills Motorist in Gunfight During Traffic Stop</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELT, Mont. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A state Highway Patrol officer responding to
a report of a possible drunk driver shot a motorist to death
Tuesday after the man opened fire with a pistol at point-blank
range, authorities said.
   The motorist stopped by officer Ronald T. Kunkel raised a pistol
and fired without warning as the patrolman reached into the man's
window to switch off the ignition, said patrol spokesman Sgt. Randy
Yaeger of Helena.
   ``(Kunkel) just walked up and `boom,''' Yaeger said.
   Kunkel, wounded in the left shoulder, drew his .38-caliber
revolver and apparently fired six shots as he fell away from the
van, and at least one bullet hit the motorist in the head, Yaeger
said.
   Officers said they found Kunkel's blood-stained hat in the
motorist's lap. The shooting occurred about 3:45 p.m., and Kunkel,
who was alone on patrol, radioed for help after he was wounded,
Yaeger said.
   Kunkel, 37, of Belt, was listed in fair condition at Columbus
Hospital in Great Falls.
   The dead motorist's identity ``isn't available at this time,''
Yaeger said. His van had license plates from Cascade County, the
Great Falls area.
   Yaeger said the man was described as elderly, with white hair
and a beard.
   Kunkel stopped the van for erratic driving just east of Belt on
U.S. 87 near Armington Junction, about 25 miles east of Great
Falls, Yaeger said. Officers on the scene said Kunkel had received
a report of a possible drunk driver.
   Yaeger said the motorist didn't pull to the side of the road,
but stopped in the middle of the westbound lane.
</TEXT>
