<HEAD>Town Mourns At Funeral of Slain Boy, School Service</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 4 grafs after 3rd graf, `The youngster ..., to UPDATE
with ex-husband's quotes; picks up 4th graf: `Children, teachers
...</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos CX5,6</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES LITKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WINNETKA, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Family and friends Monday buried an
8-year-old boy shot to death during a deranged woman's rampage,
struggling to make sense of a death so tragic that ``we know that
God is weeping,'' a rabbi said.
   On a brooding, gray day that mirrored the community's grief,
more than 1,000 mourners _ dozens of them children in brightly
colored slickers _ crowded a synagogue for a funeral service for
Nicholas Corwin.
   The youngster was fatally wounded Friday when Laurie Dann
stormed the Hubbard Woods Elementary School and fired on a
second-grade classroom. Five students and a man who lived at a
nearby house were wounded during Ms. Dann's spree of violence,
which ended when the 30-year-old woman shot herself to death.
   In a broadcast interview Monday night, her ex-husband Russell
Dann said her rampage might have been prevented.
   ``I hired attorneys. I hired private detectives. ... This was
the North Shore of Chicago reaching out for help, not just Russell
Dann ... I'm not saying we got no help, but Friday happened,'' Dann
said on ABC's ``Nightline.''
   He also said that ``on many occasions, we tried to get her
arrested,'' but police did not pursue her case actively enough.
   ``Nightline'' host Ted Koppel said Dann volunteered to appear on
the program in the hope that he could prevent the repeat of a
tragedy like the school shootings.
   Children, teachers, counselors and other parents gathered at the
school later Monday for a memorial service.
   ``I think the adults will have a harder time letting go than our
kids. They're much more resilient that way,'' said LaDonna Covelle,
whose second-grade son, Mark, and third-grade daughter, Jennifer,
attend the school.
   ``We left the funeral service this morning and ... Mark said, `I
can't wait until it's normal again.'''
   Classes were canceled at the school Monday and a half-dozen
police officers were outside.
   ``We're running a tightrope between an attempt to keep things
normal and secure,'' Superintendent Donald Monroe said. ``We
shouldn't tell schools across America to lock their doors to the
neighborhoods around them,'' Monroe said.
   ``So deep is our sorrow, so great is our loss, that we know that
God is weeping,'' said Rabbi Robert Schreibman during Nicholas'
funeral service at Temple Jeremiah in nearby Northfield.
   ``The death of the young is always tragic, but this was so
sudden, so swift _ it was such an unexpected loss of a wonderful
and promising child with so much to give,'' Schreibman said.
   Nicholas was buried at Memorial Park Cemetery in nearby Skokie.
   ``Nicky was extremely well-liked _ loved. He seemed to be the
leader,'' said Amy Moses, 29, the substitute teacher who was in the
classroom when the shooting occurred and tried unsuccesfully to
disarm Ms. Dann.
   She said children asked her who would serve as the rules expert
for playground games with Nicky gone, ``who was going to break the
records, who was going to score the goals?''
   The students and faculty plan to give Nicholas' parents a book
of remembrances about the boy titled, ``Gifts Nick Gave Us,''
Monroe said after the school memorial.
   Three of the five children wounded in Friday's attack were in
fair condition at Evanston Hospital on Monday, while 8-year-old
Lindsay Fisher remained in critical condition, said Dr. John C.
Alexander Jr., chief of heart and chest surgery at the hospital.
   The two other victims were listed in fair condition Monday at
Highland Park Hospital, said hospital spokesman Chuck Block.
   Before the shooting, Ms. Dann delivered tainted treats to two
college fraternities and several homes where she had worked as a
babysitter. Police said no one was seriously injured by the
poisoned fruit juice and cereal treats.
   After the poisonings, discovered Saturday, ``we're just keeping
our fingers crossed that it is over,'' said Winnetka Police Chief
Herbert Timm on CBS ``This Morning.''
   Later Monday, Timm said a task force had been formed by area
police departments in an effort to ``put Laurie Dann and this
situation to rest.'' He said authorities had ``a few other leads to
pursue'' but wouldn't be more specific.''
   Gov. James R. Thompson on Monday called for tightened
handgun-control laws, although he noted the general public ``is
never going to be protected against random, bizarre behavior.''
   On Friday morning, Ms. Dann set a small fire at the house of a
family she babysat for who had told her they were moving away and
gave tainted milk to two of the children.
   The daughter of a wealthy suburban family and a former student
at the University of Arizona in Tucson, Ms. Dann was due to stand
trial in Madison, Wis., on charges of shoplifting several women's
wigs March 14.
   She also was being investigated by federal authorities for
making threatening telephone calls in three states to former
friends and members of her ex-husband's family.
</TEXT>
