<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Writer Honored,0183</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Aspiring Writer Receives Prestigious Prize</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHESTERTOWN, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dean O. Hebert, who remembers being
called an ``oyster'' by high school classmates taunting him for his
love of writing, has been awarded the Sophie Kerr Prize.
   The prize, which this year is worth $27,836, is awarded annually
to a graduating senior from Washington College who displays
``ability and promise for future fulfillment in the field of
literary endeavor.''
   It was established 20 years ago after the death of novelist,
serial writer and Eastern Shore resident Sophie Kerr, who left a
trust fund and stipulated that half the interest be awarded to a
promising young writer.
   Hebert was awarded the prize Sunday after a panel of literature
teachers praised an unpublished novel he began three years ago.
   Hebert's first book is a two-part futuristic novel in which the
main character tries to find order in a turbulent world.
   ``This makes me feel very good,'' the 20-year-old Hebert said.
``It just makes me feel like I'm going to be a writer some day. Or
even maybe today.''
</TEXT>
