<2ND_LINE>PM-Summit-People,740</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>All Washington Officialdom Wants a Piece of Summit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Even for veterans of White House bureaucratic
battles, the competition to go to Moscow for next week's historic
U.S.-Soviet summit is intense.
   ``Is there a lot of interest in the trip? The answer is yes,''
said Thomas C. Griscom, the assistant to the president for
communications and planning. Griscom and Colin L. Powell, Reagan's
national security adviser, chair a summit planning group.
   Besides interest, there are hurt feelings from the State
Department in Foggy Bottom to the White House at 1600 Pennsylvania
Avenue over who's going to the summit and who's not, officials say.
   ``We really need to restrict the numbers and you have to start
at home so you have to make cuts within your own operation,''
Griscom said. Among the casualties: Karen Fuller, Griscom's
executive assistant.
   Even so, 800 people _ from arms control negotiators to White
House stewards _ will be part of the president's entourage, Griscom
said. That number includes 275 members of the White House press
corps. The four television networks, ABC, CBS, NBC and Cable News
Network, also are expected to each have as many as 150 people
flying in separately to the Soviet Union.
   With the president's eight-year term nearing an end, the May
29-June 2 summit is one of the last _ and possibly the most
spectacular _ overseas extravaganzas to be staged by the Reagan
White House.
   The Moscow leg of the trip, the first visit by a U.S. president
to the Soviet Union in 14 years, is preceded by three days in
Helsinki, Finland, and followed by a stop in London.
   Reagan and his wife, Nancy, will be joined by key members of the
Cabinet, including Secretary of State George P. Shultz and Defense
Secretary Frank C. Carlucci. Also joining the traveling party are
White House chief of staff Howard Baker and U.S. Information Agency
Director Charles Z. Wick. Besides Mrs. Reagan, Mrs. Shultz is the
only wife traveling with her husband.
   Rozanne L. Ridgway, the assistant secretary of state for
European and Canadian affairs who has participated in many
negotiations with the Soviets, will play a key role in the summit,
as will members of the Arms Control and Disarmament Agency.
   ``It's a wonderful finale,'' said Ambassador Selwa Roosevelt,
the chief of protocol. ``I can't think of a more appropriate way to
come to the concluding months of the president's term.''
   Mrs. Roosevelt's office is helping Linda Faulkner, the White
House social secretary, prepare for the ``enormous project'' in
Moscow, which includes a dinner party the Reagans will host for the
Gorbachevs at Spaso House, the ambassador's residence in Moscow.
American food and California wines will be flown in for the
evening, with entertainment by jazz pianist Dave Brubeck.
   Among the other events: Reagan's visit to historic Danilov
monastery; one meeting with dissidents and another with Soviet
writers and artists; a speech at Moscow University; a state dinner
hosted by the Gorbachevs in the Hall of Facets at the Kremlin; Mrs.
Reagan's trip to Leningrad; and a performance at the Bolshoi
Theater.
   Primarily because of security, the number of Americans attending
the summit is larger than normally would attend a meeting such as
the annual economic summit, which is being held June 19-21 in
Toronto, Canada.
   ``When you are having a meeting in Moscow, you really have to
take extraordinary security precautions, precautions you would
ordinarily not have to take in Tokyo or London,'' said Robert E.
Lamb, the assistant secretary of state for diplomatic security.
   But the State Department's budget cuts mean the agency may send
fewer people to Moscow than it did to Reagan's first superpower
summit in Geneva in November 1985, said one official, speaking on
condition of anonymity.
   Diplomats and White House aides will be joined in Moscow by
engineers, technicians, guards, cooks, stewards and support staff.
   The U.S. Embassy in Moscow differs from most embassies, where
foreign nationals cook, clean, answer telephones, make repairs and
run errands for the diplomats and their families. In October 1986,
260 Soviets were removed from the embassy as part of a series of
diplomatic expulsions between Washington and Moscow.
   To compensate for the short-staffing in Moscow, the U.S.
government will send people to help out at the embassy and at Spaso
House. Lamb's staff has sent technicians to assure secure rooms
inside the embassy, as well as additional American guards to keep a
24-hour-a-day watch on the facilities, he said.
</TEXT>
