<2ND_LINE>PM-People-Hamilton,0222</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>George Hamilton Says Sunning Recharges His Battery</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Despite lampoons in ``Doonesbury,'' actor George
Hamilton says he lives to tan.
   ``For me it's direct energy. It's like plugging my battery in.
It isn't just the actual feeling I get,'' the tawny actor said in
June's Vogue magazine.
   And he doesn't worry about the damage it may cause, either.
   ``If anybody should be a piece of parchment, it's me. My skin,
though, is as smooth as anybody's who hasn't been in the sun,''
said Hamilton, whose sunning passion provides Garry Trudeau's
``Doonesbury'' comic strip with plenty of fodder. One of Trudeau's
characters regularly attends ``The George Hamilton Cocoa Butter
Open.''
   The actor recalls a time in London when he was staying at the
Grosvenor House Hotel, and the weather was typically English.
   ``All of a sudden the sun came out,'' Hamilton said. ``And it
was hitting a spot on the wall outside my room. So I climbed out
onto the ledge and positioned myself for maybe half an hour to get
some sun.''
   A crowd quickly gathered and one woman began shouting, ``Look at
'im. 'E's gonna jump,'' Hamilton said. ``Soon there were 20 people
gathered below thinking I'm trying to commit suicide.
   ``All I wanted was a little sun.''
</TEXT>
