<FILEID>AP-NR-05-24-88 0243EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-RailSafety     05-24 0491</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Rail Safety,470</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senate Gets Bill Expanding Government Rail Safety Powers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The first national standards on who can
operate a train, and other steps strengthening the government's
hand for dealing with railroad accidents, are awaiting final
congressional approval.
   The House approved the legislation by voice vote Monday and sent
it to the Senate, where approval is expected this week.
   The measure is an outgrowth of the Jan. 4, 1987, collision of an
Amtrak passenger train with three connected Conrail locomotives in
Chase, Md. The crash killed 16 people and injured 175 others. Two
of the Conrail crewmen admitted later that they had been smoking
marijuana in the cab.
   The legislation does not include a requirement for the mandatory
random testing of railroad workers, which is strongly opposed by
rail unions. That language is part of another bill that is mired
down by differences between the House and Senate.
   It does order the Transportation Department to set up a national
system for licensing train engineers, give the government the power
to penalize individual workers _ not just railroad companies _ for
safety violations, and increase the federal fines that can be
imposed.
   The bill's passage brought mixed reactions from railroad and
labor union officials.
   William H. Dempsey, president of the Association of American
Railroads, praised parts of the measure, but said it also should
have required mandatory random drug testing of railroad workers.
   ``It cannot be said that the ... bill adequately addresses the
issue of rail safety'' without that language, Dempsey said in a
written statement.
   James Kennedy, executive secretary-treasurer of the Railway
Labor Executives Association, said parts of the bill were good, but
added that it should have raised fines further and offered more
protections for employees who report workplace problems.
   ``It certainly doesn't go far enough,'' said Kennedy, whose
organization represents 300,000 railroad workers.
   Under the licensing program, applicants' automobile driving
licenses would be examined for drug and alcohol convictions. An
individual whose record shows such convictions could receive an
engineer's license only if he or she had completed an approved
rehabilitation program.
   The bill also requires the Transportation Department to issue
rules forbidding the disabling of safety devices, a practice that
is not now illegal.
   Instruments to record a train's operating data, similar to
``black boxes'' in aircraft, would be required within three years.
And automatic braking devices, common on Amtrak trains but missing
on many freight trains, would be required in the busy Northeast
Corridor.
   The maximum civil fine imposed for safety violations would be
increased from $2,500 to $20,000 for grossly negligent breaches of
the law.
   ``This legislation takes a significant new stride in enhancing
safety,'' said John Dingell, D-Mich., chairman of the House Energy
and Commerce Committee, which originated the bill.
   The House and Senate each had approved earlier versions of the
legislation. Negotiators from the two chambers agreed last Thursday
to the compromise bill.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
