<1ST_LINE>r a PM-HellsAngels     05-24 0454</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hells Angels,0465</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Informant Was `Coke' User; Mistrial Declared</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB EGELKO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government's nationwide case against
members of the Hells Angels could be jeopardized by a mistrial
declared in one case after a disclosure that the chief informant
lied about his history of cocaine use.
   Informant Anthony Tait had testified that he took cocaine twice
in his life and also used marijuana but stopped because ``they made
me violently ill.''
   U.S. District Judge Robert Schnacke on Monday declared a
mistrial in the case of Michael Lessard, 39, a member of the
motorcycle gang's Oakland chapter, after learning Tait admitted to
the FBI in 1985 that he had been a regular cocaine user.
   Lessard is charged with four counts of illegally possessing
explosives.
   ``It's going to show that Tait's not to be trusted,'' said
defense attorney Richard Hove. ``He's capable of lying at any time.
   ``It also demonstrates that the government has let him go ahead
and lie till somebody's conscience decided that they had to say
something about it.'' Assistant U.S. Attorney John Stephen Graham
said the disclosure about Tait wouldn't have any significant effect
on the government's case. Graham heads the Drug Enforcement Task
Force that is coordinating the Hells Angels prosecutions.
   Defense lawyers ``have been doing everything they can in all of
the trials up to this point to put Tait himself on trial, to divert
attention from the fact that somebody else actually is charged with
a crime,'' Graham said.
   Tait worked for three years as an undercover informant in the
Hells Angels. He has received $63,000 in fees from the government
and is the chief witness against all 41 of the gang members who
were charged last November with drugs or weapons violations.
Several members already have been convicted.
   The defendants include Ralph ``Sonny'' Barger, founder of the
Oakland chapter, who is awaiting trial in Kentucky in the
explosives conspiracy case.
   Lessard faces a trial in Kentucky on charges that he gave
explosives to Tait, who testified they were to be used to kill
members of a rival gang, the Outlaws.
   After Tait's testimony about his drug use, Graham sent a letter
to defense lawyers, describing Tait's February 1985 interview with
FBI agent Peter Flanagan in Alaska, where Tait had infiltrated a
Hells Angels chapter. Graham realized he was required to disclose
evidence that could be useful in their cases, he said.
   In the letter, Graham quoted Flanagan as saying Tait ``advised
that although his current narcotics use is limited to marijuana ...
he did previously have a problem with cocaine use up until 1980.''
Tait said he managed to ``completely kick the cocaine habit,'' the
letter quoted Flanagan as saying.
</TEXT>
