<FILEID>AP-NR-05-24-88 0254EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Panama     05-24 0725</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Panama,0750</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bid To Compel Noriega To Appear In Congress Fails</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Legislators of the governing
coalition tried without success to compel Gen. Manuel Antonio
Noriega to appear in congress to report on talks with the United
States.
   Twenty-seven legislators voted for the motion Monday. Eight
voted against it and 12 abstained. Forty-seven of the body's 67
members were on hand for the session of the Legislative Assembly,
as the unicameral legislature is called.
   The congress is empowered to call before it any official, but
such a measure must be approved by two-thirds of those present.
   Had it been passed, the motion would have compelled Noriega, who
is commander of the 15,000-member Defense Forces and de facto ruler
of Panama, to appear before the lawmakers to respond to specific
questions.
   Among the questions included in the resolution as proposed by
Luis Gomez, a lawmaker of the Revolutionary Democratic Party, or
PRD, were:
   ``What has been proposed by the North American negotiators?
   ``What has been proposed by the Panamanian negotiators?
   ``Why is the United States participating in these negotiations
when it persists in not recognizing the legitimate government of
Panama?
   ``What is the basic objective pursued by the Panamanian
negotiators, and what relation does it have with the national task
of recovering our complete sovereignty and control of the (Panama)
Canal in the year 2000?
   ``How has the fact that you have been formally accused of
participating in drug smuggling to the United States affected your
decision to carry out these negotiations? Has the United States
offered to lift these indictments? In exchange for what concessions
from you?''
   A coalition called the National Democratic Union ostensibly
governs Panama. It comprises the pro-military Revolutionary
Democratic Party, the Republican Party and the Labor Party.
   Eight other legislators representing the Revolutionary
Democratic Party, the Laborites and the Republicans were
co-sponsors of Gomez's resolution.
   Most abstentions and votes against the resolution came from
members of the opposition _ Christian Democrats and members of the
Authentic Panamenist Party.
   Representatives of Noriega have been involved for most of May in
talks with Reagan administration envoy Michael Kozak in an effort
to resolve the crisis in U.S.-Panamanian relatins. Washington
insists that the general, who was indicted in Florida in February
on federal drug-smuggling and money-laundering charges, resign his
post and leave the country, at least temporarily.
   Neither Noriega nor his associates have spelled out his position
explicitly. But the general has said repeatedly there can be no
solution as long as what he calls U.S. aggression against Panama
continues.
   He says sanctions imposed by the Reagan administration
constitute economic aggression. Noriega contends that the
deployment of nearly 2,000 soldiers in recent months to reinforce
the 10,000 already stationed in U.S. military institutions along
the canal constitutes psychological aggression.
   He also has demanded that Washington ``respect'' the government
of President Manuel Solis Palma. Solis replaced Eric Delvalle, who
was removed from the presidency by the National Assembly on Feb. 26
after trying to fire Noriega. Washington continues to recognize
Delvalle, who remains in hiding in Panama, as the country's
president.
   Asked by The Associated Press 10 days ago if he was considering
retiring in August _ which has been suggested as a feasible date
for stepping down _ Noriega said the date of his retirement is none
of Washington's business.
   His spokesman Maj. Edgardo Lopez said Noriega could continue as
commander for ``several more years.''
   Noriega denies the drug charges, contending they are politically
motivated.
   He says Washington intends to replace him with a less
nationalistic leader who would consent to a strong U.S. military
presence in Panama well into the next century.
   The 1977 Panama Canal Treaty between the United States and
Panama obliges Washington to hand over to Panama complete control
of the waterway and U.S. military installations by midday Dec. 31,
1999.
   Kozak returned to Panama on Monday following a weekend meeting
with Reagan and the president's top Cabinet members and advisers.
   Neither the U.S. Embassy nor Panamanian officials would comment
on what meetings the envoy has planned in coming days.
   Precisely what the U.S. is offering Noriega has not been
disclosed, though reports from Washington have indicated the
president is inclined to authorize dismissal of the indictments
against Noriega if that would entice him to give up power.
</TEXT>
