<FILEID>AP-NR-05-24-88 0300EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-HasenfusSuit     05-24 0629</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hasenfus Suit,610</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>State Department Stopped Defense Fund for Hasenfus, Attorney Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department persuaded the wife of
Eugene Hasenfus not to form a defense fund following her husband's
capture in Nicaragua when a U.S. plane carrying arms for the
Contras was shot down, an attorney says.
   The accusation that Assistant Secretary of State Elliott Abrams
and another State Department official interceded within days of the
Oct. 5, 1986, crash of a C-123 transport plane was made by an
attorney representing the Hasenfuses in a civil suit filed Monday
in federal court.
   Los Angeles attorney Brian R. Strange said Abrams and William P.
Schofield telephoned Sally Hasenfus to tell her the operators of
the private resupply network would pay for her husband's legal
expenses following his capture by the Sandinista government.
   Tape recordings that Mrs. Hasenfus made of the telephone
conversations provide ``undisputable evidence of these
representations,'' Strange said in a telephone interview after the
lawsuit was filed.
   State Department spokeswoman Ellen Bork said she could not
comment on the assertion because the case is in litigation.
   The lawsuit originally was filed last fall in California state
court. That action was dismissed hours before the new case was
brought in U.S. District Court in Washington, Strange said.
   The breach-of-contract suit against Southern Air Transport,
Corporate Air Services and arms dealers Albert Hakim and Richard V.
Secord charges that Hasenfus' employers broke their promises to pay
his legal expenses after his capture in Nicaragua.
   Hakim and Secord, defendants in the Iran-Contra arms and money
conspiracy case along with fired National Security Council aide
Oliver L. North and former national security adviser John M.
Poindexter, ran the secret Contra resupply network during a time
when American military aid to the rebels was banned by law.
   Southern Air, once a CIA proprietary company, provided planes
for ferrying arms to the Nicaraguan rebels during the aid cutoff.
   The lawsuit charges that Corporate Air Services, which hired
Hasenfus as a cargo handler in July 1986, was a front created for
the operation by Southern Air.
   Abrams testified before Congress after the crash that there was
no U.S. involvement in the plane, which was carrying rifles,
ammunition and grenade launchers to the Contras.
   Later, Abrams was forced to admit he was ``completely wrong'' in
making this assertion.
   The suit alleges that U.S. officials were told by operators of
the covert arms supply network that they would pay for Hasenfus's
legal expenses following his capture.
   These officials, who were not specifically identified in the
complaint but were alleged by Strange to be Abrams and Schofield,
in turn urged Mrs. Hasenfus and her friends not to publicly solicit
funds for her husband's legal defense in Nicaragua, where he was
charged with terrorism.
   Mrs. Hasenfus relied on the promises relayed by Abrams and
Schofield that her husband's legal bills would be paid by his
employers, the lawsuit said. But those bills were never paid, the
lawsuit contends, forcing the Hasenfus family to deplete their
life's savings.
   ``Sally and Eugene face financial ruin, including potential
foreclosure of their home and possible forced sale of their
assets,'' the lawsuit said.
   Strange said Schofield, who was assigned to the Nicaragua desk
in 1986, telephoned Mrs. Hasenfus several times within days of the
crash and that Abrams made one call himself.
   ``They told Sally Hasenfus they were in contact with Gene's
employers and that everything would be taken care of,'' Strange
said. ``They induced them not to go forward with a fund that was
being raised.''
   Hasenfus, of Marinette, Wis., was tried and convicted and
received a 30-year prison sentence. But on Dec. 17, 1986, he was
pardoned by Nicaraguan President Daniel Ortega and allowed to
return to the United States.
</TEXT>
