<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Dukakis-Organizer     05-24 0590</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dukakis-Organizer,580</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Veteran of Farm Workers Union Organizes Western States for Dukakis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Richard Yberra, heading Michael Dukakis'
presidential campaign in the West, says he is taking a page from
the farm workers' struggles of the 1960s and '70s as he organizes
California for the Democratic front-runner.
   The highest-ranking Hispanic in the Dukakis campaign, Yberra is
a veteran of the United Farm Workers union and its boycott
campaigns. He is son-in-law of the union's longtime leader, Cesar
Chavez, and his former aide.
   Yberra directed Dukakis' campaign in seven other Western states
earlier this year where Dukakis won.
   In California he is concentrating on building an organization
both to counter Jesse Jackson's plans to outspend Dukakis on
television ads, and to lay the groundwork for the fall campaign
against Republican George Bush.
   ``For many years the conventional wisdom has said California is
too large to have a grassroots political organization,'' and that
only big spending on TV is effective, Yberra said.
   ``Campaigns often just come in here to raise money,'' he said.
``You have to go back to the Bobby Kennedy campaign and George
McGovern campaign of '68 and '72, to where the farm workers union
had a lot of involvement and turned out numbers of people in
certain areas of the state to contribute significantly to those two
victories.''
   ``Years later, there are a number of Democratic activists who
came out of that period and experience ... and who take the same
things we used, the same methods we used in the successful
boycotts, into other areas.''
   California state Democratic Chairman Peter Kelly, a Los Angeles
attorney, said the United Farm Workers has produced Democratic
strategists and organizers for several successful recent campaigns.
   ``They ran all those boycott campaigns, and that transferred
them into politics,'' Kelley said.
   Like many in the Dukakis campaign, Yberra met the Massachusetts
governor while a student at Harvard's Kennedy School of Government,
where Dukakis taught after losing re-election in 1978.
   Yberra, 39, whose name is pronounced E-bear-a, was from San
Diego and had left college without graduating to volunteer with the
farm workers. He was recruited to attend the Kennedy school and
earned a masters degree in public administration.
   ``I was one of those rare ones at the Kennedy School who comes
from where I came from,'' he said. ``I had Dukakis as my professor
for three courses, and sat in on another. I had him for almost half
what I did there. I was that impressed with him.''
   He had been Chavez's administrative assistant for three years in
the early 1970s, when he married Chavez's daughter, Anna, and later
held jobs in the administration of California Gov. Jerry Brown. He
worked in Brown's 1980 presidential campaign, and for Sen. Edward
Kennedy, D-Mass., after Brown quit the race.
   Dukakis relied on organizational strength in several Western
states where he defeated Jackson and other rivals, including some
where he did not campaign.
   Dukakis won Arizona without a visit there, and won Colorado's
caucuses after a visit of only a few hours, while Jackson spent two
days and drew massive crowds everywhere he went.
   ``We had supporters calling us, worried,'' Yberra said,
recalling the days Jackson drew throngs in Colorado. ``We'd say no,
just keep down the line, do the program, stay consistent. We're
going to be OK.''
   As it turned out, he said, on caucus day Dukakis' count proved
more accurate than the state party's early projections. ``That's
how good our organization was,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
