<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Lites     05-24 0528</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lites,0554</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>On the Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LINCOLN, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If Menda McKenzie was waiting for a sign to
decide whether to marry Bruce Lear, she got one.
   Roses in hand, Bruce ``B.T.'' Lear showed up at Miss McKenzie's
office and asked her to come outside.
   In front of the building, a mobile red and white sign asked:
``Menda McKenzie will you marry me! B.T.''
   ``I didn't even answer. I just laughed,'' Miss McKenzie said of
Friday's proposal. ``Someone from the third floor yelled, `What did
you say?' And I said `Yes.'''
   Miss McKenzie, a part-time nutrition aide, and Lear are seniors
at the University of Nebraska-Lincoln.
   ``I was really nervous,'' Lear said. ``You spend your whole life
feeling kind of young _ it's always the other people getting
engaged. There's a seriousness to that kind of commitment. We're
both serious about it.''
   However, he said, he didn't want a traditional proposal.
   ``I wanted to do something kind of fun, but not tasteless,'' he
said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Horns blasted and a sign unfurled for an
8-year-old New Jersey boy who had never been to New York before _
and who turned out to be the 40 millionth passenger on the Circle
Line boats that circumnavigate Manhattan.
   ``I felt great because I never won anything,'' said Mark Bodal,
a third-grader on a school outing from South River, N.J.
   The boy was the 40 millionth passenger since the Circle Line
sightseeing boats first weighed anchor in 1945, according to
executive vice president Beverly Meyer.
   As Mark approached the boat Circle Line XII on Monday, a banner
opened noting the 40 millionth passenger, ``the horns went off and
the bells rang and he was very, very excited,'' said spokesman
Richard Basini.
   Mark got to ring the excursion boat's bell, spin the wheel and
bask in the media limelight.
   What did he like most?
   ``The free stuff,'' especially a silver apple from Tiffany's, he
said. Mark also won a lifetime pass on the Circle Line.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW BEDFORD, Mass.(AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States has avenged three
straight losses to Canada to finally triumph in the international
scallop shucking contest.
   In becoming the first U.S. shucker to win, Jimmy Jardin of New
Bedford beat two Canadians who had won in the last three years.
   Jardin scored 184.25 points, while another U.S. contestant, Mark
Picanso, came in second with 183.25 points in Sunday's fifth annual
competition.
   The four men donned long rubber aprons and gloves and warmed up
by shucking a practice round of 25 scallops. Then 200 scallops were
carefully counted out, and hands began flying.
   A team of Canadian and U.S. judges inspected the scallop meats,
and deducted points for nicks and sloppy cuts.
   ``I'm a natural,'' Jardin said before the competition, held at
the State Pier as part of the International Commercial Fisheries
show. ``I've only been fishing for a year and a half.''
   Jardin said he and Picanso develop their talents by competing
daily as crewmates aboard the fishing vessel Raider. Picanso beat
Jardin on Friday at a U.S. shucking competition.
   ``We work side by side, and we drive each other all day long,''
Jardin said.
</TEXT>
