<1ST_LINE>r a PM-TMIFall     05-24 0190</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-TMI Fall,0195</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Worker Falls Into Reactor Water</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIDDLETOWN, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A member of the crew pulling damaged fuel
and debris from the Three Mile Island Unit 2 nuclear plant fell
part way into radioactive water covering the reactor, a spokesman
says.
   The 30-year-old worker, whose name was not given, caught
himself, and only his legs below the knees went into the water
Monday, said Doug Bedell, spokesman for GPU Nuclear Corp., which
manages the plant.
   The worker, who was wearing protective clothing, suffered only
minor bruises and received a radiation exposure to the skin of less
than several hundred millirems, Bedell said. The federal limit for
skin exposure to a workers' legs is 18,250 millirems every three
months.
   The worker was decontaminated at the plant, and the Nuclear
Regulatory Commission was notified, Bedell said.
   It was the first time someone fell into the reactor pool since
the cleanup began 2{ years ago, he said.
   Unit 2 was damaged in 1979 in the nation's worst commercial
nuclear accident, when some of the fuel melted after a loss of
reactor coolant. Two-thirds of the damaged fuel has been removed.
</TEXT>
