<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Jackson     05-24 0448</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Jackson,410</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Says Dukakis Fund to Rebuild America Is Inadequate</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUG WILLIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson was turning his
attention today to foreign affairs, a day after touting a new
budget plan and criticizing the economic policies of his rival,
Democratic front-runner Michael Dukakis.
   Jackson on Monday proposed a five-year, $344 billion package of
new health, education and housing programs financed by raising
taxes on corporations and the rich and a freeze on military
spending.
   Jackson released his 18-page spending plan _ the most detailed
budget proposal by any of the presidential candidates remaining in
the race _ at a news conference Monday at the state Capitol in
Sacramento. He was in California campaigning in advance of the June
7 primary.
   Also Monday, Jackson toured a Head Start center in a low-income
neighborhood near the California Capitol and faced a hostile crowd
of nuclear plant workers at a rally planned by anti-nuclear
activists outside of Sacramento's Rancho Seco nuclear plant.
   The Democratic presidential candidate was playing up foreign
policy today, addressing the World Affairs Council of Los Angeles.
He also scheduled a stop at the South African consulate to
underline his anti-apartheid message.
   Jackson used his budget news conference to contrast his agenda
for the nation with both Dukakis and Vice President George Bush,
the Republican nominee-to-be.
   He said Bush would continue the policies of President Reagan and
Dukakis offers only timid adjustments.
   ``Reagan has cut investment in health care, housing, legal
services, day care, scholarships by more than $100 billion. Mr.
Dukakis rails against that as being wrong, but offers to offset it
by only $775 million,'' Jackson said. ``That is radically
conservative, away from the dreams and aspirations of most
Democrats.''
   Dukakis, campaigning in New Jersey Monday night, took exception
to that assessment.
   ``It does represent a fundamental change over what we've had the
past four years,'' the Massachusetts governor said of his own
economic plan, which he has outlined in more general terms than
Jackson's.
   Dukakis also suggested Jackson might be naive for trying to set
down spending figures so far in advance.
   ``There's no way you can prepare a budget today for 1989,'' he
said.
   At a rally outside the Rancho Seco nuclear power plant near
Sacramento, Jackson told plant workers nuclear power is ``a
dangerous job option.''
   A Sacramento-area voter referendum seeks to shut down the plant.
   ``We have oil reserves. We have coal reserves. We have solar. We
have hydroelectric,'' Jackson said as he discussed the dangers of
nuclear power.
   The crowd of about 250, in which plant workers appeared to
outnumber Jackson supporters by about 3-1, broke out in boos at
that point.
</TEXT>
