<1ST_LINE>r a PM-GoneHome     05-24 0333</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gone Home,0342</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Toddler Leaves Hospital for First Time in His Life</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Little Calvin Lorick, who weighed less than 2
pounds when he was born nearly two years ago, has gone home from
the hospital for the first time in his life.
   Calvin was born June 25, 1986, at St. Mary's Health Center, two
months premature and weighing only 1 pound, 11 ounces. He was
transferred soon after to Cardinal Glennon Children's Hospital.
   On Monday, Calvin, weighing 17 pounds, 10 ounces, left for home.
His nurses crowded into his room and threw a going-away party. They
took turns snuggling with him and gave him tastes of a chocolate
cake that bore the message, ``Calvin, We Will Miss You.''
   The youngster's parents, Ella Pritchard and Calvin Lorick of St.
Louis, said they were overjoyed and apprehensive to be taking their
son home at last.
   ``We have been looking forward to this day for quite some
time,'' said Pritchard, 26.
   ``I'm a little scared,'' said Lorick, 33. ``This is an
experience that we have not had before. I feel that between the
good Lord and myself, we are going to pull it through.''
   Dr. Suzanne Toce, a neonatologist at Cardinal Glennon, said
Calvin had developed a severe chronic lung disease and had required
long-term treatment in the neonatal intensive care unit and the
special care nursery.
   He will still require oxygen during the day and a ventilator at
night, but will be weaned from both.
   ``I just thank God for his coming as far as he has,'' Pritchard
said. ``This is a whole new start for him now.''
   Calvin has two brothers and two sisters who visited him
regularly in the hospital, which became a home away from home for
the family.
   Lorick, who works as a lift truck operator, said that he did not
know how much Calvin's medical care had cost but that the total was
probably ``in the millions.'' Pritchard said expenses had been
covered by insurance.
 
</TEXT>
