<1ST_LINE>r w PM-MarcosPaintings     05-24 0455</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Marcos Paintings,450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Marcos Paintings Coming Back As Evidence</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A dozen paintings believed obtained by
Ferdinand and Imelda Marcos will be brought to the United States
from France in an effort to recover some of the at least $3.5
billion in wealth the couple removed from the Philippines,
U.S.-based Philippine investigators said today.
   The 16th and 17th century paintings confiscated from Saudi
Arabian businessman Adnan Kashoggi are to be used in a grand jury
investigation of Marcos in New York, according to Severina Rivera,
in charge of the U.S. office of the Philippine Commission on Good
Government.
   Some of the paintings expected to be turned over to the Justice
Department this week had been hanging in the Philippine
presidential palace ballroom in Manila before Marcos was deposed in
February 1986, the commission said.
   Among the paintings are works by El Greco, Peter Paul Rubens,
Frans Hals, and several other artists.
   The commission says it has recovered $204 million in cash, real
estate, stocks, paintings and antiques, with another $2.11 billion
contested in litigation in the Philippines, the United States and
Switzerland.
   Estimates of wealth taken out of the country by Marcos, who
ruled for 20 years, and by his family members and associates have
ranged as high as $10 billion. But the commission formed to pursue
his wealth puts the value of Marcos assets currently frozen or
actively pursued at $3.5 billion.
   In a news release from the commission's Washington office,
commission Chairman Ramon A. Diaz is quoted as saying that a
worldwide inventory of paintings claimed by the Philippines is
being put together, but it is believed the Marcoses purchased more
than 100 valuable masterpieces from around the world.
   The Philippines claims that after the Marcoses were exiled in
Hawaii, his agents and Kashoggi carted away 25 paintings from New
York properties owned by the Marcoses. The action allegedly came
after a California federal judge ordered that none of the Marcoses'
property could be ``transferred, encumbered or conveyed'' until the
court decides who it belongs to _ Marcos or the government of his
successor, President Corazon Aquino.
   Thirteen of the paintings were previously returned to the United
States after Kashoggi turned them over to French authorities. But a
company called Interconsult Eastern Management claimed it had
purchased the remaining 12 art works from Kashoggi for $3.2 million.
   The Philippine government alleged the sale was invalid because
Kashoggi never actually owned the paintings, but was only acting as
a front for Marcos. A Paris court last Friday agreed the paintings
could be returned to the United States.
   The Philippine government hopes eventually to sell the
paintings, using the proceeds for land-reform programs, officials
have said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
