<1ST_LINE>r w PM-FedNomination     05-24 0324</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Fed Nomination,320</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Boston Banker To Be Federal Reserve Board Nominee</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Reagan Administration says it wants to put
Boston banking executive John P. LaWare on the Federal Reserve's
board of governors.
   LaWare, whose nomination was announced Monday, would fill a
14-year seat that has been empty since December 1986, when Henry
Wallich resigned.
   LaWare, a 60-year-old Democrat, has been chairman and director
of Shawmut National Corp. and Shawmut Bank in Boston since 1978.
   He was the latest in series of potential candidates for the job.
Others considered at one time or another for the post were Leif
Olsen, the former chief economist at Citibank, and William
Eagleson, retired chairman of Mellon Bank Corp. of Pittsburgh.
   Many of the potential candidates ran afoul of a requirement that
no two members of the seven-member board can reside in the same Fed
district.
   LaWare resides in Brookline, Mass., in the Boston Federal
Reserve district, which does not have a representative on the board.
   That LaWare is a Democrat is expected to boost his chances of
winning approval. There had been speculation the
Democratic-controlled Senate might block any nominee to allow the
next president to fill the spot.
   But both Sen. William Proxmire of Wisconsin, the chairman of the
Senate Banking Committee, and Sen. Jake Garn of Utah, the ranking
Republican, have indicated their willingness to consider a Reagan
nomination if it were made quickly.
   LaWare's appointment would mean a board of all Reagan nominees.
It was not expected that his arrival would alter the general
direction of Fed policy under Chairman Alan Greenspan, who was
appointed by Reagan a year ago to succeed Paul Volcker.
   LaWare came to Shawmut as president in 1978 from Chemical Bank,
which he joined in 1953. He was named chairman and chief executive
of Shawmut in 1980.
   He was graduated from Harvard University in 1950 and received a
master's degree from the University of Pennsylvania in 1951.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
