<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Minorities-Commission     05-24 0352</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Minorities-Commission,340</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Refuse To Sign Report Decrying Minority Plight</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two members of a commission on America's
minorities refused to sign a final report which says the nation is
slipping in efforts to achieve equality for blacks, Hispanics and
Indians.
   The report, ``One-Third of a Nation'' by the Commission on
Minority Participation, proposes a 20-year effort to close the gap
between the races in income, education and other areas.
   The group of civic, academic and political leaders including
former Presidents Ford and Carter said America has not only ``lost
the momentum of earlier minority progress'' but has suffered
reversals in the drive for full equality.
   Panel members Missouri Gov. John Ashcroft and former Secretary
of State William Rogers refused to sign the final report.
   Ashcroft indicated he found it too negative. Rogers declined to
discuss his reasons, but he was said to have felt the report was
exaggerated.
   Ashcroft, a Republican and one of four governors on the
40-member commission, thought the report's ``generalizations about
setbacks in progress are overly broad and counterproductive,''
according to his office.
   Two education groups, The American Council on Education and the
Education Commission of the States, established the commission last
fall. Ashcroft chairs the Education Commission of the States.
   Among the statistics cited in the report:
   _In 1986, 31 percent of blacks and 27 percent of Hispanics were
living in poverty, nearly three times the rate for whites.
   _Unemployment in April was 12.2 percent for blacks, 9.3 percent
for Hispanics and 4.6 percent for whites.
   _Twenty percent of whites age 25 or older have completed
college, compared with 11 percent of blacks and just 8.4 percent of
Hispanics.
   The bipartisan panel refrained from directly criticizing the
Reagan administration or anyone else, but it said leaders from the
White House to Congress to state capitals must ``lend their full
energies to the cause'' of minority advancement.
   The panel included business executives, college presidents,
three former secretaries of state (Edmund Muskie, Cyrus Vance and
Rogers); Coretta Scott King, former Education Secretary T.H. Bell,
Baseball Commissioner Peter V. Ueberroth, and Ted Koppel of ABC
News.
</TEXT>
