<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Nicaragua     05-24 0520</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nicaragua,0537</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ortega Extends Cease-Fire</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FILADELFO ALEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Daniel Ortega extended for
30 days a cease-fire to give his leftist Sandinista government and
the rebels more time to arrange a permanent truce.
   However, the two sides remained deadlocked on Monday over the
site of their next round of peace talks.
   Ortega insisted that the three days of negotiations scheduled to
begin on Wendesday be held in the Nicaraguan capital of Managua.
   In a statement issued in Miami, the rebels said they were
planning to meet in Sapoa, a small Nicaraguan village on the Costa
Rican border.
   Both sides had agreed in March to a 60-day truce that would have
expired May 30. The extension means the temporary truce ends June
30.
   Ortega said he decided to stretch the cease-fire ``in the
interest of allowing negotiations to continue on a definite truce.
We hope the counterrevolutionary directorate contributes to this
effort and acts in accordance with the Nicaraguan people's wishes
for peace.''
   The Contras, as the rebels are known, have resisted holding
another round of negotiations in Managua.
   They complained that during two previous sessions, the
government restricted them to a hotel near the airport on the
outskirts of Managua and refused to let them move freely in the
capital and meet with domestic political opposition groups.
   The five directors of the Nicaraguan Resistance, the Contras'
Miami-based umbrella organization, said in their statement on
Monday that Defense Minister Humberto Ortega had proposed Sapoa and
San Juan del Sur as meeting sites. The defense minister is
President Ortega's brother and chief of the government delegation
negotiating with the Contras.
   President Ortega said Contra delegates would be allowed to meet
in Managua with representatives of the Democratic Coordinate, the
principal opposition group; the opposition newspaper La Prensa; and
Roman Catholic bishops.
   In another development, a source at the Interior Ministry said
American Gary Moore, 38, was expelled from Nicaragua after he
entered a restricted military zone with fake identification
documents.
   In Washington, the State Department described Moore as a
free-lance journalist.
   The Interior Department source, who spoke on condition of
anonymity, said Moore was working for a conservative American group
and was arrested May 18 at Laguna de Perlas, a military zone on the
Caribbean coast. He was deported to neighboring Costa Rica either
late Friday or Saturday.
   The source said Moore ``entered military bases illegally. He
also falsified an accreditation from the presidency's International
Press Center.''
   According to the source, Moore told authorities that he worked
for the National Forum Foundation, a conservative group based in
Washington, D.C., which cooperates with the Nicaraguan Resistance.
   In an interview on Sunday in San Jose, Costa Rica, Moore told
The Associated Press that he was 38 years old, was from Tupelo,
Miss., and had worked for The Atlanta Constitution and The Miami
Herald newspapers. Moore confirmed that he was working for the
National Forum Foundation.
   He said he was working on a documentary on alleged human rights
abuses by the Sandinista government when arrested.
   ``They confiscated all my material,'' including videotapes,
notes and photographs, Moore said.
</TEXT>
