<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Brite-FightingLawmaker     05-24 0239</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Brite-Fighting Lawmaker,0245</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senator Dons Gloves For ``Fight'' With Assemblyman</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TRENTON, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. John Ewing put new meaning into the
words ``legislative battle'' when he bobbed and weaved through the
Statehouse wearing a bathrobe, sneakers, a towel around his neck
and red boxing gloves.
   The 69-year-old Republican, weighing in at 150 pounds, was
making light of a near-fight he had last week with Assemblyman
Anthony `Doc' Villane Jr., the 58-year-old chairman of the Assembly
appropriations committee.
   ``I want you to know that I've been staying in form at Mike
Tyson's gym,'' Ewing said Monday as he displayed some fancy
footwork to reporters. ``Got to keep moving all the time.''
   Ewing went into the Senate gallery and then took a quick trip to
the hallway outside the Assembly's chambers.
   Ewing and fellow Republican Villane, a dentist, had a heated
backroom argument last week that nearly erupted into fisticuffs.
The two ultimately were separated by aides and other lawmakers.
   The dispute flared after both had agreed to a compromise on a
bill to fight illegal drug use. Ewing became angry because Villane
would not let him testify about it before the appropriations
committee.
   Ewing's staff distributed a poster touting the ``long awaited
rematch'' for the ``World's Appropriations Championship'' between
``Mad Jack From Peapack'' Ewing and Doc ``No Novocaine'' Villane.
   When told of Ewing's antics Monday, Villane said with a smile:
``I didn't know I hurt him that bad.''
