<2ND_LINE>PM-Washington in Brief,680</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Zoo Gets Green Light on Panda Exhibit _ For Now</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal officials have given the Toledo Zoo
the green light to open its giant panda exhibit today, but are
still asking the zoo to produce original export documents for the
animals by next week.
   Last week, the U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service said the zoo would
not be allowed to display the two pandas, on loan from China, until
the document issue was resolved. The zoo, which is scheduled to
open the panda exhibit today, was given 10 days to come up with the
documentation.
   However, FWS spokesman David Klinger said Monday that lawyers
for the zoo gave the service a copy of the Chinese export permit
over the weekend and appear to be making a good-faith effort to
deliver the original documents.
   ``We're not going to stand in the way of them opening their
exhibit this week,'' said Klinger.
   Klinger said the pandas were taken out of the wild in China
nearly two months after Dec. 6, 1983, the date pandas were put on
an international conservation group's endangered species list. That
means the animals do not qualify for an exemption under a 1975
convention signed by 95 countries, including China and the United
States, he said.
</TEXT>
