<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Acid Rain Effects New Extending Into Streams in Mid-Atlantic</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   States
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The federal government says the effects of
acid rain are being felt in small streams in the mid-Atlantic
states where surface waters had previously had not been proven
vulnerable.
   Four percent of the stream mileage sampled in 1985 and 1986 in
mid-Atlantic areas was acidic and showed chemical characteristics
that made it unlikely all the acidity could have come from natural
sources, an Environmental Protection Agency study concluded.
   The study, made available Monday, said the proportion reached 10
percent on forested ridges inland from coastal lowlands.
   ``The lack of plausible sources of neutral salts in these
streams makes it likely'' that their acidity is ``probably
associated with atmospheric acid deposition,'' said the study.
   Courtney Riordan, head of acid rain research for EPA, said the
new findings show there has been ``an expansion of the geographic
area'' known to be influenced by acid rain.
</TEXT>
