<1ST_LINE>r i PM-India-Sikhs     05-24 0314</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-India-Sikhs,0322</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hindu Family Of Six Shot To Death In Punjab</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Hindu family of six was shot to death
early today by Sikh extremists in the state of Punjab, the Press
Trust of India reported.
   The family was killed after volunteer guards in the village of
Dhariwal in Jalandhar District exchanged fire with six gunmen who
arrived on motorcycles, the news agency said. The village is 50
miles southeast of the Sikh holy city of Amritsar in northern India.
   The victims were identified as Ram Murti, 25, his mother, wife,
brother, sister-in-law and nephew, the agency said. One of the
guards and a child were seriously injured, the news agency reported.
   Police said one other Hindu was reported killed by Sikh
militants overnight in Amritsar District.
   The latest slayings raised to at least 1,160 the number of
people killed by Sikh radicals in Punjab so far this year. In 1987,
1,030 people were killed.
   Hundreds of migrant workers, mainly Hindus from the northern
states of Bihar and Orissa, have been reported fleeing Punjab
following three attacks on migrant laborers' camps in recent days.
No exact figures were available on the number of migrants leaving
Punjab.
   The migrants traditionally have traveled to Punjab, India's
richest agricultural state, to help with planting and harvesting.
   Sikh extremists have been waging a guerrilla war for an
independent homeland in Punjab since 1982.
   Police and paramilitary forces continued today to surround the
Golden Temple at Amritsar, where a 10-day siege that ended last
week succeeded in driving militants from the shrine. The temple was
reopened to the public Monday.
   Sikhs, whose religion was formed about 500 years ago as an
alternative to Hinduism and Islam, claim they are discriminated
against by India's majority Hindus. Sikhs make up less than 2
percent of India's 800 million population but are a majority in
Punjab.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
