<1ST_LINE>r i PM-MissUniverse     05-24 0500</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Miss Universe,0515</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thai-Born Woman From California Captures Miss Universe Crown</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto TPE1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SHIRLEY LAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LINKOU, Taiwan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 19-year-old psychology student who has
born in Thailand but lives in southern California captured the 1988
Miss Universe crown today in a pageant dominated by Asian women.
   Porntip Nakhirunkanok, the reigning Miss Thailand, wiped away
tears of joy and joined her hands in a Thai sign of thanks after
she was named to succeed 1987 Miss Universe Cecilia Bolocco of
Chile.
   Miss Nakhirunkanok, a black-haired woman from Bangkok, will
receive more than $250,000 in cash and prizes, including a Maserati
convertible and a mink coat.
   Three of the other four finalists were from Asia, including
first runner-up Yunjung Chang of South Korea. Amanda Olivares of
Mexico, Mizuho Sakaguchi of Japan and Pauline Yeung of Hong Kong
were finalists in a field that began with 66 contestants.
   Miss USA, Courtney Gibbs of Fort Worth, Texas, was one of 10
semi-finalists.
   Taiwan authorities lifted a 23-year-old ban on beauty contests
in October to bring the 37th annual pageant to this island.
   Organizers estimated about 700 million people watched the event
beamed around the world from Linkou Stadium in suburban Taipei.
   The pageant began at 9 a.m. today (9 p.m. EDT Monday) so U.S.
viewers could watch the program during prime time.
   Miss Nakhirunkanok, who weighs 114 pounds and stands 5 feet 8
inches tall, said she moved to Los Angeles with her family 15 years
ago.
   When asked by host Alan Thicke how she had learned English she
replied: ``I think I owe it to Big Bird. I watched `Sesame Street'
a lot when I was little.''
   The new Miss Universe said she is a sophomore studying
psychology at Pasadena City College in Californa and that she
briefly attended UCLA. She also is involved in charity work for
youth in Thailand.
   Thailand won the Miss Universe title once before, in 1965 when
Apasra Hongsakula was chosen.
   Beauty pageants were banned in 1964 by Taiwan's leaders, who
viewed the competitions as an extravagance for a poor nation and
were dismayed by reports that a Miss China winner performed strip
dances in Las Vegas.
   The island has since emerged as one of Asia's most prosperous
countries. Authorities lifted the ban last year to clear the way
for a domestic airline to sponsor the Miss Universe pageant despite
lingering opposition from a few groups, including retired soldiers
who view beauty contests as an insult to mothers.
   But the telecast generally was seen in Taiwan as an opportunity
to present the island to a worldwide audience as the Republic of
China, the official name of Taiwan that is seldom used
internationally because most countries recognize the rival
communist Chinese government in Beijing. The televised program
repeatedly referred to Taiwan as the Republic of China.
   Missing from the program was long-time host Bob Barker, an
animal rights activist who resigned after last year's competition
in Singapore to protest the use of furs.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
