<1ST_LINE>r a PM-MissingDocuments     05-24 0400</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Missing Documents,0412</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Documents In Noriega Case May Be Missing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JACKIE HALLIFAX</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Documents that support the story of a pilot whose
testimony is key to U.S. drug charges against Panama's Gen. Manuel
Antonio Noriega may be missing, federal officials say.
   An investigation is under way to determine whether the documents
were lost somewhere between Panama's capital and Miami or never
existed, said Jack Hook, a spokesman for the U.S. Drug Enforcement
Administration here.
   ``That's the big question,'' Hook said Monday night. ``That's
why we turned the investigation over to our internal affairs unit
out of Washington.''
   A Panamanian attorney working undercover for the DEA gave the
documents to agency officials in Panama City, and they were stored
in a safe in the U.S. Embassy in Panama's capital, NBC's ``Nightly
News'' reported Monday.
   A 12-count indictment returned by a federal grand jury in Miami
on Feb. 4 accused the Panamanian leader of accepting $4.6 million
in bribes from Colombia's violent Medellin drug cartel. A grand
jury in Tampa indicted Noriega the next day on three marijuana
importation counts.
   The post-indictment information reportedly contained in the
documents was not crucial to the case, said DEA spokesman Cornelius
Dougherty in Washington.
   ``At this point in time, it does not affect the indictment,'' he
said. ``Beyond that I can't go.''
   Hook said he was unsure how important the documents were but
that the person who provided them to the DEA described them as
relevant to the charges.
   ``His claim was that they would be beneficial in the General
Noriega case for the United States and, again, at this point we
don't know if that's true or not,'' Hook said.
   U.S. Attorney Leon Kellner confirmed that an investigation into
the documents was being conducted but said he couldn't comment on
the contents or significance of the documents.
   The documents reportedly include flight plans and financial
records that corroborate the testimony of drug pilot Floyd Carlton,
a key witness against Noriega.
   NBC quoted unidentified authorities as saying that U.S. drug and
intelligence agents in Panama City were suspects in the
disappearance of the documents.
   ``That's absolutely false,'' Dougherty told The Associated
Press. ``There's no information or indication in any information
that we've received that would support any such allegation.''
   The investigation, a matter of routine policy, ``is on the
informant and not on any DEA agent,'' Dougherty said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
