<FILEID>AP-NR-05-24-88 0544EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-HarvardTrial     05-24 0575</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Harvard Trial,0592</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Trial Opens In Sex Discrimination Case Against Harvard Business
School</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former Harvard Business School professor who
claims she was the victim of sex discrimination is being pressed to
identify specific acts of bias that allegedly stopped her from
becoming the school's fifth tenured woman.
   Barbara Bund Jackson, 44, said Monday in the first day of
testimony that several faculty members discriminated against her
during her 11 years of teaching at the 80-year-old school.
   Jackson, who resigned in 1984, is asking U.S. District Court
Judge Douglas P. Woodlock to reinstate her with tenure and award
$847,000 in lost income.
   She cited several incidents of alleged sex bias by several
faculty members, saying one professor threatened that if she didn't
change the title of a course he would not back her for tenure. The
same professor, she said, refused to help her with computer program
problems in one course.
   ``Maybe he simply didn't like you as an individual,'' Harvard
attorney Allan A. Ryan Jr., said of Professor Robert Schlaifer.
   ``I had been told the opposition was based on gender,'' Ms.
Jackson said. ``My reaction when I see someone acting childish is
to look for a reason. Through conversations with a number of
people, I was led to conclude it was bias.''
   But when Ryan asked whether she could link Schlaifer to her
tenure denials in 1981 and 1983, she said she had ``no information
one way or another.''
   ``To me bias is a spectrum and I don't know where to draw the
line in that spectrum,'' Ms. Jackson said.
   In her lawsuit, Ms. Jackson says she was held to higher
standards than male candidates during her tenure review. She said
the school destroyed documents requested by her attorney to support
her claim that less-qualified men than her received tenure from
1974 to 1984.
   Ms. Jackson also says Harvard has discriminated against women in
hiring and admissions and is guilty of institutional bias.
   Harvard maintains Ms. Jackson was denied tenure solely because
her academic work was substandard, and the tenure records were
unwittingly destroyed by someone outside the business school.
   The lawsuit also names the school's dean, John H. McArthur.
   Under cross-examination, Ms. Jackson testified that she
supported McArthur's appointment in 1980 and thanked him for
settling a dispute involving an on-campus recruiter who told
students his company would not post women to Europe.
   Ms. Jackson, now a private marketing consultant, began teaching
at Harvard as an assistant professor in 1973. She was promoted to
associate professor in 1977 and applied for tenure in 1981.
   After failing to win faculty support on the grounds that while
her teaching skills were up to par her scholarship was inadequate,
Ms. Jackson was given a three-year extension on her appointment.
She submitted new academic work for review, but in December 1983
was rebuffed again.
   Tenure decisions at Harvard are submitted to a faculty
subcommittee and to the faculty to gauge support for the professor.
The actual decision rests with the university president, who
receives a recommendation from the school's dean.
   Three of the business school's 90 tenured professors are women.
Four women have received tenure in the business school's history,
the first in 1961.
   Nationally, 72 percent of male faculty members have tenure
compared with 45 percent of females, according to a recent survey
of 1,055 two- and four-year institutions by the American
Association of University Professors
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880524-0075 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-24-88 0548EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ComputerVirus     05-24 0394</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Computer Virus,0404</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man To Stand Trial On Computer Sabotage Charges</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A programmer deleted more than 160,000
files from his ex-employer's computer by infecting it with an
electronic ``virus,'' said authorities who are prosecuting him on
felony charges.
   Donald Gene Burleson, 39, faces a charge of ``harmful access to
a computer,'' and is free on a $3,000 bond pending his July 11
trial. If convicted, he could be sentenced to 10 years in prison.
   An indictment accuses him of executing programs ``designed to
interfere with the normal use of the computer'' and of acts ``that
resulted in records being deleted.''
   Police described the electronic interference as a ``massive
deletion'' of more than 168,000 records of sales commissions for
employees.
   Burleson is thought to be the first person charged under the
state law that took effect Sept. 1, 1985, and prohibits computer
sabotage, said Davis McCown, chief of the Tarrant County district
attorney's economic crimes division.
   Three weeks after the law went into effect, USPA and IRA Co., a
Fort Worth-based national securities and brokerage concern, noticed
a problem with its computer system, investigators said.
   An investigation revealed that an intruder had used a ``backdoor
password'' at night to gain access to the computer and covered his
tracks by erasing computer logs that would have documented his
activity.
   Burleson, a computer security officer who had been fired two
days before the infection, was one of only a few of the 200 workers
in the home office to have the access and knowledge needed to
sabotage the system, officials said. A computer ``virus'' is a
program that can severely damage a system's regular software.
Viruses can be transmitted among systems through contaminated
software or from programs picked up from electronic bulletin boards.
   ``You can see it, but you can't see what it does _ just like a
human virus,'' said McCown. ``It had the ability to multiply and
move around and was designed to change its name so it wouldn't be
detected.''
   McCown, quoted in Monday's Dallas Morning News, said he wants to
make sure ``that this type of criminal understands that we have the
ability to make these type of cases; that it's not so sophisticated
or complicated that it's above the law.''
   USPA already has been awarded $12,000 by a jury in a civil
lawsuit filed against Burleson.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
