<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Moose Dies,0153</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Wandering Moose Dies After Being Tranquilized</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PULLMAN, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A yearling moose that rampaged across the
Washington State University golf course has died after authorities
tried to tranquilize it.
   ``Apparently the moose started chasing people, and for his own
safety they wanted to get him out of here,'' said Theresa Martz,
director of support services for the campus police department.
   As it was disrupting golfers and stomping on fences on Saturday,
an attempt was made to sedate the animal so it could be returned to
nearby Moscow Mountain.
   But the university police said in a statement that the animal
apparently had ``an adverse reaction to the drug in the
tranquilizer'' and died after it was administered.
   Officials at the College of Veterinary Medicine were performing
an autopsy on the moose to determine the exact cause of death. The
persons administering the tranquilizer were not identified.
