<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Soviet-Unrest     05-24 0269</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Unrest,0278</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hundreds of Armenians Strike, March in Disputed Area</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of Armenians stayed off their jobs and
marched in protest through Stepanakert, said a resident of the city
in Nagorno-Karabakh, a Caucasus Mountains region that has been the
focus of ethnic unrest.
   In a telephone call to The Associated Press in Moscow, a man
said several hundred people marched from downtown Stepanakert, the
largest city in Nagorno-Karabakh, to an Armenian cemetery on Monday.
   The caller hung up the receiver before a reporter could ask his
name and the purpose of the strike and march. Subsequent telephone
calls to Stepanakert did not go through or were unanswered.
   Nagorno-Karabakh is a region in the republic of Azerbaijan that
Armenians want made part of their neighboring republic.
   Most of the 160,000 residents of Nagorno-Karabakh are ethnic
Armenians, predominantly Christians. But since 1923 the region has
been part of Azerbaijan, most of whose residents are Moslem.
   Armenians in the region allege they are discriminated against
economically and culturally by Azerbaijani leaders.
   Strikes and street rallies began in Nagorno-Karabakh in
February, subsided and then began again March 24. That round of
walkouts tapered off gradually starting April 1.
   The latest round came two days after Communist Party officials
fired the two leaders of Armenia and Azerbaijan, apparently because
they had not quelled the ethnic unrest in the region, where at
least 32 people have died violently since February.
   The central government in Moscow has refused the demands to turn
the area over to Armenia, offering instead a plan for $690 million
in economic, social and cultural improvements for Nagorno-Karabakh.
</TEXT>
