<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Koreas-Olympics     05-24 0569</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Koreas-Olympics,0583</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>UN Command Accuses North Korea Of Disrupting Olympics</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY RENFREW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.N. Command today accused North
Korea of trying to disrupt the 1988 Olympic Games by fabricating
false claims that war is looming on the Korean peninsula.
   U.S. Rear Admiral William Pendley, in a letter delivered to
North Korean officials, said an investigation of a recent spate of
claimed border violations found they were ``completely false.''
   ``These ridiculous actions by your side, that are obviously
designed to discourage participation in the forthcoming Seoul
Olympics, will convince no one and will be condemned by the world
community,'' Pendley said in the letter, which was released to the
press.
   North Korea has charged repeatedly in recent months that U.S.
and South Korean forces are preparing to start a war on the divided
peninsula to try and conquer the communist north.
   In Tokyo, President Joaquim Chissano of Mozambique said today
that North Korean leader Kim Il Sung told him the north will not
take part in the Olympics.
   Chissano, who arrived in Japan on Monday after visits to North
Korea and China, told reporters that Kim Il Sung ``indicated the
(North Korean) position on the Olympics just by saying that North
Korea was not going to participate in the Games because they did
not want to condone the policy of two Koreas.''
   North Korea said in January it would boycott the Olympics after
its demand to co-host the Games was rejected by South Korea and the
International Olympic Committee. The committee said the Games are
awarded to a city and cannot be shared.
   South Korea and the committee have been urging the north to
reconsider and take part in the Games in Seoul, but Chissano's
statement indicated there was little hope Pyongyang would agree.
   South Korea, the United States and other nations charged that
North Korea was responsible for the Nov. 29 bombing of a South
Korean airliner that killed all 115 people on board. A
self-confessed North Korean agent said the plane was bombed to
disrupt the Olympics.
   Pendley, senior delegate to the United Nations Command, charged
that North Korea was conspiring to disrupting the Olympics by
fomenting tension with false charges of border incidents.
   ``The results of our investigations revealed that your charges
are completely false,'' he said.
   The UNC is a military command composed of U.S. and South Korean
forces. It deals with North Korean and Chinese delegates at
meetings of the Military Armistice Commission that polices the
cease-fire that ended the Korean War in 1953. Some 42,000 U.S.
troops are based in South Korea under a mutual defense pact.
   The command's statement was issued after South Korea refused
today to accept a North Korean letter calling for talks between
student delegations from the two nations on improving relations,
the South Korean Red Cross said.
   The South Korean Red Cross said in a telephone message to its
North Korean counterpart that the letter would not be accepted at
the border truce site of Panmunjom. The north called for student
talks on promoting reunification.
   The South Korean government insisted instead that the north
resume inter-government talks it broke off in 1986 to protest
U.S.-South Korean military exercises.
   The two Koreas, divided since 1945, are bitter enemies that have
clashed repeatedly over the years. They fought the Korean War from
1950 to 1953 after the north invaded the south.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
