<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SchoolShooting     05-24 0634</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-School Shooting,0654</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Task Force Established To Trace Killer's Final Year</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto CX1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES LITKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WINNETKA, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As this suburb mourned a slain boy, police
formed a task force to investigate the final year in the life of a
woman who opened fire at a grade school, killing the child and
wounding five others.
   Police in a nearby suburb, meanwhile, said Monday they
considered the woman, Laurie Dann, dangerous enough two years ago
that they asked her parents to turn over her handgun. Her parents
refused, but promised to lock it in a safe deposit box, officials
said.
   Paper tulips hung from the ceiling of a second-grade classroom
Monday and more than 1,000 mourners, dozens of them children,
braved a downpour to crowd a synagogue where funeral services were
held for 8-year-old Nicholas Corwin.
   ``I never really knew that kids cared so much,'' said
11-year-old Brian Lewin, minutes before the memorial service ended.
``Now that he's dead, it's hard to think that so many people felt
that way.''
   Nicholas and four other youngsters were wounded Friday after Ms.
Dann burst into their classroom at Hubbard Woods Elementary School
and opened fire. She also shot an 8-year-old boy in a bathroom.
   After fleeing the school, she shot a 20-year-old man at a house
and killed herself after a nine-hour standoff with police.
   Police Chief Herbert Timm on Monday announced the formation of
the task force to investigate the final year in the life of Ms.
Dann, a 30-year-old baby sitter who police say was upset because
the family she worked for was moving.
   Police say tracing the trail of Ms. Dann's bizzare behavior has
led to the discovery of 15 or more poisoned food and fruit juice
packages, attempted firebomb attacks, hundreds of harassing
telephone calls and a possible stabbing attack on her ex-husband,
Russell Dann.
   ``Why couldn't it have been stopped? Here was a person reaching
out for help. She didn't get it. It was a matter of time before
this bomb exploded,'' Dann said Monday, criticizing police for
failing to heed warnings about her.
   ``I hired attorneys. I hired private detectives ... This was the
North Shore of Chicago reaching out for help, not just Russell Dann
... I'm not saying we got no help, but Friday happened,'' Dann said
on ABC's ``Nightline.''
   The Danns' three-year marriage ended in divorce in 1986.
   Dann also made a plea for gun control, saying it was
``horrible'' that his ex-wife was allowed to purchase a gun.
   ``On many occasions, we tried to get her arrested,'' he said,
but police did not pursue her case actively enough.
   Prosecutors have said they were investigating Ms. Dann, but had
not developed enough evidence to arrest her.
   Robert Bonneville, police chief of Glencoe, said authorities
asked her parents to surrender Ms. Dann's .357-caliber Magnum
handgun two years ago because of allegations that she had made
harassing phone calls and had committed theft.
   Her father, Norman Wasserman, refused, but ``agreed to have it
locked up in the safety deposit box,'' Bonneville said.
   One of the three guns Ms. Dann carried at the school Friday was
a .357-caliber Magnum, police said.
   The Wassermans as cooperative with police, Bonneville said, but
refused to believe their daughter was making the telephone calls
and took her side in the other incidents.
   In at least two cases, Bonneville said, Wasserman made
restitution to families for whom Dann worked as a baby sitter or
domestic after she was suspected in thefts of food and clothing
from the homes.
   The Wassermans refused to comment.
   Four of the children wounded in Friday's attack have been
upgraded from serious to fair condition and one remains in critical
but stable condition, hospital officials say. The wounded man was
upgraded from serious to fair condition.
</TEXT>
