<2ND_LINE>PM-Dollar-Gold,0297</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Lower, Gold Weaker</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar traded lower against major foreign
currencies in Europe today. Gold prices also fell.
   Early trading was quiet, with many traders on the Continent
extending a holiday weekend.
   ``Dollar dealing is very sleepy,'' said one exchange dealer with
a major Italian commercial bank. ``Most interest is on the cross
rates.''
   Traders predicted the dollar would remain in the narrow range
established after last week's better-than-expected U.S. trade
figures until fresh news or rumors move the market.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends as Europe's business day begins,
the dollar fell 0.55 yen to a closing 124.25. Later, in London, it
was quoted at 124.35 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Monday:
   _1.6996 West German marks, down from 1.7030
   _1.4165 Swiss francs, down from 1.4198
   _5.7485 French francs, down from 5.7570
   _1.9026 Dutch guilders, down from 1.9075
   _1,262.70 Italian lire, down from 1,263.75
   _1.2412 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2427
   In London, one British pound cost $1.8705, more expensive for
buyers than $1.8675 Monday.
   The price of gold weakened in quiet London trading in the wake
of overnight profit-taking that followed gold's rise above $460 an
ounce Monday.
   At midmorning, London's five major bullion dealers fixed a
recommended price of $458.60 a troy ounce, down from an opening bid
of $459.40 and from late Monday's $459.60.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $458.90. The Zurich market was
closed Monday for a religious holiday celebrated in much of Europe.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell 22 cents to close at a bid
$460.91.
   Silver was quoted in London today at a bid $6.72 a troy ounce,
up from Monday's $6.70.
</TEXT>
