<1ST_LINE>u i PM-FerryFire     05-24 0428</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Ferry Fire,0441</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ferry Towed To Port After Fire Kills Crewman In English Channel</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL WEST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fire broke out on a freight ferry carrying 75
people in the English Channel, and one crewman was killed and
another severely burned before firemen flown in by helicopter put
out the blaze early today.
   Emergency services on both sides of the channel, the world's
busiest waterway, launched a rescue operation when the fire began
in the ferry's engine room at 9:30 p.m. (4:30 p.m. EDT) Monday.
   The fire was reported two hours after the Seafreight Freeway
left the southeast English port of Dover for the Belgian port of
Zeebrugge.
   Sealink U.K. Ltd., owners of the 5,917-ton ferry, said in a
statement that 15 firefighters and their equipment were flown by
helicopter to the vessel.
   It said the firefighters would remain aboard until the ferry
arrived at the French port of Dunkirk, where a tugboat was towing
it today.
   ``They had to extinguish a fairly serious fire in the engine
compartment, which caused quite considerable damage,'' the fire
brigade said in a statement.
   A British Royal Air Force helicopter airlifted the injured crew
member to the Kent and Canterbury Hospital in southeast England.
The hospital said his burns were critical.
   ``We understand ... that it (the cause of the fire) was a
fractured fuel pipe which caused fuel to leak over the port engine
room which then eventually caught fire,'' Chris Garnett, Sealink's
European director, said in a radio interview with the British
Broadcasting Corp.
   The Seafreight Freeway, built in 1981 and capable of carrying
about 70 trucks, has been on charter to Sealink since June 1986. It
operates between Dover, Britain's busiest ferry terminal, and
Zeebrugge and Dover and Dunkirk.
   Lifeboats, rescue tugs and helicopters from both sides of the
channel raced to the Seafreight Freeway when it reported the fire
28 miles off the southeast English coast.
   Other helicopters stood by in case passengers and crew had to
abandon ship.
   Firefighters found the dead crew member in the engine room after
extinguishing the blaze there. His body was put aboard a lifeboat
to be returned to England. The vessel sailed from Dover with 32
crew members and 43 truck drivers, Garnett told the BBC.
   On March 6, 1987 the British cross-Channel ferry Herald of Free
Enterprise capsized outside Zeebrugge, killing 193 people. The
Herald of Free Enterprise, carrying passengers and freight, went
down when water poured through the bow doors, which had been left
open as the vessel pulled out of Zeebrugge.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880524-0084 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-24-88 0639EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Iran-Unrest     05-24 0555</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Iran-Unrest,0571</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Khomeini Faces Growing Unrest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED BLANCHE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini, faced with
deepening divisions in Iran's leadership, called on his supporters
not to stage a rally in the capital, Tehran Radio reported.
   The official radio, monitored in Nicosia, gave no reason for the
highly unusual request on Monday to scrap today's ``allegiance
march'' by the Shiite Moslem fundamentalist Hezbollah, or Party of
God.
   But diplomatic sources with contacts in Tehran, speaking on
condition of anonymity, said other recent pro-Khomeini
demonstrations led to violent protests against the Tehran regime
and against Iran's 7{-year-old war with Iraq. Several people were
reported killed and scores arrested.
   It was not clear whether Khomeini's request to cancel the march
was linked to the protests, which diplomatic sources and travellers
from Iran reported during and after the second stage of elections
for the Majlis, or parliament, on May 13.
   But it was believed that the regime was seeking to avoid
provoking more trouble in the capital, which has been badly
battered by long-range Iraqi missiles in a seven-week missile
exchange with Iraq that ended April 21.
   Iranian officials reported 1,500 people killed in the missile
blitz. But diplomatic sources said the death toll was closer to
3,000.
   Khomeini called last week for unity among Iran's leaders after
the elections in which radicals made sweeping gains and
conservatives fared badly.
   Khomeini said in an address broadcast by the state-run
television and radio network: ``A Majlis without diversity of views
is an imperfect Majlis ... But the outcome should not result in
dividing us into two hostile groups.''
   The leader, whose pre-election support for the radicals was seen
as a major boost for them, said there had been unspecified attempts
``to create discord,'' but that ``thanks to God, they did not
succeed.''
   In an apparent reference to deepening divisions between the
radicals, who advocate wider state control of the economy, and the
conservatives who support a more open capitalist system, Khomeini
noted:
   ``There are not two fronts. Of course, there are two ways of
thinking and it should be so,'' he said. ``But different tastes do
not mean that the people should not be on good terms with each
other.''
   Two senior Shiite clergymen, meanwhie, were reported to have
written an open letter to Khomeini appealing to him to end the
conflict with Iraq.
   But Iran's official Islamic Republic News Agency, also monitored
in Nicosia, on Saturday reported that the two ayatollahs, Mohammed
Reza Golpayegani and Shahbeddin Najafi-Marashi, ``categorically
denied that they had demanded an end to the war.''
   By some Western diplomatic estimates, as many as 1 million
Iranians have been killed or wounded in the conflict. The Iranians
have suffered several military and economic setbacks in recent
weeks.
   On Monday, an Iranian war communique said Iranian warplanes
heavily bombed Iraqi troops east of the border city of Basra in
five consecutive runs.
   Iranian land forces also repulsed an Iraqi attack near Sumar,
``completely routing and chasing the attackers into Iraq after
inflicting heavy losses,'' the communique claimed.
   The official Iraqi News Agency said on Monday that Iraqi jets
flew 145 combat missions and helicopter gunships flew 163 missions
against the Iranians, ``inflicting heavy losses and damage.'' The
Iraqi News Agency reported downing an Iranian Bell-214 helicopter,
but Iran denied the claim.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
