<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel-Lebanon,0287</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Israeli Army Fired On U.N. Peacekeepers, U.N. Charges</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli troops opened fire on United Nations
peacekeeping forces in southern Lebanon, riddling an armored
vehicle with artillery and rifle fire, a U.N. spokesman said today.
   None of the U.N. troops was injured, said Timor Goksel,
spokesman for the U.N. Interim Force in Lebanon.
   He said the peacekeeping force filed a protest with Israel's
army. An Israeli military spokesman said the army was investigating
the incident.
   Goksel said Israeli troops opened artillery fire late Sunday on
an armored personnel carrier, which was stamped with a U.N.
insignia and parked in a lighted lot within a position manned by
Norwegian peacekeepers.
   He said the Israeli troops kept firing on the position despite
two red flares fired by Norwegian troops to alert the Israelis to
the U.N. presence. The incident occurred near the village of
Ibl-es-Saki, north of Marjayoun, inside Israel's self-declared
``security zone.''
   Speaking in a telephone interview, Goksel said the armored
vehicle was hit by more than 60 rounds of artillery and rifle fire,
but there were no casualities.
   ``Both the U.N. checkpoint and the (personnel carrier) were
clearly marked and illuminated at night. There was absolutely no
problem in the area, it was wide open and lighted,'' Goksel said.
``We have protested the incident very strongly.''
   Tensions between Norwegian peacekeepers and Israeli troops grew
earlier this month when the Norwegians destroyed an unmanned
Israeli position established in the U.N. zone near Ibl-es-Saki,
U.N. officials said.
   The Israelis built the position at the time of the army's May 2
raid into southern Lebanon, a three-day incursion aimed at
destroying guerrilla bases north of the security zone.
