<1ST_LINE>r a PM-LancasterLawsuit     05-24 0336</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lancaster Lawsuit,0345</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Burt Lancaster Files $1.5 Million Suit Against Columbia Pictures</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actor Burt Lancaster filed a $1.5 million
breach-of-contract lawsuit against Columbia Pictures, contending
the studio improperly fired him from the film ``The Old Gringo''
and replaced him with Gregory Peck.
   The suit, filed Monday in Superior Court, charged that
Lancaster, 74, was dismissed because the studio had trouble
obtaining cast insurance for him. Such insurance protects a
studio's investment in a film should an actor die or become
disabled.
   The suit seeks $1.5 million for the alleged breach of an oral
contract.
   ``Columbia had no right to terminate the agreement between the
parties based on an inability to obtain cast insurance ... until it
first notified (Lancaster) or his representatives of any potential
problem ... and allowed them to resolve it by various measures,''
the suit states.
   The suit also contends Columbia negotiated with Peck even before
Lancaster was fired.
   Studio officials could not immediately be reached for comment. A
telephone call to Columbia Monday night went unanswered.
   Lancaster declined to discuss the suit.
   According to the suit, the veteran actor and Columbia agreed
verbally in October 1987 that he would be paid a minimum of $1.5
million over a three-year period for his work. As part of that oral
agreement, the suit stated, the studio was to obtain cast insurance.
   Lancaster said the studio failed to notify him of the insurance
problems until it announced in December that he was being fired
because it was unable to secure insurance for him at customary
rates.
   Lancaster had quadruple bypass heart surgery in 1983. However,
the suit said a doctor determined in November 1987 that the actor's
heart conditon had stabilized and he was in good physical health.
   Lancaster, a former circus acrobat, established himself as a
star with his first film, ``The Killers,'' with Ava Gardner in
1945. He received an Academy Award as best actor in 1960 for his
portrayal of a Depression-era evangelical huckster in ``Elmer
Gantry.''
</TEXT>
