<1ST_LINE>r i PM-China-Investment     05-24 0447</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-China-Investment,0459</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>China Must Be Bold In Luring Investment, Deng Tells Corporate
Leaders</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY WILHELM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senior leader Deng Xiaoping today told the
chairmen of some of the world's leading corporations that China
must be bold in its efforts to modernize and attract outside
investment.
   ``We should now advance against difficulties head-on, and
guarantee the continuity of our policies and development,'' the
official Xinhua News Agency quoted Deng as telling the members of
Chase Manhattan Bank's International Advisory Committee.
   ``I often encourage my comrades to be bolder,'' it quoted him as
saying. ``In acting boldly, mistakes are hardly unavoidable. People
should be allowed to make mistakes.''
   Former U.S. Secretary of State Henry Kissinger, counselor to the
Chase committee, told a news conference after the meeting with
Deng: ``The impression he left was China is determined to pursue
its course and maybe accelerate it in the direction of a greater
market component in its economy.''
   ``It was an extraordinary impressive performance on his (Deng's)
part,'' said former Chase Manhattan Chairman David Rockefeller.
``He spoke with great simplicity and vision on China and the world
and confirmed my opinion and that of many others that he is one of
the great men of this century.''
   Chase's 25-member International Advisory Committee also met
today with Chinese Communist Party leader Zhao Ziyang and Premier
Li Peng.
   The committee members, who include the heads of major
corportions such as Italy's Fiat Spa and the Netherlands' Philips
electronic giant, held their biannual meeting in Beijing on Monday
and today.
   In addition to the top leaders, they also met with Minister of
Finance Wang Bingqian, Foreign Minister Qian Qichen and Foreign
Trade Minister Zheng Tuobin.
   Rockefeller said their goal was not to advance individual
business deals but to learn about China's reforms.
   Deng, who began China's retreat from central planning toward a
partially market-regulated economy in 1978, was quoted by Xinhua as
telling the businessmen that price reform has become the toughest
problem.
   The process of lifting government controls that kept prices
artifically low has given rise to inflation that reached 11 percent
in the first quarter of the year.
   Nonetheless, Kissinger said Deng and other Chinese leaders
``seemed to feel they have no other way to go if they don't want to
be suspended in midstream'' in the reform process.
   Chase Manhattan Chairman Willard Butcher said the bank has no
plans to take advantage of China's recent moves to allow foreign
banks to set up full-service operations in China, including
accepting deposits.
   Foreign banks, including New York-based Chase, so far have been
limited to making loans to the government and Chinese and foreign
joint venture companies.
</TEXT>
