<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Japan-Markets     05-24 0300</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0310</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stocks Up, Dollar Down Against Yen In Japan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices gained slightly while the dollar lost
ground in Tokyo trading today as traders reacted to lackluster
market performances abroad.
   The dollar closed at 124.25 yen, down 0.55 yen from Monday's
closing.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225
selected issues moved up 62.90 points, or 0.22 percent, to end the
day at 27,312.66 points. The stock market's gain followed a
144.09-point tumble in trading Monday.
   Led by foreign exchange bank selling, the softer dollar
reflected an overnight weakening in New York, traders said.
   ``The yen is still strengthening ... with some profit-taking
from Europe,'' said King Ogino, a foreign exchange trader with
Goldman Sachs.
   ``Generally people are paying attention to interest rates and
the stock exchange and commodity markets. The soft exchange market
will keep a soft tone in the dollar market,'' Ogino said. ``The
money supply is not excessively high ... so people are buying yen
and selling marks.''
   Shares on the stock exchange also reacted to a slump in New
York. The Dow Jones industrial average fell 11 points overnight in
the slowest trading Wall Street has seen this year.
   ``The gain on the Tokyo exchange was due largely to the purchase
of steel shares such as Kawasaki Steel and Nippon Kokan,'' said
Hitomi Sakano of Nomura Securities, Japan's largest brokerage.
``Otherwise trading was fairly normal, without any particular
market-motivating factors.''
   Electrical and automotive issues also advanced, traders said.
Pharmaceuticals, securities and banking shares were weak, while
nonferrous metals and shippings firmed.
   Domestic economic fundamentals remain strong, however, and a
monthly report issued today by the Economic Planning Agency said
the Japanese economy, backed by private consumption and increased
capital spending, has continued to expand in May.
</TEXT>
