<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Britain-Soviets 1stLd-Writethru a0474 05-24 0642</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Britain-Soviets, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0474,0658</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviets Taking First Tour Of Western Europe Chemical Warfare
Center</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with start of visit, British military
demonstration, Soviet quotes. TRIMS. No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By EDITH M. LEDERER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PORTON, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet experts, making their first visit
to a secret chemical warfare facility in Western Europe, today
watched as British soldiers in gas masks fought off a simulated
attack by an enemy using nerve agents.
   The display marked the official start of the Soviets' three-day
visit to Britain's Chemical Warfare Defense Center in Porton Down
in southwest England.
   It is part of an exchange program to promote progress on a
chemical weapons ban. ``It should facilitate negotations,'' Yuri
Nazarkin, chief Soviet negotiator at the 40-nation Geneva
Conference on Disarmament.
   The conference ended its spring session April 29 with no
breakthrough in sight on an agreement to ban development,
production and stockpiling of chemical weapons.
   After watching the display by nine British soldiers, the 13
Soviet scientists and military experts entered the main buildings
of the British facility to begin talks with British experts.
   The visit, a week before the superpower summit, was billed by
British officials as the most detailed exchange of information to
date with the Soviets on chemical weapons by a Western European
power.
   ``We're not going to reveal all,'' Graham Pearson, director of
the facility, said. ``We're going to try to build confidence
between the United Kingdom and Soviet Union in respect of the
negotiations in Geneva.''
   Lt. Gen. Anatoly Kuntsevich, deputy commander of Soviet Chemical
Troops, said after the display: ``If we consider it to be a
beginning, it is interesting and purposeful.''
   While nuclear weapons will be the centerpiece of the summit,
progress on a chemical weapons ban has so far proven elusive.
   At last December's Washington summit, President Reagan and
Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev called for ``intensified
negotiations'' on a verifiable agreement covering all nations
capable of producing chemical weapons.
   Britain, which halted production of chemical weapons in the
1950s and destroyed its stockpiles in 1957, has been in the
forefront of the Geneva conference negotiations that have dragged
on for 20 years.
   As part of the exchange, British scientists and military experts
will visit the Soviet chemical warfare facility at Shikhany on the
River Volga. The Ministry of Defense said the exchange will be the
first between the Soviet Union and a Western European country
focusing on chemical warfare.
   The Soviet Union only acknowledged in early 1987 that it had a
chemical weapons stockpile amounting to 50,000 tons. One major
problem in the Geneva negotiations is that Western experts put the
Soviet stockpile at 300,000 tons.
   A British defense policy paper issued last week said: ``The
Soviet Union commands the world's largest, most comprehensive and
advanced capability for chemical and toxic agent warfare.
   ``The Soviet capability for chemical warfare far outstrips those
of the West and cannot be justified by any comparable threat from
NATO.''
   The United States, the only other country that acknowledges
possessing chemical weapons, has a stockpile estimated at 30,000
tons.
   It ended an 18-year moratorium on production in December when it
started manufacturing binary weapons, those made from two chemicals
which are harmless alone but lethal when they interact.
   Last October, specialists from the Geneva Conference visited
Shikany, where they were shown chemical weapons which seemed to
date from the 1950s. In November, Soviet inspectors visited a U.S.
Army chemical weapons disposal plant at Toole, Utah, where they
were shown techniques for destroying old gas munitions.
   Since Britain now has no chemical weapons, the Soviet delegation
will only see laboratories at Porton Down where toxic chemicals and
biological agents are tested against protective equipment such as
gas masks, clothing and monitoring instruments which are developed
for the armed forces.
   The facility also tests antidotes to chemical weapons.
</TEXT>
