<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Noriega-Ambassador     05-24 0366</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Noriega-Ambassador,360</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>With PM-US-Panama</HEAD>
<HEAD>Ex-Envoy Says Dropping Indictment May Be Acceptable</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States should accept a ``fair
trade'' that removes Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega from power in
exchange for dismissal of the drug indictment against the
Panamanian ruler, a former American ambassador to Panama said today.
   ``If we want Noriega to leave Panama, we can't keep up an
indictment that simply locks him in,'' Ambler Moss, ambassador to
the Central American nation from 1978-82, said on NBC-TV's
``Today'' program.
   Moss said the indictment against Noriega was a ``bad mistake''
that should now be secondary to changing the political situation in
Panama.
   ``If the rest of the package worked out to be all right _ for
instance Noriega departs from power, a mechanism is put in place
for free elections and other parts of the package look all right _
then it may be a fair deal,'' Moss said.
   U.S. officials have said that, under one arrangement, Noriega
would leave Panama in August and return after the May 1989
presidential elections. They said Noriega would have a hand in the
selection of an interim government, which would serve until the
elected government takes office.
   But the Reagan administration has come under increasing pressure
to halt its negotiations with Noriega, and Vice President George
Bush moved away from the White House stance last week as the
dealings became an issue in the presidential campaign.
   Noriega has remained in power even though the United States in
February began applying pressure, including economic sanctions.
   Sen. Alan Cranston, also interviewed on the ``Today'' program,
said the Noriega dealings have been a ``foreign policy
embarrassment for the Reagan adminstration.''
   ``There was an underestimation of (Noriega's) determination and
his capacity to hang on,'' said Cranston, a member of the Senate
Foreign Relations Committee.
   Moss said the White House has ``displayed poor political
judgment'' in using intelligence reports from Panama on Noriega's
entrenchment.
   ``It isn't a question of not having the information, but a
question of what they did with that information. They misjudged the
character of Noriega; they certainly misjudged the effect of
economic sanctions. From one step to another, the whole thing was
badly mishandled,'' Moss said.
</TEXT>
