<FILEID>AP-NR-05-24-88 0834EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-WritersStrike     05-24 0478</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Writers Strike,0491</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Opposing Sides Meet In Hopes of Settling Scriptwriters Strike</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD DE ATLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Striking scriptwriters and producers met for
the first time in more than a month and talked for nearly eight
hours, but reached no agreement to end the walkout that has delayed
the start of the fall TV season.
   The afternoon session Monday resulted in several closed meetings
between a federal mediator and top negotiatiors for the Alliance of
Motion Picture and Television Producers and the striking Writers
Guild of America.
   ``The parties met under auspices of a federal mediator. Although
we can report no substantive progress, another meeting has been
tentatively scheduled for Wednesday,'' said Writers Guild of
America spokeswoman Cheryl Rhoden.
   Before the meeting, federal mediator Leonard Farrell told
reporters he called for renewed bargaining ``simply because I
believed it was time,'' referring to the 12-week-long strike and
industry job losses.
   Producers have said the strike has cost the industry more than
$15 million in lost jobs and production time, with about 1,400
clerical workers, cast and crew members laid off.
   WGA President George Kirgo said he believed the producers were
beginning to ``feel the impact of no scripts and no new
production.''
   The session at the producers alliance headquarters was
apparently more fruitful than a mediated April 18 meeting, which
ended after only 20 minutes. A March 14 meeting also failed.
   Farrell sat down Monday with Kirgo, WGA West Executive Director
Brian Walton, East Coast WGA Director Mona Mangen, alliance
President Nicholas Counter III and alliance Vice President Carol A.
Lombardini.
   Nearly 100 negotiators, attorneys and advisers for both sides
gathered in other conference rooms to discuss new ideas and
proposals.
   ``They are talking. And there's plenty to talk about,'' said
alliance spokesman Herb Steinberg.
   The walkout began March 7 over creative control on the set and
residual payments for both one-hour syndicated television show
reruns and works distributed in foreign countries.
   The renewed bargaining came four days before writers were
scheduled to meet and consider whether to approve independent
contracts, which would allow some production companies to resume
work.
   About 80 companies have been negotiating for waiver contracts
with the WGA, Ms. Rhoden said. She added that she had no estimate
of how many contracts might be considered and approved by members.
   Leaders of the 9,000-member guild are recommending that West and
East Coast members ratify the independent contracts in hopes of
shortening the walkout, she said.
   Steinberg said the signing of the independents would not affect
negotiations, because they represent less than 10 percent of
feature film and 15 percent of television production.
   The fall television production season usually begins in late
June or early July, but approved and edited scripts in hand are
vital for production to begin. Those scripts are usually being
evaluated by this time of year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
