<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Soviet-Party     05-24 0380</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Party,0391</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Communist Party to Consider 10-Year Limit on Officials</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Communist Party will consider at a June
conference a proposal to limi party officials to two five-year
terms, but it is uncertain whether the change would apply to
general secretary Mikhail S. Gorbachev, a top official said today.
   ``This is a big step in the development of intraparty
democracy,'' Karl Vayno, party leader of the Estonian republic,
said in an interview with Western correspondents.
   Current terms for party jobs are unlimited, and longevity is one
of the key ways Communist Party officials build their personal
power and maintain privileges in their city, region or at the
national level.
   Vayno, one of the more than 300 members of the policy-making
Central Committee, discussed the committee's meeting Monday during
a break in a session of the Supreme Soviet, the country's nominal
parliament.
   The Central Committee discussed and approved the party's
blueprint for the June 28 special party conference, which other
officials say is shaping up as a show-down between backers of
Gorbachev seeking radical changes in the Communist Party and those
who want limited changes.
   Other officials have said earlier that limits on terms of office
would be considered at the party conference, but Vayno provided
more detail on the proposal after it had been accepted by the
Central Committee for discussion.
   One proposal is to limit all elected party leaders, from cities
and local regions all the way to the ruling Politburo, to two
five-year terms, Vayno said.
   But he said there were other proposals to exclude certain party
jobs, including Gorbachev's, from the limitations. He said it was
uncertain what the conference would decide.
   Asked his personal view, he said it ``depends on the
personality.''
   ``If the vote is about Gorbachev, I would vote with both hands
to exclude him,'' Vayno said.
   Gorbachev has urged the Commuunist Party to adopt means of
ensuring turnover in top party positions, and asked by the
Washington Post in an interview last week whether he supported
limited terms of office he answered ``yes,'' but did not elaborate.
   The Central Committee also agreed to place reforms in the
electoral system for government positions before the party
conference, Vayno said. He did not elaborate.
</TEXT>
