<FILEID>AP-NR-05-24-88 0907EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Sequoyah     05-24 0423</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sequoyah,0436</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sequoyah Restarts after Second Shutdown</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHATTANOOGA, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Sequoyah Nuclear Plant reactor was
restarted today, one day after shutting down for the second time
since May 13, a Tennessee Valley Authority spokeswoman said.
   The Unit 2 reactor started up at 3:25 a.m. and was reconnected
to the TVA power system at 6:05 a.m., said spokeswoman Janice
Brady. Within four hours of the restart, the reactor reached about
30 percent power, she said.
   Sequoyah was automatically shut down at 12:28 a.m. Monday
because of an instrument problem in its reactor coolant system,
said Joe Bynum, TVA's assistant manager of nuclear power.
   It was the reactor's second shutdown since it was restarted 11
days ago after a 33-month shutdown for safety reasons.
   However, TVA officials said the two shutdowns were no cause for
concern.
   ``It was a relatively minor instrumentation problem that we can
correct,'' Ms. Brady said. ``As we've said repeatedly, because of
the complexity of any nuclear plant, it's not uncommon for a unit
to automatically shut down.''
   Bynum said the incident, evaluated Monday by a Tennessee Valley
Authority investigative team, represented no danger to plant
employees or the general public.
   At the time of Monday's shutdown, Unit 2 was approaching 75
percent power _ about the same level as on May 19 when a water
gauge problem caused the reactor to shut down.
   The reactor was restarted Saturday after repairs and
adjustments. Plant workers were calibrating a transmitter that
provides readings on reactor water flow when the second shutdown
occurred.
   The employees put the transmitter in the ``trip,'' or off,
position, then detected a trip signal from one of two other
transmitters in the same reactor loop that indicated low water
flow, said Ms. Brady. Four such loops are in each reactor.
   The reactor's transmitter system is designed to automatically
shut down the reactor when two out of the three transmitters in a
loop send trip signals, she said.
   When Sequoyah's Unit 2 went back on line May 13, it became the
first TVA reactor to do so since the federal utility shut down its
nuclear program in August 1985 because of safety concerns.
   TVA tentatively expects Sequoyah Unit 1 to be back on line by
September, and Unit 2 at Browns Ferry Nuclear Plant outside Athens,
Ala., by year's end.
   The federal utility, which has been relying on hydroelectric and
coal-fired plants while its nuclear system has been idled, provides
power to customers in Tennessee and parts of Kentucky, Virginia,
North Carolina, Georgia, Alabama and Mississippi.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
