<HEAD>Reputed Mob Captain Sentenced to 10 Years</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man prosecutors say was a Southern
California crime family leader has been sentenced to 10 years in
prison on drug and conspiracy charges.
   Luigi Gelfuso Jr., 62, pleaded guilty last month to one count
each of conspiracy to distribute cocaine, conspiracy to use
extortion to collect a gambling debt and conspiracy to violate
labor laws by taking money to guarantee a movie was made with
non-union workers.
   His sentencing came Monday, a week after his reputed boss, Peter
John Milano, received a six-year sentence. The two were among 15
people indicted last year on extortion, racketeering and drug
trafficking charges.
   When the indictment was announced, U.S. Attorney Robert C.
Bonner said, ``The main body of La Cosa Nostra in Los Angeles has
been severely gutted.''
   Seven of those indicted were sentenced last week, including
Milano, under a plea bargain. Sentences ranged from 10 years in
prison to five years' probation.
