<DOCNO> AP880524-0099 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-24-88 0916EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w PM-DurableGoods     05-24 0366</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Durable Goods,360</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Durable Goods Orders Rose 0.8 Percent in April</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Orders to U.S. factories for ``big ticket''
durable goods rose 0.8 percent in April, boosted by a jump in
orders for military communications equipment, the government said
today.
   The Commerce Department said orders for durable goods, items
expected to last three or more years, totaled a seasonally adjusted
$116.3 billion last month.
   It was the third consecutive monthly increase and followed gains
of 0.9 percent in March and 0.1 percent in February.
   Analysts had worried that declines in new orders in November and
January indicated some softening of the economy in the wake of the
October stock market crash, but the increase in April confirmed
most analysts' views that the economy is now growing robustly. Most
had expected a rise about in line with today's report.
   Overall, orders in April were 8.5 percent ahead of a year
earlier.
   In April, a large increase in orders for new military
communications hardware more than offset declines elsewhere in
electrical machinery, contributing to a sharp 4.4 percent increase
in that category. It followed a 3.7 percent drop in March.
   Orders in the volatile defense goods category rose 1.4 percent,
following a big 15.1 percent increase in March. Orders excluding
defense goods rose 0.8 percent to $106.3 billion.
   There was also strength in primary metels such as steel. Orders
rose 0.2 percent following a 5.5 percent increase in March.
   The key category of non-defense capital goods, considered a good
sign of business expansion plans, rose 1.4 percent last month
following a 3.9 percent decline. But at $32.9 billion, orders were
still 15.1 percent ahead of last year.
   Orders for civilian aircraft, particularly to Boeing Corp.,
increased. But that was more than offset by a decline in orders for
military planes, leading to an overall 0.3 percent decline in the
transportation category, following a 2.8 percent increase a month
earlier.
   There was also a decrease in orders for non-electrical
machinery. They fell 1.3 percent following a 2.5 percent increase
in March.
   Shipments of durable goods fell 1.1 percent in April to $112.6
billion, following a 3.0 percent increase in March.
</TEXT>
