<2ND_LINE>PM-Lebanon, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0512,0772</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Beirut Factional Fighting Escalates after Mediation Fails</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS thruout to UPDATE on casualties, Hezbollah advances,
Christian fighting easing, NO PICKUP</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thunderous blasts of tank and artillery
fire jolted Beirut today as fighting between Shiite Moslem factions
escalated after the collapse of Syrian and Iranian talks aimed at
reining in their allies.
   In east Beirut, right-wing Christian militias clashed overnight
in a resurgence of a power struggle within the Christian community.
Police said one person was killed and four were wounded.
   Police said 15 people were killed and 42 wounded today as the
pro-Iranian Hezbollah and the Syrian-backed Amal fought one of
their heaviest duels yet in Beirut's southern slums. The casualties
raised the toll since the Shiite fighting broke out May 6 to 294
killed and 993 wounded.
   Police said Hezbollah was inching toward Amal's last stronghold
in the 16-square-mile enclave where most of the 18 foreign hostages
are believed held.
   There has been no confirmed news on the fate of the hostages
since the fighting began. Lebanese reports have said the captives,
who include nine Americans, have been moved several times.
   Also today, a statement signed by Islamic Jihad, which claims to
hold some hostages, said the captives would be killed if their
governments did not initiate direct negotiations with the
kidnappers.
   There was no way to verify the authenticity of the statement.
Islamic Jihad has said it would always send a picture of a hostage
with its statements, but no photograph accompanied the statement
left at the home of a reporter today.
   The statement said: ``The Islamic Jihad Organization advises
countries interested in the hostages' problem to speed up direct
negotiations for their safety, because the application of pressures
as well as the current plans and recipes on the ground targeting
the Islamic fervency will lead to liquidating all the hostages and
throwing their dead corpses out.''
   One daily, Ad-Diyar, which is published in Christian east
Beirut, reported today that two American captives are being held at
the Iranian Embassy. The report, which did not name the hostages,
could not be verified independently.
   Iran last week denied that foreign hostages were being held in
its embassy.
   A police spokesman said Amal militiamen withdrew today from
positions in the Ghobeiry district under a fierce barrage of
howitzer and mortar fire.
   Amal fighters withdrew to the district of Shiyah at the northern
edge of south Beirut, said the spokesman, who cannot be named under
standing regulations.
   Hezbollah controlled the southern and western flanks of Shiyah
and its gunners were pounding Amal's threatened supply lines at the
northern edge of the area, he said.
   ``Hezbollah has managed to achieve some gains across the
Ghobeiry positions,'' an Amal communique said.
   It said Hezbollah gunners blasted Shiyah and the surrounding
area with 1,500 shells in a nine-hour barrage.
   Meanwhile, a Hezbollah statement accused Amal of
``indiscriminately bombarding'' areas under the party's control in
south Beirut.
   T-54 tanks and multi-barrel rocket launchers mounted on trucks
at Amal positions in Shiyah poured gunfire into Hezbollah's
territory. Hezbollah fired back with 155mm howitzers and 120mm
mortars.
   Police said both sides also traded grenades in hit-and-run
forays.
   The escalation followed Syria's rejection of a proposal by Iran
for the deployment of a joint peacekeeping force in the slums.
Brig. Gen. Ali Hammoud, Syria's military intelligence chief for the
Beirut area, said the Iranian proposal was ``out of the question.''
   Such an involvement would strengthen Iran's influence in Lebanon
while Syria is seeking to eliminate sectarian rivalries and end the
country's 13-year-old civil war.
   Acting Prime Minister Salim Hoss called Monday for Syrian
military intervention ``without delay'' to end the Shiite militia
fighting.
   Syria has had about 7,500 troops, 100 tanks and 400 armored
vehicles massed around the area's narrow alleyways and cement-block
shanties for the last 10 days. The buildup came after Hezbollah
seized 90 percent of the urban battleground in the first week of
fighting.
   Syria is Iran's main Arab ally in its 7{-year-old war with Iraq.
But Hezbollah's move to dominate Lebanon's 1.2 million Shiites has
strained that alliance.
   The east Beirut fighting pitted President Amin Gemayel's
Phalange Party irregulars against fighters of the Lebanese Forces,
the Christians' main militia.
   Police said both sides used machine guns and rocket-propelled
grenades in the duels, which raged through the night. The fighting
began after Lebanese Forces ambushers shot and wounded Nabil
Kahhaleh, Phalangist commander for the Sin el-Fil district of
Beirut.
</TEXT>
