<2ND_LINE>PM-Jet Crash,0223</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Small Jet Crashes, Kills Four on Board</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WEST PATERSON, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A small jet crashed and exploded
early today in a wooded area near a 900-unit condominium complex
here, killing two crew members and two passengers, authorities said.
   No one was injured on the ground as the plane plowed into a
rocky hillside; it narrowly missed several homes and landed in the
back yard of one home, about 25 feet from a house, authorities said.
   The twin-engine Learjet crashed shortly after 3 a.m. on Garrett
Mountain, within 50 feet of the 900-unit Westmount Village complex,
said Police Chief Joe Renney.
   ``We heard the impact and when we came outside, we saw the whole
thing in flames,'' said Tula Savickas, in whose back yard the plane
came to rest. ``We couldn't see anything, it was just one
tremendous flame.''
   The jet shattered on impact, making it difficult at first to
determine the number of victims and to identify the craft, Renney
said. Police said woods and a road were aflame with burning jet
fuel when they arrived at the scene.
   The jet had departed Teterboro Airport en route to Morristown
Airport, according to Kathleen Bergen of the Federal Aviation
Administration.
   The regional office of the National Transportation Safety Board
sent three investigators to the scene.
