<1ST_LINE>r a PM-MultipleTransplant     05-24 0305</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Multiple Transplant,0311</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Doctors Unable to Save Youngest Multiple Organ Transplant Patient</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELIZABETH SHOGREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Doctors weren't able to save the life of a
10{-month-old boy who was the last survivor among four children
with rare multi-organ transplants. However, a pioneer in the
experimental surgery said that the child's experience helped
doctors learn that organ rejection can be prevented.
   Michael Steward of Rockford, who received a liver, small bowel,
pancreas and a portion of his stomach in February, died Sunday of
multiple organ failure, said Carolyn Reed, a spokeswoman at Rush
Presbyterian-St. Luke's Medical Center. The hospital announced the
death Monday.
   Michael was the youngest of four children in the nation who
received a multi-organ transplant, doctors said.
   Dr. James Williams, who performed the experimental surgery, was
out of town Monday and could not be reached for comment. But Dr.
Thomas Starzl, a Pittsburgh physician who is considered a pioneer
in the field, praised doctors at Rush Presbyterian-St. Luke's for
their efforts to save Michael.
   ``They were treating a child who otherwise had no hope,'' Starzl
said by telephone Monday night.
   Three-year-old Tabatha Foster of Madisonville, Ky., was the
world's longest survivor of a multi-organ transplant. She underwent
surgery Nov. 1 to replace her liver, pancreas, small intestine and
parts of her stomach and colon; she died May 11 in Pittsburgh after
an infection caused her heart, kidneys and liver to fail.
   Starzl, Tabatha's doctor, said that even though both she and
Michael died, ``there were some very positive sides'' to what
doctors learned through their treatment.
   ``In both these cases we learned we could prevent rejection of
these organs,'' he said.
   ``What will be done now is to take a careful look at the
autopsies and try to assess the prospects of future multi-organ
transplants,'' he said.
</TEXT>
