<FILEID>AP-NR-05-24-88 1102EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w PM-HomeSales     05-24 0527</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Home Sales,550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rate of Existing Home Sales Slows</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The pace of existing homes sales slowed in the
first three months of 1988 as 28 states and the District of
Columbia posted declines from last year's record levels, a real
estate trade group said today.
   The National Association of Realtors said Minnesota, with a 39.3
percent decline, suffered the biggest setback of any state during
the January-March period, when compared with sales during the same
period of 1987.
   In all, 20 states suffered declines of 10 percent or more. Of
those, nine states posted drops of more than 20 percent. The sales
pace picked up in 21 states and held steady in one, Washington.
   Nationally, existing homes sold at an annual rate of 3.66
million units during the quarter, 8 percent lower than a year ago.
   ``Although there were more resale decreases than increases, many
of the declines were in comparison to a surge in sales during the
first quarter of 1987,'' said John A. Tuccillo, the realtors' chief
economist.
   Despite the decline, association officials said sales were still
strong. They noted that sales in early 1987 were propelled by
relatively low interest rates on fixed-rate mortgages, which fell
to nine-year lows of 9 percent to 9.5 percent, on average. Rates in
the first quarter of this year were about a percentage point higher.
   While sales were falling, prices were rising. Honolulu, which
was included in the survey for the first time, supplanted New York
as the costliest housing area in the nation. Median prices in
Honolulu were $198,400. In New York and its suburbs, the median was
$186,600.
   They were followed by Orange County, Calif., $183,300; San
Francisco, $178,800, and Boston, $176,900.
   The least costly housing area was Louisville, Ky., where the
median home cost $51,100. Lansing, Mich., was next at $54,400,
followed by Des Moines, Iowa, $54,500; Grand Rapids, Mich.,
$55,400, and Oklahoma City, $56,500.
   Washington, D.C., had the largest price jump for the quarter.
The median home cost $132,400, up 24.7 percent when compared with a
year ago. Washington was followed by Hartford, Conn., where prices
climbed 21.8 percent and Providence, R.I., where prices increased
19.9 percent.
   Tuccillo said price increases were held back somewhat in New
York City and in other financial centers by the October stock
market crash. The increase in New York was 10.2 percent.
   Forty-four of the 61 metro areas surveyed posted price increases.
   Housing prices dropped in some areas heavily dependent on either
oil or farming. Oklahoma City posted the largest drop, 9.5 percent,
followed by Houston, 7 percent, and Denver, 6.9 percent.
   Nationally, prices rose 4.1 percent to a median of $88,100,
meaning half the houses sold for more and half for less.
   In addition to Minnesota, other states with large declines in
the pace of sales were Colorado, with a 31.4 percent drop;
Arkansas, down 25.2 percent, and New Hampshire, down 24.8 percent.
   By contrast, Alaska recorded a 77.1 percent increase in sales,
followed by Kentucky, with a 28.6 percent rise; Vermont, with a
25.8 percent pickup, Nevada, up 23.7 percent, and West Virginia, up
18.9 percent.
</TEXT>
