<FILEID>AP-NR-05-24-88 1106EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-MenofDartmouth     05-24 0192</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Men of Dartmouth,0196</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Charges of Sexism Prompt Changes in Dartmouth Song</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HANOVER, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dartmouth College, which began admitting
women 15 years ago, has changed the name of its school song from
``Men of Dartmouth'' to ``Alma Mater'' in response to pressure from
alumni and female students.
   The new version ``celebrates the presence of men and women as a
single community on this campus,'' James O. Freedman, president of
the Ivy League school, said Monday.
   A group of alumni and students two years ago began considering
changes for the song, although a campus poll last year indicated 61
percent of the students did not want the song changed.
   Also changed was the opening phrase, ``Men of Dartmouth,'' which
became ``Dear old Dartmouth.''
   ``Chivalric faith'' was replaced with ``undying faith,''
``sons'' with ``ones,'' and one reference to ``brother'' with
``sister.''
   The original lyrics were written in 1894 by Dartmouth alumnus
and poet Richard Hovey.
   Many members of the college community fought the revision and
for the past several years, whenever the song was sung, shouted out
the lyric that told Dartmouth men to stand firm ``lest the old
traditions fail.''
</TEXT>
