<FILEID>AP-NR-05-24-88 1111EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Afghanistan     05-24 0343</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Afghanistan,0363</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviet Pullout Slowed By Guerrilla Gains</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN WILDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet army's march home from
Afghanistan is being slowed by Moslem guerrillas who are attacking
troops still positioned in the eastern part of the country, sources
said today.
   Western diplomats based in Islamabad said reports indicate
Soviet forces will not meet their deadline of withdrawing 25
percent of their estimated 115,000 troops by the end of the month,
as announced by Soviet Lt. Gen. Boris Gromov before the May 15
pullout began.
   Soviet troops entered Afghanistan in December 1979 to support
the country's Marxist regime.
   ``It is difficult to see how the 25 percent withdrawal this
month, promised by Gromov, will be achieved,'' said a diplomat, who
spoke on condition of anonymity.
   Reports said Afghan guerrillas have in the past week attacked
Soviet-Afghan convoys along the Soviet withdrawal route north and
west of the capital of Kabul, as well as in the eastern provinces
near the border with Pakistan.
   ``The regime has lost 18 district towns since mid-March, an
unprecedented string of losses with tactical implications,'' said
the diplomat.
   Afghan sources in Peshawar said they had no figures on the
number of troops who have returned to Soviet territory.
   Guerrilla commander Ahmad Shah Masood, who controls a large
portion of the mountainous region north of Kabul, reportedly agreed
not to fire on Soviet troops if they withdraw peacefully.
   Control of the eastern part of Afghanistan opens strategic new
supply routes to the guerrillas, who are slowly pushing their way
toward the capital.
   Photographs of some of the captured military posts show the
Soviets left behind large amounts of weapons, supplies and
vehicles, indicating they made a hasty retreat.
   As Soviet military support decreases, Afghan President Najib is
expected to concentrate his forces around Kabul.
   Hundreds of government forces have either surrendered or
defected to the insurgents since the Soviet pullout began,
according to diplomatic sources. Exact figures were not available.
   Guerrilla leaders have said their goal is to make Afghanistan a
Moslem republic.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
