<FILEID>AP-NR-05-24-88 1118EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w PM-SuddenAcceleration     05-24 0424</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sudden Acceleration,400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NHTSA Probes Alleged Sudden Acceleration in GM C-body Cars</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM BOVEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal engineers have broadened their
examination of alleged sudden acceleration problems in General
Motors cars, adding 1.4 million C-body cars to the 703,000 H-body
vehicles already under study, it was announced today.
   The National Highway Traffic Safety Administration said it was
opening an engineering analysis of the C-body cars _ 1985-88 model
year Oldsmobile 98s, Buick Electras and Cadillac Devilles and
Fleetwoods _ because they can accelerate suddenly to produce a
``significant increase in engine speed and power output.''
   The agency said it has received 110 complaints of sudden
acceleration in the cars, allegedly resulting in 67 accidents in
which 43 people were injured.
   Since November, the agency has been investigating GM's H-body
cars.
   The agency had received more than 500 complaints of sudden
acceleration or throttle control problems in those cars, the
1986-87 Oldsmobile Delta 88 and Buick LeSabre, and the 1987 Pontiac
Bonneville, resulting in more than 300 accidents.
   An engineering analysis is the second-highest level of
investigation used by NHTSA in its monitoring of auto safety. The
probe of the C-body cars was opened in response to a petition by
the Center for Auto Safety, a consumers group often at odds with
the auto industry and its regulators.
   GM was preparing a response to NHTSA, said GM spokesman John
Hartnett.
   ``As far as we're concerned, we're cooperating with them,''
Hartnett said. ``Just because it is an engineering analysis and the
petition has been granted certainly doesn't mean that there is a
defect. It is not unusual for NHTSA to do this. It has been done in
the past.''
   Asked if there were throttle design similarities between the
C-body and H-body cars, Hartnett said the company had found no
mechanical cause for sudden acceleration in the H-body cars.
``Comparing the systems doesn't help anything. The fact is, we
haven't found anything,'' he said.
   But Sam Cole of the Center for Auto Safety said the C-body and
H-body cars ``share similar mechanical components, and that's why
we believe that those cars may experience a sudden acceleration
problem that is as bad or worse than the H-body cars.'' The cars
use the same electronic cruise control system, Cole said.
   Other sudden acceleration engineering analyses and cases listed
in the report involve the 1986-88 Honda Acura and Sterling and the
1986-87 Mercedes 300E, as well as two that have resulted in
recalls: the 1979-87 Nissan 280Z and 300Z and the 1978-86 Audi
5000.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
