<1ST_LINE>u a PM-WeatherpageWeather 1stLd-Writethru a0545 05-24 0587</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Weatherpage Weather, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0545,0600</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Strong Thunderstorms Rumble Along Middle Atlantic Coast</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 14 grafs UPDATE with storm-related death in North
Carolina, other details. Picks up in 9th graf, `In western ...'
List of temperatures that normally appears at end of story is
unavailable today, because of computer problems at the National
Weather Service.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Thunderstorms rumbled along the East Coast today, killing a
woman in North Carolina and unleashing winds up to 72 mph that cut
power to as many as 55,000 homes in three states.
   A Florida weatherman and a cameraman also were hurt by an
explosion in their van resulting from a strong wind.
   Powerful thunderstorms hit the Middle Atlantic coast from
southeastern New York to Delaware; showers and thunderstorms
extended from western Pennsylvania to eastern South Carolina.
Scattered light showers fell across New England.
   Showers and a few thunderstorms lingered over Alabama and
Mississippi, Arkansas, Kentucky, Illinois, Indiana and Ohio. A few
light showers dampened Kansas and Oklahoma.
   On Monday, fierce thunderstorms downed trees and power lines,
knocking out electricity to 23,000 homes in the Baltimore area,
9,000 homes in the Washington area and up to 23,000 homes in North
Carolina, utility officials said.
   In North Carolina, high winds blew the roofs off five apartment
buildings in Burlington, forcing the evacuation of 50 people, said
the Alamance County communications office.
   A 37-year-old North Carolina woman was killed Monday night when
lightning struck a tree, severing a large limb that fell on the
truck she was driving.
   Another woman was seriously hurt in a separate accident when her
car crashed during the storm, the state Highway Patrol reported.
   At Piedmont Triad International Airport in the Winston-Salem
area, winds were clocked at 72 mph, just 2 mph below hurricane
strength.
   In Jacksonville, Fla., a weatherman and a cameraman for a local
TV station suffered burns when a gust of wind pushed the antenna on
their remote-broadcast van into a power line.
   The 24,000-volt charge surged through the van's wiring, causing
electrical equipment inside to explode, Paul Baldwin, news director
for WLTV-TV Channel 12, said of the noontime Monday accident. The
accident happened just after a live broadcast from the town of
Atlantic Beach.
   Both men were listed in fair condition today.
   In Demopolis, Ala., state troopers said small hail caused a
five-car pileup with two minor injuries.
   And in Centreville, Ala., the National Weather Service recorded
hail the size of quarters, although no traffic problems or damage
were reported.
   In western Maryland, stiff winds blew a porch roof off an
apartment house near Cumberland, but no injuries were reported,
State Police said. A house was flooded in Friendsville, and
flooding stranded motorists or closed roads in northwest Baltimore
and Montgomery County near Washington.
   Today's forecast called for showers and thunderstorms from
Kentucky, Tennessee and Alabama to the Atlantic Coast states;
scattered showers and thunderstorms in the lower Mississippi Valley
and eastern Oklahoma; and widely scattered thunderstorms from
northeast Nevada into western Montana.
   High temperatures were expected to be in the 70s or 80s in most
of the nation; 60s along the Pacific Coast and over the Great
Lakes, the northern Ohio Valley and northern New England; 50s
across Upper Michigan; 90s over parts of Georgia, Florida and
Texas; and 90s to 105 degrees across the desert Southwest.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 a.m. EDT time ranged from 42
degrees at Marquette, Mich., to 86 degrees at Phoenix, Ariz.
   Other reports were unavailable from the National Weather Service.
</TEXT>
