<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Sudan-Terrorism     05-24 0295</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sudan-Terrorism,0305</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sudan Arrests 2 More In Terrorist Attacks, Abu Nidal Connection
Alleged</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALAH ZARROUG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KHARTOUM, Sudan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police have arrested two more members of
a gang that killed seven people and wounded 21 in two terrorist
attacks, a government spokesman said today.
   Security sources, speaking anonymously under government rules,
said all five suspects now in custody carry Lebanese passports and
claim to be Palestinians affiliated with terrorist leader Abu Nidal.
   The suspects said they were retaliating for the April killing in
Tunisia of the Palestine Liberation Organization's military
commander, Khalil Wazir, the sources reported. Palestinian groups
and others said Wazir's assassination was carried out Israeli
commandos.
   However, Sudan's prime minister had earlier ruled out
Palestinian involvement in the May 15 attacks on the Sudan Club and
Hotel Acropol in Khartoum.
   Information Minister Abdallah Mohammed Ahmed, the government's
official spokesman, said the suspects had confessed their roles in
last week's attacks. The final two suspects in the attacks were
arrested Monday.
   Gen. Ibrahim Ahmed Abdel-Karim, Khartoum's inspector of police,
said last week the first three suspects said in their confessions
that the attacks were directed ``against American and British
interests'' in the northeast African nation.
   All the deaths, mostly of foreigners, occurred at the Hotel
Acropol, where two bombs went off outside the dining room as guests
sat down for Sunday dinner. Shortly afterward, men opened fire with
submachine guns at the front gate of the Sudan Club, reserved for
British and Commonwealth nationals.
   In a nationwide broadcast Friday, Prime Minister Sadek el-Mahdi,
said, ``I rule out (any) relationship between the operation and a
Palestinian national group.'' He suggested the attackers could have
been hired by Israel to plant ``the seeds of doubt between Sudan
and the Palestinian struggle.''
</TEXT>
