<1ST_LINE>u i PM-CannesAwards 1stLd-Writethru   05-24 0609</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cannes Awards, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0549,0624</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cannes Film Festival Puts History in Spotlight</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to CORRECT spelling of conqueror</NOTE>
<DATELINE>CANNES, France (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Films with a sense of history, including
Danish director Bille August's ``Pelle the Conqueror'' and Clint
Eastwood's ``Bird,'' dominated the 41st annual Cannes Film Festival.
   ``Pelle the Conqueror'' on Monday won the Golden Palm award as
best film. American actor Forest Whitaker took the best actor prize
for portraying jazz great Charlie Parker in the film ``Bird,''
directed by Eastwood.
   Three performers shared the best actress award _ American
Barbara Hershey, South African Linda Mvusi and 13-year-old Jodhi
May of Britain _ for the British film ``A World Apart.'' The film
about an adolescent's awakening to South Africa's apartheid system
also won the festival's Special Jury Grand Prize.
   August, who also wrote ``Pelle the Conqueror,'' received his
prize from French film star Gerard Depardieu and Italian director
Ettore Scola, president of the 10-member festival jury.
   ``Pelle the Conqueror'' (``Pelle Erbreren'') is based on a novel
by Martin Anderson Nexo. It tells the story of Lasse and his
9-year-old son Pelle, who leave Sweden in the 19th century to work
as cattlemen on a farm in Denmark. There, they are treated like
slaves until Pelle revolts and goes out to make his way in the
world.
   Film star Max von Sydow plays the father, Lasse. Dane Pelle
Hvenegaard, 13, plays Pelle.
   August said he intends to continue his work with historical
settings. He said his next film will be shot in the United States
and set during the Civil War.
   ``Bird,'' which opens next week in France, received a great deal
of media attention during the festival because Eastwood was in
Cannes and because the French public has a long-term love affair
with American jazz. Saxophonist Parker, whose bebop swing
influenced a generation of jazz players, is well-known in France
three decades years after his death.
   Whitaker, who also appeared in ``Platoon'' and ``The Color of
Money,'' was joined on stage to accept the award by Eastwood.
   ``Bird'' also won the technical excellence award in recognition
of its soundtrack.
   It was the second year in a row that Miss Hershey won the best
actress award. Last year, she took the prize for her performance in
``Shy People.''
   The film for which she won this year, ``A World Apart,'' is
based on the true story of Shawn Slovo, an adolescent whose parents
were anti-apartheid activists. The film looks at South African race
relations through the eyes of a 13-year-old girl, Miss May, whose
father flees and whose mother is imprisoned.
   ``A World Apart'' was the first film by director Chris Menges.
   Indian director Mira Nair won the Golden Camera award given to
the best young director for her film ``Salaam Bombay,'' shot in the
streets of that Indian city, that tells the story of a group of
destitute children.
   ``Salaam Bombay'' was the first full-length film by the
30-year-old Indian director, who was trained at Harvard University.
   The prize for best director went to Fernando Solanos of
Argentina for his film ``The South.''
   Other awards went to British director Peter Greenaway, honored
for best artistic contribution for his film ``Drowning by
Numbers.'' The award is given in recognition of a film's
originality and visual innovation.
   The jury prize went to Polish director Krzystof Kieslowski for
``A Short Film About Killing.''
   Soviet director Gary Bardin's film ``Ornaments'' took the Golden
Palm for best short film, Hungarian director Ferenc Cako's film
``Tracks in the Sand'' won the best animated film award, and French
directors Yann Piquer and Jean-Marie Maddedu won best short fiction
film for ``Bodybuilding.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880524-0123 </DOCNO>
