<HEAD>Honduran Ambassador Ordered Held Without Bond</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal magistrate today ordered the Honduran
ambassador to Panama held without bond on charges of trying to
smuggle 26 pounds of cocaine into the United States.
   Rigoberto Regalado Lara, 49, was arrested May 15 at Miami
International Airport when the drugs were discovered in his
luggage. Honduran officials immediately stripped him of diplomatic
immunity.
   Today Regalado's attorney, David Rothman, sought to have him
freed from the Metropolitan Correctional Center, where he has been
held since his arrest.
   But Assistant U.S. Attorney Odilio Diaz said the ambassador was
``an extreme risk of flight,'' noting that if Regalado fled to
Honduras, he could not be extradited back to the United States.
   U.S. Magistrate Samuel Smargon ordered Regalado held without
bond, but said the matter could be raised at next week's
arraignment hearing.
