<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Pakistan-Missile 1stLd_Writethru a0434 05-24 0315</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Pakistan-Missile, 1st Ld _ Writethru, a0434,0322</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reports Pakistan Test Fired Missile, Pentagon Officials Doubt It</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Eds.: RECASTS lead and UPDATES thruout with denial from Pakistanis,
quotes, further background.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pakistan recently test-fired a missile capable
of carrying a nuclear weapon, according to a report in today's New
York Times, but Pentagon sources said they doubt it and Pakistani
officials denied it.
   A Pakistani source said the missile was launched at a test range
in southern Pakistan's Thar Desert on April 25, and that it was
capable of reaching the Indian cities of Bombay and New Delhi, the
newspaper reported.
   The Times quoted a source with ties to the Pakistani government
as saying the missile was of ``home design'' and produced with the
help of Chinese experts.
   The newspaper also said a Reagan administration official, who
asked not to be identified, confirmed that such a test firing had
been conducted.
   However, a senior Pakistani Defense Ministry official in
Islamabad, speaking on condition of anonymity, said: ``I have no
information whether or not such a missile exists.''
   Moreover, two Pentagon officials Monday night said they are
unaware of such a test and do not believe Pakistan has any missile
capable of carrying a nuclear warhead.
   ``To our knowledge, Pakistan does not have any missile,
long-range or tactical, capable of delivering a nuclear device,'' a
senior Pentagon official said.
   The officials, who spoke on condition of anonymity, also said
they do not believe Pakistan has acquired any missiles from any
other nation.
   Pakistan is widely reported to have the capability of building
nuclear weapons, or to be close to it.
   Such reports have been circulating since late April, when India
announced it had developed a long-range missile.
   Neighboring India exploded an atomic device in 1974.
   Moslem Pakistan and Hindu India have fought each other three
times since they became separate nations in 1947.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
