<HEAD>Missouri Dairy Farmer Sentenced to Death</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MARSHFIELD, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Missouri dairy farmer was sentenced to
death today for the slaying of his wife and two nephews in a
September shooting spree that left seven family members dead.
   Judge John E. Parrish followed the recommendation of the jury
that convicted 37-year-old James Schnick last month and imposed the
death sentence. The alternative would have been life in prison
without parole.
   Schnick will be the 60th inmate of death row in Missouri. The
Missouri Legislature approved the death penalty in 1977, but no one
has been executed in the state since 1965.
   Schnick was convicted April 14 for killing his wife, Julie
Schnick, 30, and nephews, Kirk Buckner, 14, and Michael Buckner, 2.
   Schnick also was accused but not tried in the deaths of his
wife's brother, the man's wife, and the couple's two other sons.
