<2ND_LINE>PM-Police Rider,0169</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Officer Jumps On Hood, Shoots Through Windshield To Prevent Theft</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAMPA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A police officer jumped on the hood of his
patrol car and fired three shots through the windshield to stop a
man from stealing the vehicle.
   Police Cpl. Gene Strickland and his partner stopped a pickup
truck for a routine violation about 9:30 p.m. Monday and were
talking to the driver when another man ``came from out of nowhere''
and jumped into the cruiser, said police spokesman Steve Cole.
   The car struck Strickland before he jumped on the hood, Cole
said. The cruiser had traveled about 100 feet when Strickland fired
the shots.
   The driver, Christopher Keenan Dexter, 24, was shot in the chest
and arm and was listed in stable condition at St. Joseph Hospital,
Cole said.
   Strickland, 31, was treated for cuts and bruises at Tampa
General Hospital. He was placed on administrative leave pending an
investigation, which is standard procedure in shooting incidents,
Cole said.
