<1ST_LINE>r a PM-MechamTrial     05-24 0260</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mecham Trial,0266</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prospective Jury Pool Narrowed to 51</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURIE ASSEO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About half of the jury pool for former
Gov. Evan Mecham's criminal trial was being questioned today after
48 prospective jurors were eliminated for showing signs of bias.
   Of the original 99 people, 51 remained as efforts continued in
Maricopa County Superior Court to empanel eight jurors and four
alternates. Mecham and his brother, Willard, are charged with
failing to report a $350,000 campaign loan.
   All 99 had filled out long questionnaires last week aimed at
ferreting out those with obvious bias. The prosecution, defense and
judge reviewed the forms.
   Twenty-three of those dropped from the pool had signed Mecham
recall petitions. Others said they were friends of the Mecham
brothers.
   Mecham is charged with six counts of perjury, willful
concealment and filing false documents; he faces up to 22 years in
prison if convicted. Willard Mecham, his brother's 1986 campaign
treasurer, faces three similar counts and up to 9{ years in prison
if convicted.
   Prosecutor Michael Cudahy and co-prosecutor Barnett Lotstein
asked that the recall petition signers be eliminated from the pool
_ a motion Judge Michael Ryan ``reluctantly'' granted because he
said he doubted that signing a recall petition was directly related
to the criminal charges.
   One person struck from the panel had written, ``Everything I
know about the last 18 months biases me against the Mechams.''
   Another wrote, ``I don't like Evan Mecham.''
   Other prospective jurors struck from the panel wrote that they
believed Mecham was railroaded.
</TEXT>
