<1ST_LINE>u a PM-SchoolTakeover 2ndLd-Writethru a0585 05-24 0718</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-School Takeover, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0585,0738</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>State Officials Move to Take Control of Local System</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to UPDATE with quote from Cooperman's
order, reaction from Jersey City school board spokeswoman. Picks up
in 4th graf, `During the ...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JO ASTRID GLADING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TRENTON, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New Jersey officials today began legal
action to take control of the troubled Jersey City schools system,
saying local administrators have repeatedly failed to improve
education for the district's 32,000 students.
   The state's action could result in the biggest seizure of its
kind in the nation.
   Education Commissioner Saul Cooperman based his decision on an
independent auditor's report that is heavily critical of the local
board of education, district administrators and school principals.
   ``Political patronage, union pressure and cronyism is a
consistent motivation, at all levels, in the hiring, firing and
promoting of staff,'' Cooperman said in an order in which he
formally notified the district of his takeover plans.
   Leslie Silberman, a spokeswoman for the Jersey City Board of
Education, said the panel would not comment on Cooperman's
recommendation until they had time to read the report.
   ``During the (investigation), the department found an
overwhelming failure of the school system. We have documented
example after example of the Jersey City school district's chronic
failure,'' said Assistant Commissioner Walter J. McCarroll.
   Cooperman signed an order Monday requiring the district to
accept the decision within 10 days or respond with reasons why it
should not be taken over.
   If a state takeover is achieved, Cooperman would be empowered to
fire Jersey City schools Superintendent Franklin Williams, top
administrators and the entire board of education, which is
appointed by the mayor.
   The report also said the individual schools in the industrial
city are disorganized and mismanaged.
   The department has gone to court to seek an emergency order that
will give it veto power over personnel and fiscal matters in the
district, Cooperman said. McCarroll said the action was taken
Monday in an effort to maintain the ``status quo'' while the
takeover dispute is resolved.
   A hearing on the state's request is scheduled for June 7.
   Cooperman began a nationwide search several weeks ago for a
superintendent the state can appoint to oversee the district in the
event of a takeover.
   The National Governors Association said a takeover in Jersey
City would be the first time a state took control of such a large
urban system, New Jersey's third-largest.
   Mayor Anthony Cucci will not fight a takeover, aide Robert Ricci
said.
   ``The mayor is saying, `Here are the keys, come on in,''' Ricci
said.
   ``I think any change will be good,'' said Linda Smith, a math
teacher. But she said there were no guarantees even with state
control.
   ``You look at this place and everything is falling apart,'' says
Denise Perez, a senior at Lincoln High School. ``There's grafitti
all over the walls, security guards in the halls. It doesn't make
you very enthusiastic about coming to school.''
   The takeover law, enacted five months ago, gives New Jersey
officials some of the broadest powers in the nation to take control
of troubled districts.
   The state can fire the local board of education, superintendent
and top administrators and appoint someone to operate the district
for at least five years.
   Under the law, troubled districts are given three chances to
improve. But Jersey City was not given a third chance because state
officials said city officials either were unwilling or incapable of
making improvements.
   Educators locally and on a state level have urged the state to
step in.
   Williams would be the first person replaced by the state and has
vowed to fight a takeover. Williams, who declined request for
interviews, has said his district has been unfairly singled out.
   He noted that a third of his district's students come from
single-parent families and hundreds more live in homeless shelters.
Many students come from homes in which English is not the primary
language.
   He has recommended more state funding.
   Kentucky, South Carolina, Texas and New Mexico have laws
allowing state takeovers of failing school districts. Laws in
Illinois and Arkansas let the state eliminate deficient districts,
an Ohio law allows the state to revoke a troubled district's
charter and Georgia officials may impose heavy financial penalties
on such districts.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880524-0138 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-24-88 1321EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-US-Panama1stLd-Writethru a0439   05-24 0741</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US-Panama 1st Ld-Writethru, a0439,740</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>EDs: Tops with Panamanian ambassador's comments, grafs 1-9; picks
up 3rd graf pvs, In a statement.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA </BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Panamanian opposition leader said today the
deal being negotiated by the Reagan administration for a political
settlement in Panama would be turned down by forces opposed to
ruler Manuel Antonio Noriega.
   If a deal is approved by President Reagan and Noriega, forces
opposed to the military chieftain ``will reject the deal. There
will be no peace in Panama; the turmoil will continue,'' Ambassador
Juan B. Sosa said.
   The ambassador, who continues to occupy his nation's embassy
despite being fired by Noriega, said the deal under negotiation
between U.S. and Panamanian negotiators does not call for a
revamping of the Panamanian Defense Forces, thus enabling the
``criminal empire'' Noriega has created within that institution to
wield power even if he departs the country.
   Sosa confirmed many of the previously reported details of the
proposed agreement. He said Noriega would resign as commander of
the Defense Forces in August, then leave the country for an
extended period while preparations are made for elections in May
1989.
   Sosa criticized the administration for negotiating subjects with
Noriega that go well beyond bi-lateral issues.
   He said it is improper for U.S. negotiators to discuss Panama's
political future.
   Under the plan now under negotiation, Panamanian President
Manuel Solis Palma would continue on chief of state while the
United States would recognize ousted President Eric Arturo
Delvalle, Sosa said.
   He said the plan would not guarantee free elections in 1989 nor
would it ensure an end to the ``systematic corruption'' that
currently exists.
   ``No deal is better than a bad deal,'' he said.
   In a statement issued Monday from hiding, Delvalle and his
allies said the negotiations with Noriega, as reported in the
media, ``would mortgage the future of Panama for a long time to
come.''
   The statement was issued through the pro-Delvalle Panamanian
Embassy in Washington by Delvalle and Panama's ``democratic
forces.''
   The administation's chief Panama negotiator, Michael G. Kozak,
was ordered back to Panama late Sunday by the White House to
continue negotiations with Noriega even though Vice President
George Bush has counseled against any dealings with drug dealers,
whether foreign or domestic.
   Delvalle was forced out of office after he tried to fire Noriega
as head of the Panamanian Defense Forces. Delvalle continues to
receive U.S. backing as the legitimate president of Panama, but the
statement indicated he believes the administration has made too
many concessions in its negotiations with Noriega.
   It said Noriega would be able to to continue to exercise
authority even after resigning as defense chief unless the Defense
Forces are revamped.
   U.S. officials who have described the negotiating process have
not suggested that a major overhaul of the Defense Forces is
contemplated.
   The embassy statement also demanded the ``immediate exit'' of
Noriega from Panama, suggesting unhappiness with the August
departure date now planned.
   The U.S. officials have said that, as foreseen in the
negotiations, Noriega would leave Panama in August and return after
the May 1989 presidential elections. They said Noriega would have a
hand in the selection of an interim government which would serve
until after the elected government takes office.
   The embassy statement called for Delvalle's reinstatment as
president and for the formation of a government of national
reconciliation.
   Noriega, the de facto Panamanian ruler who is under
drug-smuggling indictments in the United States, has successfully
resisted prolonged U.S. pressure to force him out.
   There is a sharp division within the administration over what
kind of deal Noriega should be offered, and particularly whether
the government should go ahead with an offer to drop the drug
charges.
   Reagan said nothing had been settled and that there was not a
timetable for concluding a deal. But Under Secretary of State
Michael Armacost said it would be desirable to reach a settlement
before Reagan's departure for Finland on Wednesday. He is due in
Moscow on Sunday.
   Reagan, asked whether he was prepared to drop the drug charges
against the Panamanian general, said, ``Nothing's been settled.
It's still in the works.''
   Kozak, the deputy assistant secretary of state for
inter-American affairs, spent the weekend in Washington after
nearly a month of negotiations in Panama. Kozak briefed Reagan and
other high-level officials and returned to Panama Monday morning.
   State Department spokesman Charles Redman said Kozak ``is
prepared to continue discussions.''
</TEXT>
