<1ST_LINE>r w AM-BRF--SpacePoster     05-24 0156</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Space Poster,150</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Poster Picturing Space Travelers to be Given to Soviets</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A poster picturing all 204 men and women who
have flown in space is being carried to the Soviet Union for next
week's summit meeting at which joint U.S.-Soviet space ventures are
to be discussed.
   The framed poster, which symbolizes international cooperation,
was presented by the Smithsonian Institution on Tuesday to Dr.
William Graham, President Reagan's science adviser, who is
accompanying President Reagan on the trip.
   A second such poster is being sent to Dr. Guriy Marchuk,
president of the Academy of Sciences of the U.S.S.R.
   The poster has individual pictures of the 76 people who have
flown on Soviet ships and 128 aboard American spacecraft in the
order in which they flew.
   The Soviets have long espoused the possibility of a joint
unmanned flight to Mars and Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev renewed
the idea in an interview last week.
</TEXT>
