<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-Allies     05-24 0587</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Allies,580</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Official Says Italy to Take U.S. Air Wing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NATO ministers meeting later this week in
Europe are expected to formally ask Italy to accept 72 U.S. Air
Force jet fighters being evicted from Spain, the Pentagon's No. 2
official said Tuesday.
   Deputy Defense Secretary William H. Taft IV told the House Armed
Services Committee he expects Italy will then agree to be host to
the 401st Tactical Fighter Wing.
   Defense ministers of the 16 North Atlantic Treaty Organization
nations meeting Thursday and Friday in Brussels will probably
approve the funds needed for the relocation of the F-16 planes, he
said.
   Italy had expressed willingness to deploy the wing after the
Spanish government, bowing to internal political pressure, asked
for its removal late last year. But the Italians insisted that NATO
make a formal request and finance the move, expected to cost some
$500 million.
   One of the sites under discussion for the new deployment is the
Italian air force base at Goia Delle Colle on the Adriatic coast of
southern Italy, a defense official said.
   The official, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the
American presence in the impoverished region may be ``easy to sell
to the Italian public'' because of the economic advantages it would
bring.
   Defense Secretary Frank Carlucci had given NATO until August to
reach a decision about the 401st, saying that otherwise he would
order the wing and its estimated 5,000 personnel sent back home and
deactivated.
   Carlucci, who will attend the Brussels meeting en route to the
superpower summit in Moscow, is then scheduled to visit South Korea
and Japan.
   Taft said Carlucci ``has every confidence that (Korean)
officials will be prepared to respond with specific increased
funding levels for their programs at that time.''
   Taft did not say what aid the United States is expecting beyond
the $100 million in direct contributions South Korea gives annually
to support the 43,000 American troops on the Korean peninsula.
   Privately U.S. officials say that while they have not asked
South Korea for specific sums, they expect an offer of no more than
$60 million annually. The officials point out that South Korea
contributes more than $1 billion to the U.S. presence annually in
indirect costs such as real estate and personnel.
   Taft said that on a visit to South Korea earlier this month he
`'suggested they increase their contribution in support of our
common defense efforts against North Korea as well as the growing
Soviet regional presence.''
   The United States has been urging such Asian countries as South
Korea and Japan to increase their defense spending in the face of
their successful economic performance and the decline in the U.S.
spending allowance.
   Taft said he was ``very encouraged'' by Japan's reaction to his
pitch when he stopped in Tokyo earlier this month. He said he would
visit there again this fall following Carlucci's trip, ``and I hope
we'll have something very good to tell you.''
   Taft said NATO, of which Japan is not a member, had reacted with
``extraordinary speed'' in setting up a panel to review each
country's contribution to the alliance. The defense ministers in
Brussels will probably vote to submit a report on the review in
December, he said.
   The NATO review board was set up in response to growing
sentiment in Congress that alliance members whose economies are
improving should carry more of the defense burden and stop relying
on the United States to make up the shortfall.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
