<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--Laos-China     05-24 0139</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Laos-China,0145</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Laos Picks Its First Ambassador to China in a Decade</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Laos has appointed an ambassador to
China, ending a decade of estrangement between the communist
neighbors.
   The official news agency KPL, monitored in Bangkok, reported
Tuesday that envoy Phoungsavath Boupha received his credential
letter on Monday from the Laotian government. It didn't say when he
would take up his post.
   Although some diplomatic ties remained in place, the two
countries withdrew their ambassadors after Laos' ally, Vietnam,
invaded Cambodia in 1978 and ousted a pro-Chinese government.
   In addition, Laos has accused China of aiding Laotian exiles
fighting to overthrow the Laotian government.
   Relations improved in the past year and a half with meetings
between high-level Laotian and Chinese officials. According to
Laos, China has pledged it would no longer help the exiles.
</TEXT>
