<DOCNO> AP880524-0146 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-24-88 1424EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Summit-Souvenirs     05-24 0291</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Summit-Souvenirs,0299</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Just in Time For The Summit: The `Tass Top 20'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Reagan-Summit, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here's the latest bulletin from Tass: The official
Soviet news agency is going into the souvenir T-shirt, button,
record and cassette business, just in time for the summit.
   Tass announced Tuesday night that it has entered into an
agreement with a Washington firm to design, produce and distribute
souvenirs of the May 29-June 2 meetings here between Mikhail S.
Gorbachev and President Reagan.
   Tass Director General Sergei Losev said his agency was venturing
into the souvenir market for the first time, and that it ``makes
good sense for American companies and Soviet organizations to work
together, especially during the planning for such an important
event as the summit.''
   The U.S. partner in the business was identified as Kavulich
International, Inc.
   Tass said the company's chairman, John S. Kavulich II, praised
the joint souvenir operation and said it ``demonstrates the desire
of the Soviet Union to learn more about Western marketing methods.''
   The T-shirts to be produced have a four-color design on the
front, which Tass did not describe, and a new ``Tass Top 20'' logo
on the back to promote a new music rating program the news agency
plans.
   The souvenirs will be sold at Moscow hotels and at ``selected
stores within the United States,'' Tass said.
   Buttons, audio cassettes and record albums also will be
produced, Tass said, without providing details.
   Central planning in the Soviet Union has prevented most
industries from capitalizing on short-term business prospects such
as souvenir sales during events like the summit. But economic
reforms introduced by Gorbachev have allowed more flexibility by
individual enterprises and agencies, and the Tass project is an
outgrowth of those reforms.
</TEXT>
