<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Jackson-Ads     05-24 0281</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jackson-Ads,280</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Sets TV Campaign for California</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson will spend between $500,000 and
$750,000 on TV commercials starting next week in California, his
campaign manager said Tuesday.
   Voters in California and three other states wind up the long
Democratic primary season on June 7.
   Jackson's campaign chairman Willie Brown, the California
Assembly speaker, had earlier said that the budget would be more
than $2 million, but campaign manager Gerald Austin said that
figure might encompass the total campaign budget for advertising,
staff and other costs.
   ``I never thought to spend $2 million on TV,'' he said in a
telephone interview from Los Angeles. But he said the $750,000
estimate may go up ``if some additional money comes in.''
   The Jackson campaign, which has improved its fund-raising to a
$4-million-a-month operation, is paying staff members at offices in
37 of California's 45 congressional districts and thus has other
financial commitments to meet, he said.
   The California commercials will start on May 31, one week before
the election. Austin said it has not been decided whether new ones
will be produced or the campaign will recycle some of the ones it
has used throughout the campaign.
   In New Jersey, which also holds a primary on June 7, along with
California, Montana and New Mexico, there will be no expenditures
for TV, he said, but the campaign is buying some radio time. The
overall campaign budget in New Jersey is about $250,000, Austin
said.
   New Jersey viewers already got a good dose of Jackson ads
because they are in the markets where he aired commericals during
the New York and Pennsylvania primaries, Austin said.
</TEXT>
