<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Honduran-Drugs     05-24 0266</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Honduran-Drugs,0275</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Honduran Ambassador Was `Mule,' Prosecutor Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal magistrate ruled Tuesday that the
Honduran ambassador to Panama must remain in jail on cocaine
charges, and a prosecutor said the suspect apparently was a
``mule'' who simply transported the drug.
   Rigoberto Regalado Lara, 49, was arrested May 15 at Miami
International Airport after 26 pounds of cocaine was discovered in
his luggage.
   He was immediately stripped of his diplomatic immunity by
Honduran officials, who said he would also be prosecuted there if
he returned home.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Odilio Diaz said following Tuesday's
hearing before U.S. Magistrate Samuel Smargon that there is no
evidence Regalado was a major player in the drug trade.
   ``Right now, it looks as if all he is is a typical mule who just
happened to be a Honduran ambassador,'' said Diaz. A mule is a
low-level figure who carries the drugs across borders.
   But Regalado's attorney, David Rothman, said his client was
innocent, and he had proof.
   ``There is a witness in Honduras who can provide a reasonable
and innocent explanation'' for the presence of the cocaine, Rothman
said. Regalado will plead innocent, Rothman said.
   He sought unsuccessfully to have his client freed from the
Metropolitan Correctional Center, where Regalado has been held
since his arrest.
   But Diaz called the ambassador ``an extreme risk of flight,''
noting that if Regalado fled to Honduras, he could not be
extradited back to the United States.
   Smargon ordered Regalado to remain in custody without bond, but
said the issue could be raised again at an arraignment hearing
scheduled Tuesday.
</TEXT>
