<DOCNO> AP880524-0151 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-24-88 1420EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-TVProtest Bjt   05-24 0579</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-TV Protest, Bjt,0595</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Unflappable BBC Newscasters Prevail in Studio Invasion</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Faced with a studio invasion by four screaming gay
rights activists, a BBC-TV newscaster coolly delivered the evening
news while her resourceful co-anchor grappled with one of the women
and silenced her off-screen.
   The women, protesting a new law concerning homosexuality, rushed
into the studio shouting, just as the British Broadcasting Corp.'s
``Six O'Clock News'' went on the air Monday night.
   Puzzled viewers, however, heard only a few unintelligible howls
in the background as anchorwoman Sue Lawley unflinchingly proceeded
with the news of the day.
   Off-camera, as the invaders ran around handcuffing themselves to
pieces of equipment, co-anchor Nicholas Witchell saw a woman run
toward Miss Lawley's desk.
   ``I found she had handcuffed herself to Sue's desk so I sat on
her and put my hand over her mouth,'' he said. ``I thought we would
be taken off the air but Sue, very calmly, kept running through the
introduction to the first piece.''
   Miss Lawley asked viewers to ignore what was going on in the
background and, in her usual pleasant tone, said, ``We have rather
been invaded.''
   She closed the show by apologizing to viewers and telling them,
``Our unwelcome guests have now been taken away by the police.''
   Later she said, ``It was a very alarming experience.''
   BBC security men handed the four women over to police, who
released them without charge later Monday.
   British newspapers carried admiring stories of the two cool
newscasters on their front pages and Ron Neil, BBC's deputy
director of news and current affairs, said: ``Presenting the news,
which is live, is the most difficult of tasks in normal conditions.
To carry on through that kind of unnerving and unpredicted invasion
shows a superb level of professionalism.''
   The BBC said Tuesday it would review and change its security
measures at the Television Center studio in West London.
   ``This group used deception to get into the premises and had
carefully planned their demonstration,'' said a BBC spokeswoman.
``An inquiry has taken place and there will be a slight change in
security practices.''
   She did not give any details, but Press Association, the British
domestic news agency, said the women were believed to have bluffed
their way past the security guards by asking for a fictitious name
at the gate.
   Unable to find the person in the building directory, the guard
told them to go to the reception area in the main building, and
they were unchallenged as they went through the building to find
the news studio, the agency said.
   One of the invaders, Rachel Cox, said Monday the group was
trying to draw attention to the controversial Clause 29, which went
into effect at midnight Monday, barring local authorities from
promoting homosexuality, such as through grants to centers for
homosexuals.
   ``This is a further statement of lesbian defiance,'' Ms. Cox
said.
   On Feb. 2, women protesters slid down ropes from the public
gallery onto the floor of the House of Lords during debate on the
bill. And on March 8, five women chained themselves to the gates of
Buckingham Palace to protest the clause.
   The legislation has been criticized by homosexuals and the arts
community as a threat to artistic freedom. Critics claim it could
lead to the censorship of writers who are homosexuals.
   Proponents of the measure say it is intended to prevent local
governments from using taxpayers' money to teach children that
homosexuality is acceptable.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
