<1ST_LINE>r w AM-GandhiMemorial     05-24 0330</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gandhi Memorial,320</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gandhi Memorial Proposed for Washington</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GENE KRAMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Washington, with its many memorials to war
heroes, needs a monument to a man of peace, Mohandas K. Gandhi,
Congress was told Tuesday.
   The same message was voiced by a parade of witnesses testifying
in favor of legislation to re-authorize construction of a Gandhi
memorial on government-owned land in the capital.
   Gandhi, India's apostle of non-violence and civil disobedience,
was assassinated in 1948 and Congress authorized a Gandhi memorial
the next year But the authorization expired before the then-small
Indian-American community could raise enough money, said Rep.
Mervyn M. Dymally, D-Calif., author of new legislation co-sponsored
by 74 House members.
   A memorial to Gandhi and his philosophy would be especially
important as an inspiration for the millions of children who visit
Washington, Dymally told a House Administration subcommittee.
   ``At a time when ethnic strife is rampant in many parts of the
world, and nations spend significant amounts of wealth on
amrmaments, the preservation of Gandhi's spirit and message has
become a mandate,'' he said.
   Dymally's bill authorizes construction of the memorial at no
cost to the government by the Indian-American Forum for Political
Education, a non-partisan organization that teaches Americans of
Asian Indian ancestry about their adopted homeland.
   Achamma Chandersekaran, the forum president, noted that Gandhian
thinking is rooted in the writings of American philosophers Ralph
Waldo Emerson and Henry David Thoreau. The Indian-Americans want to
``give back to this great country what one of our own borrowed from
here,'' she said.
   The form and location of the proposed monument have not been
decided but Sharat Tak, a local Indian-American computer executive,
has offered to start fund-raising with a $100,000 donation, Mrs.
Chandersekaran said. One proposed location is in a Peace Garden
planned by the National Park Service.
   Gandhi's tactics in the Indian independence movement were used
by the late civil rights leader Martin Luther King, several
speakers noted at the hearing.
</TEXT>
