<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Cockfighting     05-24 0295</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cockfighting,0304</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senate Panel Rejects Bill To Ban Cockfights</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN SAYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After hearing cockfights condemned as a
blood sport and praised as an economic plus for Louisiana, a Senate
committee on Tuesday turned aside legislation to outlaw the
practice.
   By a 2-1 vote, two bills by Sen. Sydney Nelson were deferred by
a judiciary committee. Nelson said he would decide whether to bring
up a bill allowing parishes to ban cockfighting after the House
hears similar legislation.
   ``It took several years to outlaw dogfighting and it may take
several years to outlaw cockfighting, but I think we will
ultimately prevail,'' he said.
   Nelson's legislation would have made cockfighting a misdemeanor
punishable by a fine of up to $500 and a six-month jail sentence.
   Louisiana, New Mexico, Arizona and Oklahoma are the only states
that have not banned cockfighting.
   Nelson, who called cockfighting a ``blood sport,'' presented a
petition with more than 2,000 signatures calling for the ban. The
bill also was backed by several sheriffs and police chiefs.
   Animal activists have long condemned cockfighting. Birds that
participate are specially bred and equipped with a razor to inflict
serious or fatal wounds.
   Bob Baker, a field investigator for the Humane Society of the
United States, called cockfighting ``very degrading and
dehumanizing.'' He said breeders often use illegal drugs to make
their birds fight.
   However, a representative of the United Gamefowl Breeders
Association, said cockfighting buffs ``come from all respectable
walks of society'' and have included George Washington, Thomas
Jefferson, Andrew Jackson and Abraham Lincoln.
   Bob Guilbeau, a Lafayette restaurant owner, said cockfighting
brings tourists to Louisiana. ``My business enjoys its five busiest
weekends when the Sunset Recreation Club (a cockfighting
establishment) has its meetings,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
