<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880524-0156 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-24-88 1431EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Soviet-Party Bjt   05-24 0768</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Party, Bjt,0790</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Party to Consider Limiting Terms of Leaders</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto MOS29</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A ranking official said Tuesday the Communist
Party may limit leaders to two five-year terms, ending the
perpetual tenure that cements personal power, but he did not
indicate it would apply to Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   ``This is a big step in the development of intraparty
democracy,'' said Karl Vayno, party chief for the republic of
Estonia.
   Gorbachev has said he favors restrictions on tenure. Terms for
party leaders now are unlimited and longevity is a tool officials
at the local, retional and nation levels use to build power and
privilege.
   Vayno spoke to reporters during a break in the opening-day
session of the Supreme Soviet, the national parliament that
formally adopts party policy.
   Officials announced an agenda focused solely on domestic
affairs, indicating the 1,500-member body would not consider the
U.S.-Soviet treaty eliminating medium- and shorter-range nuclear
weapons.
   A joint meeting Monday of the Foreign Affairs committees of the
parliament's two chambers approved the treaty. The Supreme Soviet's
Presidium has authority to ratify it, but there was no indication
when it would do so.
   Both Gorbachev and President Reagan had hoped for ratification
by the time their Moscow summit begins Sunday, but the U.S. Senate
also has yet to act.
   According to Vayno, a meeting Monday of the party Central
Committee adopted proposals for consideration at by the June 28
party conference, including a limitation on tenure of party
officials.
   He said other items would exclude certain party jobs from the
rule, among them Gorbachev's as national party chief, and it was
uncertain what the conference would decide.
   Asked for his personal view, he said it ``depends on the
personality. If the vote is about Gorbachev, I would vote with both
hands to exclude him.''
   Gorbachev became first secretary in March 1985 and has urged the
Communist Party to find ways of renewing its leadership. He has
railed against the 18-year reign of Leonid I. Brezhnev as a period
of corruption and stagnation.
   Brezhnev held power until his death in 1982. Kremlin leaders
customarily die in office unless they are pushed out in power
plays, like Brezhnev's against Nikita S. Khrushchev in 1964.
   Asked by The Washington Post last week whether he supported
limited terms of office, Gorbachev answered, ``Yes,'' but did not
elaborate.
   Vayno said the Central Committee also agreed the conference
would debate changes in the voting system for positions in the
soviets, or government councils. Asked whether reforms would
include multiple candidates, he said ``Anything is possible.''
   He gave no further information about the conference agenda,
which some officials have described as showdown between Gorbachev's
reformers and conservatives in the party leadership.
   Tatiana Zaslavskaya, a sociologist and party adviser, says
citizen groups advocating new policies could be organized but
formation of rival political parties would be unconstitutional.
   She told reporters Monday she supports the idea of ``social
institutions or peoples unions'' to assist the party.
   The Supreme Soviet and Central Committee meetings illustrate the
differences between the Soviet and Western concepts of democracy.
   About 20 people spoke at the Central Committee meeting, then the
more than 300 committee members adopted the conference agenda
unanimously, Vayno said. In the Supreme Soviet, as usual, all votes
were unanimous.
   Gorbachev and other party and government leaders attended the
parliament session, including Yegor K. Ligachev, No. 2 man in the
Kremlin.
   Ligachev has been linked with a campaign to slow the reform
program Gorbachev calls ``perestroika,'' or restructuring. He and
Gorbachev spent several minutes in conversation during Premier
Nikolai I. Ryzhkov's address about a law on cooperatives that is to
be approved Wednesday and take effect July 1.
   The Supreme Soviet removed Boris N. Yeltsin, a former candidate
member of the Politburo, from the Presidium. Yeltsin fell from
power in November after making a speech in to the Central Committee
favoring a more rapid pace of reform than Gorbachev. His seat went
to Lev N. Zaikov, who also had replaced Yeltsin as Moscow party
chief.
   Ryzhkov said the cooperative movement Gorbachev offers as an
alternative to the inefficient state-run economy is of ``immense
social and political significance. In a short time it can solve the
most severe problems of perestroika, the demands of the population
for goods and services.''
   Nearly 6,000 co-ops have been formed in the three months since a
draft of the law was published, compared to 14,000 in the previous
18 months. Ryzhkov said the increased pace indicates the
progressive income tax and guarantees that cooperative property
cannot be seized are viewed favorably.
</TEXT>
