<DOCNO> AP880524-0157 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-24-88 1443EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-HazelnutPromotion     05-24 0277</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hazelnut Promotion,0286</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Growers Launch Selling Campaign</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EUGENE, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A nut is a nut, unless it's a hazelnut, in
which case it's a filbert, and in case you didn't know that, an
industry marketing board is about to spend $200,000 to make it all
perfectly clear.
   That's the Hazelnut Marketing Board, by the way. Which works
hand-in-glove with the Oregon Filbert Commission.
   State filbert growers began using the more popular name hazelnut
in the early 1980s for the round, brown nuts of the European hazel
tree.
   The nuts, whatever you call them, are more popular overseas than
they are here, but Oregon growers want to change all that; hence
their first major hazelnut-filbert marketing program.
   Oregon produces nearly the entire U.S. crop of hazelnuts,
averaging 20,000 tons a year, but it's a piker in a world of nut
behemoths like Spain and Turkey, which help produce half-a-million
tons a year.
   ``Hazelnuts are probably used worldwide more than any other
nut,'' says Robert Gelhar, executive secretary for the filbert
commission. ``We have chocolate bars with almonds. In Europe they'd
more likely be hazelnuts.''
   Gelhar said the promotional campaign is aimed at bakeries, candy
makers and other food processing concerns.
   ``It's a matter of getting people acquainted with hazelnuts,''
Gelhar said.
   Junction City grower Jim Rear said Oregon needs to increase its
production to 200,000 tons annually to compete.
   The program's $200,000 will come from an increase in packer
assessments, and not everyone is happy about it. Some say that the
program was adopted at the wrong time because demand already
exceeds supply.
   ``It's hard to sell more nuts if you don't have them,'' said
Rear.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
