<FILEID>AP-NR-05-24-88 1449EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Economy     05-24 0563</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Economy,560</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Orders For Durable Goods Up For Third Straight Month</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Orders to the nation's factories for ``big
ticket'' durable goods increased for the third consecutive month in
April, the government said Tuesday in another report indicating
strong demand for U.S. exports.
   The Commerce Department said orders for durable goods, items
expected to last three or more years, rose 0.8 percent last month
to a seasonally adjusted $116.3 billion. The climb followed gains
of 0.9 percent in March and 0.1 percent in February.
   Orders in April were 8.5 percent greater than a year earlier.
   ``It's a moderate increase. It clearly shows that export orders
are very strong,'' said Lawrence Chimerine, chairman of the WEFA
group, a Philadelphia-area forecasting firm.
   The Commerce Department last week reported that U.S. exports
surged 23 percent in March to a record $29 billion, with much of
the strength coming in machinery, aircraft and computers.
   The declining value of the dollar, which is less than half of
what it was three years ago when measured against the Japanese yen,
is bolstering sales of U.S. goods overseas by making them cheaper
when compared to foreign goods.
   Chimerine and David Jones, an economist with Aubrey G. Lanston &
Co., a government securities dealer in New York, said the cheaper
dollar also is helping U.S. manufacturers in another way by
boosting the cost of imported goods in the United States.
   ``There are some hints that consumers are beginning to turn away
from higher priced imports in favor of domestic goods,'' Jones said.
   With the signs of economic strength, comes concern that
production in industries is approaching capacity limits, a
development that could fuel price increases.
   ``The fear would be that this continuing strength ... could be a
source of renewed inflationary pressure,'' Jones said.
   However, Chimerine said, ``I think the fears of an inflationary
boom have been exaggerated right from the start. ... Even with an
upturn in exports, we're not in the midst of an economic boom.''
   Much of the strength in April came in electrical machinery,
where orders took a sharp 4.4 percent jump, following a 3.7 percent
decline in March. Orders for military communications equipment more
than offset drops in orders for other kinds of electrical machinery.
   Orders in the volatile defense goods category rose 1.4 percent,
following a big 15.1 percent increase in March. Orders excluding
defense goods rose 0.8 percent to $106.3 billion.
   There was also strength in primary metals such as steel. Orders
rose 0.2 percent following a 5.5 percent increase in March.
   The key category of non-defense capital goods, considered a good
sign of business expansion plans, rose 1.4 percent last month
following a 3.9 percent decline. At $32.9 billion, orders were 15.1
percent ahead of last year.
   Orders for civilian aircraft, particularly to Boeing Corp.,
increased. But that was more than offset by a decline in orders for
military planes, leading to an overall 0.3 percent decline in the
transportation category, following a 2.8 percent increase a month
earlier.
   There was also a decrease in orders for non-electrical
machinery. They fell 1.3 percent following a 2.5 percent increase
in March.
   Shipments of durable goods fell 1.1 percent in April to $112.6
billion, following a 3.0 percent increase in March. The backlog of
unfilled orders rose, from $400.4 billion to $404.1 billion, a 0.9
increase.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
