<HEAD>Robertson Supporters To Boycott Convention</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN FLESHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RALEIGH, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pat Robertson supporters said Tuesday they
would boycott next week's Republican convention in North Carolina,
claiming that party regulars are plotting to deny them influence at
the national convention.
   ``By not participating in a process designed to abuse our
delegates, we believe we are today making a positive protest that
we hope will help deter similar behavior in the future,'' said Sue
Wyatt, the state chairman of Robertson's organization.
   Ms. Wyatt accused state GOP Chairman Jack Hawke of stacking key
committees and levying a fee of up to $150 for convention delegates
in an alleged effort to deter Robertson supporters from attending.
   The Robertson leadership's decision apparently will spare the
GOP the bloody fight many had feared at the June 3-4 state
convention.
   But it may signify a reopening of wounds from the party's
clashes of the 1970s between its traditional and New Right wings,
spelling trouble for Gov. Jim Martin and other Republican
candidates who need GOP unity in a state where Democrats outnumber
them by more than 2-to-1.
   The spat pits Robertson supporters, many of whom are new to
party politics, against old-line Republicans who generally
supported Vice President George Bush or Sen. Bob Dole in the
presidential race. Robertson suspended his campaign last week.
   At issue is the interpretation of party rules governing the
election of delegates to the state and national GOP conventions.
   Although Robertson got less than 10 percent of the vote in the
March 8 presidential primary, his supporters packed many precinct
and county conventions _ often comprising a majority.
   They hoped that a sizable number of Robertson supporters would
be elected as delegates to the Republican National Convention in
August, where they could influence the writing of the party
platform and other matters.
   Bush supporters say state law gives their candidate a right to
his choice of at least 29 of North Carolina's 54 national GOP
convention delegates, based on his victory in the primary. They say
Dole, who finished second, won the other 25 delegates, who would be
uncommitted because he quit the race.
   The disagreement led to feuds, walkouts and challenges at
district conventions, including a fistfight at the district
gathering in Louisburg.
</TEXT>
