<HEAD>Ousted Moscow Party Leader Removed from Presidium</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Soviet-Party Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Boris N. Yeltsin, who was fired as Moscow party
boss for disagreeing with Mikhail S. Gorbachev, joined all the
other Supreme Soviet members Tuesday in voting to dismiss himself
from its Presidium.
   All votes are unanimous in the 1,500-member Soviet parliament,
whose function is to endorse Communist Party programs, and
Yeltsin's hand went up with the others when the vote was called for
those favoring his removal.
   Lev N. Zaikov, who also had replaced Yeltsin him as party chief
for Moscow, was given his place in the 36-member Presidium headed
by President Andrei A. Gromyko.
   Yeltsin was fired Nov. 11 after making a fiery speech to Central
Committee meeting on Oct. 21. The full text has not been published,
but the party daily Pravda said Yeltsin criticized the slow pace of
Gorbachev's reforms and said the changes had virtually no effect on
life in Moscow.
   He now is first deputy chairman of the State Construction
Committee, and said to be in charge of meeting the government goal
of providing adequate housing for all citizens by the end of the
century.
   Since Supreme Soviet deputies are chosen on one-party ballots,
Yeltsin probably will remain a member until the next election in
his district.
