<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Bush-House     05-24 0528</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush-House,520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Republicans Back Bush's ``Separation'' From Reagan</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   House Republicans, expressing ``concern but
not panic'' over polls showing Vice President George Bush trailing
Michael Dukakis, applauded Bush Tuesday for differing with
President Reagan on Panama's Manuel Antonio Noriega.
   ``It's a very symbolic circumstance, where Bush has moved from
being vice president to being his own candidate,'' said Rep. Jim
Leach of Iowa, one of the group attending a 90-minute closed
meeting with top Bush campaign officials.
   ``Almost to a person they were pleased about the separation on
Noriega,'' Rep. Lynn Martin of Illinois said of her House GOP
colleagues.
   Bush indicated through aides last weekend that he differed with
the Reagan administration policy of negotiating with Gen. Noriega
in an effort to get him to relinquish power in Panama.
   Part of the deal reportedly being offered by the administration
is to drop drug charges against Noriega if he agrees to leave
Panama temporarily.
   As for the recent polls showing Bush trailing Massachusetts Gov.
Dukakis by margins ranging from 7 to 16 percentage points, Martin
said, ``We have bad polls. If this were October we'd be suicidal.
But it's May.''
   She added, ``There wasn't anybody up screaming, `My God, we've
got the Titanic.' The seas are rough.''
   Meeting with the House members were Lee Atwater, the Bush
campaign manager; Craig Fuller, the vice president's chief of
staff, and pollster Robert Teeter.
   ``They have him behind,'' Teeter said of the polls.
   He said he told the House members that ``we're in a very
artificial period, that period when Dukakis has been rolling along.
What you got to do is get past this California primary before
people begin to focus on it (the presidential race).''
   California is one of four states holding primaries on June 7,
the last big day of the primary season.
   Three recent national polls have jolted Bush partisans. A Gallup
Poll in mid-May had Dukakis leading nationwide 54 percent to 38
percent. A CBS-New York Times poll earlier in the month had Dukakis
ahead 49 to 39, while a Harris poll the same period had the margin
at 50 to 43.
   Rep. Jim Kolbe of Arizona said there was ``concern, but not
panic'' among the House Republicans.
   Asked if there was concern about the impact of the Bush ticket
on House races, Kolbe replied, ``I don't think anybody is feeling
Bush is going to be a negative.''
   Leach predicted there would be other areas beside Panama where
Bush would express his differences with administration policy.
   ``The public will see a modest differentiation on isues between
Bush and the president,'' said the Iowa congressman. ``A growing
difference on the style of leadership with the vice president
making it clear that he will be an involved, hands-on leader.''
   ``Right now the American people have no particular impression of
either Bush or Dukakis,'' said Martin.
   She and Leach said Dukakis has benefited from his continuing
contest with Jesse Jackson for the Democratic presidential
nomination.
   ``He's been allowed to be defined as a moderate,'' said Martin,
because of the contrast with Jackson's views on issues.
</TEXT>
