<HEAD>Carlucci Leaving on Round-the-World Trip</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defense Secretary Frank C. Carlucci will
embark Wednesday on a 17-day trip around the world that will
include a stop in the Soviet Union for the Moscow summit, the
Pentagon said Tuesday.
   Carlucci will travel first to Brussels, Belgium, for a meeting
of the Defense Planning Committee of the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization, then meet with government and military officials in
the Netherlands before joining President Reagan in Moscow for talks
with Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   Following the conclusion of the summit on June 1, Carlucci will
fly to Japan for several days of consultations, then on to South
Korea for the annual security consultative meeting.
   He will fly home by way of Hawaii, spending one day inspecting
the U.S. Pacific Command, before returning to Washington on June
11, the Pentagon said.
