<2ND_LINE>BC-Plane Down, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0677,0374</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Plane Loses Engine Power; Makes Emergency Landing</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 8th graf, `The levee...' to CORRECT that to port, sted
Lake Pontchartrain. Subs penultimate graf to CORRECT that not a
hospital, but a facility at NASA.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Taca International Airlines jetliner
reportedly carrying 45 people lost power in both engines as it
approached New Orleans on Tuesday and made an emergency landing on
grass six miles away, an official said.
   There were no reports of injuries, said a controller at New
Orleans International Airport.
   A controller said the pilot, who was apparently coming in from
Latin America, radioed he lost power in both engines of the Boeing
737.
   ``It was clean landing,'' said Kathy Fernandez, an employee at
the U.S. Department of Agriculture offices who said she saw the
landing as she went outside to her car.
   ``It came down nice. Just fine. As soon as it landed, the door
opened, the chute came down and the people came out and ran away
from the plane.''
   ``As soon as they got out, they just ran up the levee up the
back. It started raining about five minutes after that. It really
started to pour.''
   The controller, who would not give his name, said the plane went
down shortly after noon, about six miles east of the airport, at
the National Space Technology Laboratory, and landed behind the
agriculture department offices.
   The levee is to the Mississippi River-Gulf Outlet, a shortcut to
the Port of New Orleans.
   Tom Branigan, a spokesman for Martin-Marietta Corp., the main
contractor at the space facility, said a stewardess told one of his
colleagues that the flight originated in San Salvador with a stop
in Belize.
   Unofficial reports put the number of passengers at 36 with a
crew of nine, he said.
   He said there is an overgrown paved strip at the facility, but
the plane came down on the grass. He said the plane did not appear
damaged.
   He said two passengers with pre-existing medical problems _ one
recent surgery and one high blood pressure _ were taken to a
medical facility at NASA.
   Customs officials also were notified, Branigan said.
