<1ST_LINE>r w AM-BRF--ReconnaissanceCompetition     05-24 0172</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Reconnaissance Competition,160</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US Army Wins 1st And 2nd Place In West Germany Event</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Army, which last year won the
Boeselager Cup competition in West Germany for the first time, has
taken both first and second places this year, the Pentagon said
Tuesday.
   The competition, designed to test the reconnaissance skills of
cavalry scout units, this year attracted 26 teams from various NATO
countries.
   The winning team was from the 1st Squadron, 1st Cavalry
Regiment, 1st Armored Division, while the second-place finisher
came from the 1st Squadron, 11th Armored Cavalry Regiment. Both are
assigned to the U.S. Army Europe.
   ``This is the first time that our guys have taken first and
second place,'' said Dan Howard, the Pentagon's chief spokesman.
``Our stuff works and our people do, too.''
   Each team was judged in eight events, including a 30-kilometer
reconnaissance patrol, a 300-meter tactical swim carrying a
50-pound rucksack and weapon, a 3-kilometer run, M-16 marksmanship,
enemy identification, night orienteering, driving skill and
coordination of Army aircraft.
</TEXT>
