<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Colombia     05-24 0218</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Colombia,0228</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Three Killed in Clash at Peasant March, Army Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Marchers demanding that an oil field be
closed clashed with the army, and two soldiers and a protester were
killed, the army said Tuesday.
   The deaths came as thousands of peasants marched on a half dozen
cities to demand land and nationalization of foreign oil companies.
   The military has said the protests were organized by leftist
guerrillas. It said rebels were responsible for shooting at the
soldiers Monday, and it identified the dead protester as a
guerrilla.
   The guerrillas were part of the National Liberation Army and the
Colombian Revolutionary Armed Forces, Gen. Yanine Diaz said in his
communique.
   Ecopetrol, the government's oil company, summoned the army to
its oil field in eastern Colombia after leaders of a peasant march
demanded that the field be shut down.
   The fighting occurred about 160 miles northeast of the capital,
near the city of Bucaramanga.
   Some radio stations have reported as many as 80,000 peasants
joining in the marches. But newspapers have said they number about
16,000.
   Diaz said Tuesday that guerrillas were forcing the peasants to
march.
   He also reported a rash of damaging rebel attacks Tuesday on
public facilities near Bucaramanga, including a gas and oil
pipeline, an electric tower, and a bridge.
