<1ST_LINE>r p AM-BRF--Bush-Islands     05-24 0210</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Bush-Islands,210</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Likely to Pick Up 4 Delegates in Virgin Islands</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHRISTIANSTED, St. Croix (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush, the only Republican
presidential candidate to make a campaign stop in the U.S. Virgin
Islands, likely will be rewarded with the territory's four
delegates to the GOP convention, a campaign official says.
   Balloting among the 2,108 registered Republican voters is set
for Saturday.
   ``The vice president, of course, was the only candidate _ when
we had lots of them _ who responded to our call to come to the
Virgin Islands,'' chairwoman Charlotte Poole-Davis said.
   Ms. Poole-Davis said Bush favors extending to Virgin Islanders
the right to vote in presidential elections, and he pledged to
include the territory in federal economic devolopment plans.
   Currently, the residents of this U.S. territory, and the nearby
island of Puerto Rico, may participate in Republican and Democratic
presidential nominating conventions, but cannot vote directly for
president in the general election.
   Four delegates and four alternates will be elected Saturday. Ms.
Poole-Davis said she thinks Bush will garner all four votes.
   Last June, Bush made a four-hour sweep through St. Croix. He
attended a fund-raising dinner at a local restaurant and then a
reception at Government House before flying to Puerto Rico for
other engagements.
</TEXT>
