<DOCNO> AP880524-0178 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-24-88 1959EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-ChemicalWar     05-24 0576</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Chemical War,0597</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviets Watch Simulated Nerve Gas Attack on British Troops</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EDITH M. LEDERER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PORTON, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The first Soviets to visit a chemical
warfare plant in Western Europe watched Tuesday as British troops
ripped off their helmets, donned gas masks and injected themselves
with antidote against a simulated nerve gas attack.
   Armed only with cameras and notebooks, the 13 Soviet scientists
and military experts responded by expressing hope that their
three-day visit would help promote progress on negotiations for a
global chemical weapons ban.
   Maj. Gen. Robert Fedorovich Razuvanov, commander of the chemical
warfare facility at Shikany in the eastern Soviet Union, modeled a
British gas mask for dozens of photographers.
   ``The visit is extremely significant and shows that glasnost is
starting to happen,'' said Dr. Graham Pearson, director of the
Porton Down facility, referring to the policy of openness by Soviet
leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   Among those watching the 45-minute display on the manicured lawn
outside the Chemical Warfare Defense Center at Porton Down in
southwest England was Yuri Nazarkin, the chief Soviet negotiator at
the 40-nation Geneva Conference on Disarmament.
   Nine British soldiers, carrying SA80 automatic rifles and
wearing protective camouflage uniforms, sprawled on the lawn
preparing for a simulated battle. When an alarm went off in a
nerve-agent detector, the soldiers ripped off their helmets and
pulled gas masks over their faces, screaming: ``Gas, gas, gas!''
   They later injected themselves in the hip through their clothing
with a simulated antidote used by the British armed forces against
nerve agent poisoning.
   Using a portable monitor, the soldiers measured the presence of
nerve agents and mustard gas in the air. Finally, they
decontaminated a Scorpion tank using chemical reagents.
   The Porton Down facility, which sprawls across 7,000 acres of a
nature preserve near the ancient Stonehenge monument about 80 miles
southwest of London, concentrates on defenses against chemical
warfare.
   ``We're not going to reveal all,'' said Pearson. ``We won't show
them the detailed assessment of what agents we think other
countries might have, but we will be open about the way in which we
protect the British armed forces against the effects of chemical
and biological warfare.''
   Britain produced chemical weapons until the 1950s, when it
halted all production and destroyed its stockpile.
   Pearson said talks between the British and visiting Soviet
experts would cover the full-range of chemical weapons issues
including production, detection, protection, monitoring,
decontamination, medical countermeasures and disposal.
   In July, Pearson and a dozen British experts will visit Shikhany.
   Some delegates to the Geneva Conference predicted that 20 years
of talks would culminate this year in an international agreement
banning the development, production and stockpiling of chemical
weapons. But three months of negotiations ended April 29 with no
breakthrough in sight.
   ``It is very important for our negotiations in Geneva that we
have more information about what kind of chemical weapons exist,''
said Tessa Solesby, the British ambassador to the Geneva Conference.
   One major stumbling block, along with verification, is the size
of the Soviet chemical weapons stockpile. The Soviets only
acknowledged in April 1987 that they had a stockpile of 50,000
tons, but Western experts estimated it was closer to 300,000 tons _
the largest in the world.
   Although chemical weapons have been used widely in the Iran-Iraq
war, the only country besides the Soviet Union to acknowledge
possessing such weapons is the United States, which has a stockpile
estimated at 30,000 tons.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
