<HEAD>Eight Killed, Three Injured in Blast at Fish Farm</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A devastating explosion killed eight people and
seriously injured three in a storage area of a fish farm east of
Moscow, the nightly news program Vremya reported Tuesday. Six of
those killed were firemen.
   The broadcast showed what appeared to have been a huge brick
storehouse reduced to rubble, and an announcer said the blast was
probably the result of improper storage of chemicals or fuel.
   An investigation was ordered into the cause of the explosion,
Vremya said.
   A.V. Larin, deputy chief of the Moscow region's fire prevention
service, told the news program local firefighters responded to a
report at 11:15 p.m. Sunday of a fire at the warehouse in
Yegorievsk, a town of about 73,000 people approximately 60 miles
east of Moscow.
   The report said six of those killed were firemen who arrived to
put out the blaze and the other two were fishermen who were
standing nearby.
   The broadcast said three people were in serious condition at a
local hospital, but gave no details.
   The news announcer said Soviet Ministry of Fisheries enterprises
in the Russian republic alone were hit by fire 526 times in the
past two years with 63 people killed.
   Vremya did not comment on the statistics, but the disclosure
suggested that the ministry is considered to be lax in enforcing
safety rules.

</TEXT>
