<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Nazi-Deport     05-24 0274</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nazi-Deport,260</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Justice Alleges Former Yale Academic Wrote Anti-Jewish Nazi
Propaganda</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Justice Department has begun deportation
proceedings against a former Yale University faculty member accused
of assisting the persecution of Jewish civilians as a Nazi
propagandist during World War II.
   In an order filed with the U.S. Immigration Court, the
department alleged that Vladimir Sokolov, 75, of Milford, Conn., a
lecturer who taught the Russian language at Yale for 17 years,
voluntarily served in Orel, Russia, from 1942 to 1944 as a writer
and a deputy editor of the newspaper Rech.
   The Russian-language newspaper was published by the German Army
in the Nazi-occupied Soviet Union.
   The department's Nazi-hunting unit, the Office of Special
Investigations, alleged in Monday's court filing that Sokolov wrote
and edited articles that advocated the persecution and
extermination of Jews and the defeat of the Allied powers,
including the United States.
   Sokolov was awarded medals by the German army for his work.
   Sokolov was stripped of his citizenship by the U.S. District
Court in Connecticut in 1986. The U.S. Supreme Court last week
declined to review a decision by the U.S. Court of Appeals that
upheld the lower court decision.
   From 1944 to the end of the war, Sokolov served as a writer in
Berlin for the Russian-language propaganda newspapers Zarya and
Volya Naroda. These two papers published attacks on the Jewish
people and urged Russians to support the Nazi war effort.
   The department says that because of his wartime assistance,
Sokolov was ineligible for admission to the United States under the
Displaced Persons Act, under which he was provided with a visa in
May 1951.
</TEXT>
