<1ST_LINE>r w AM-TemporaryWorkers     05-24 0509</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Temporary Workers,500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Temps Paid 30 Percent Below National Average, Survey Finds</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Workers provided by temporary help companies
are paid about 30 percent below the national average and only
one-fourth get medical benefits enjoyed by virtually all full-time
employees, the government said Tuesday.
   In its first-ever nationwide survey of the burgeoning temporary
help industry, the Labor Department found the average wage paid
last September to temporary workers by firms who hire out their
services was $6.42 an hour.
   The average hourly wage for all non-supervisory workers in
private industry nationwide for the same month was $9.06 an hour,
according to the Bureau of Labor Statistics.
   While still less than 1 percent of the U.S. work force, the
so-called ``temps'' _ who are supervised by client firms but are on
the payroll of temporary help companies _ are one of the
fastest-growing classes of workers in the country.
   In 1987, they grew by 13 per cent to just slightly over 1
million by the end of the year.
   Average hourly wages for temporary workers last September ranged
from less than $4 an hour for construction laborers up to nearly
$25 an hour for engineers. But there were considerable differences
within both occupations and geographic areas.
   For example, wages for word processors provided by temporary
services ranged from $6.09 an hour in Indianapolis to $14.11 in New
York City. Similarly, wages for non-construction laborers provided
by such services ranged from an average $3.73 an hour in Denver to
$6.43 in Newark, N.J.
   In a few isolated instances where shortages in certain skills
has put a premium on the pay that temporary workers can demand, the
government found them being paid more than their full-time
co-workers in the same occupation.
   Temporary word processors in the Bergen-Passaic, N.J., area were
paid $9.58 an hour compared to an average wage of $9.31 an hour
paid full-time employees in the same occupation.
   However, that was the exception, not the rule. Temporary
secretaries in Bergen and Passaic were paid an average $9.34 an
hour, or 81 percent of the $10.59 average paid their full-time
counterparts.
   The gap was wider elsewhere. In Baltimore, secretaries provided
by temp services averaged $6.68 hour, or 62 percent of the average
$10.59 paid to full-time secretaries. In Kansas City, temporary
secretaries averaged $5.84 an hour or 60 percent of the $9.80 paid
their full-time counterparts.
   But it is in the area of benefits _ which now account for about
40 percent of some employers' labor costs, according to the U.S.
Chamber of Commerce _ where the savings become evident in using
temporary workers.
   The government's data showed only 37 percent of temporaries
hired out by contracting companies get paid holidays and 74 percent
have paid vacations, compared with 99 percent of the permanent,
full-time workers who enjoy both.
   And less than one-fourth of the nation's temporary workers
receive any kind of employer-provided hospitalization and medical
benefits compared with 96 percent of the permanent workers who get
them, the Labor Department said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
