<HEAD>U2 Reconnaissance Plane Makes Emergency Landing After Landing Gear
Fails</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PATRICK AIR FORCE BASE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U2 reconnaissance plane
skidded to an emergency landing on a runway Tuesday, but damage was
minor and the pilot was not hurt, the Air Force said.
   A statement said the pilot made a belly landing after the
landing gear failed to come down. He was taken to the Patrick Air
Force Hospital for observation, but officials said he was not
harmed.
   Air Force Lt. Col. Chuck Lutz told Orlando's WCPX-TV Channel 6,
which photographed the U2 after the incident, that the plane
skidded 1,000 to 1,500 feet down the runway. Lutz said damage
appeared to be minor.
   The aircraft was assigned to Detachment 5, 9th Strategic
Reconnaissance Wing, stationed at Patrick Air Force Base.
   ``As a matter of policy,'' an Air Force statement said, ``we
don't discuss specific operations of the U2.'' The statement also
said the names of reconnaissance pilots are not made public.
   The Air Force said it had begun an investigation of the incident.
</TEXT>
