<2ND_LINE>AM-Hughes Aircraft,160</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Company Agrees To Pay Civil Penalty In Boycott Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hughes Aircraft Co. of Los Angeles agreed to
pay a $47,500 civil penalty for allegedly violating U.S.
anti-boycott laws by communicating with a Syrian-based organization
regarding a boycott of Israel, the Commerce Department said Tuesday.
   Paul Freedenberg, under secretary for export administration,
said that Hughes allegedly sent letters in April and May 1983 to
the Central Office for the Boycott of Israel.
   The letters contained information about Hughes' and other
companies business relationships with Israel and with persons
blacklisted by Arab League countries, most of whom boycott goods
and services from Israel, the department said in a statement.
   In paying the penalty, Hughes neither admitted nor denied guilt.
   U.S. law prohibits Americans from participating in a foreign
boycott not supported by the United States. It also bars U.S.
citizens from supplying information about their own or others'
relationship with boycotted countries friendly to the United States.
</TEXT>
