<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Brites     05-24 0396</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brites,0412</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bright and Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SHOW LOW, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The outcome of last week's City Council
election will be decided Saturday in a re-enactment of how this
town got its name.
   Diane Payne-Lara and Leon Taylor, who tied at 275 votes each,
will meet at high noon and each will draw from a deck of cards
until one picks the deuce of clubs.
   Both candidates, dressed in Western garb and carrying
six-shooters, will meet in the city's 100-year-old jail to re-enact
the fateful card game between Marion Clark and Croyden E. Cooley in
1870.
   According to legend, business partners Clark and Cooley had a
disagreement and decided to dissolve their land venture with a card
game, with the loser selling to the winner.
   After they had played all night, Clark told Cooley, ``You show
low and you win.''
   Cooley cut the cards and came up with the deuce of clubs, giving
the town its name.
   Both candidates said they believed the luck of the draw was a
fair.
   Liz Burke, deputy city clerk, said state law allows a tied
election to be resolved by drawing straws, flipping a coin or
drawing cards, but it doesn't mention a runoff.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DULUTH, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Putting a dummy behind the wheel of a
parked State Patrol car is proving to be a smart idea, patrol
officials say.
   The patrol's Duluth district started putting a mannequin in the
driver's seat of an old patrol car Monday and it will be in use at
least through the busy Memorial Day weekend.
   ``We're doing it to raise the perception of visible law
enforcement,'' said patrol Capt. Eric Gunderson. ``We've taken one
of our units that's about to be traded and parked it in an area of
high volume and high visibility.''
   The mannequin was borrowed from a clothier and dressed in a
patrol uniform.
   On Monday afternoon, the car with the mannequin was parked on
the southbound side of Interstate 35 just past the Superior Street
exit to Duluth. About one in every four motorists applied the
brakes as they approached the car.
   The mannequin won't be spending much time in one spot. Gunderson
plans to move it around daily to areas of high traffic volume or
numerous accidents.
   ``So, the next time you go past a patrol car it might or might
not be a dummy,'' Gunderson said.
</TEXT>
