<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SelectpersonsOnly     05-24 0207</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Selectpersons Only,0213</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Town Votes To Eliminate Genders From Titles</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GOSHEN, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When is a chairman not a chairman? When
he's in this town, whose residents have voted to ban the use of
``man'' to describe offices held by men and women.
   The resolution passed by a sizable majority of the 40 people at
town meeting Monday.
   Among the opponents, however, was Harold T. Mollison, who chairs
Goshen's board of selectpeople. He said Tuesday: ``I'm a selectman
and until the (state) law changes I'm still going to be a
selectman.''
   Because the resolution was not on the warrant for the meeting,
it is non-binding and may be embraced or ignored by each
selectperson or chairperson it affects.
   Former Selectperson Anthony J. Thomas said he liked the idea,
but he believed the title of ``selectman'' should remain as long as
Massachusetts uses it.
   According to Thomas, documents signed by Goshen's newly titled
selectpersons must use the term ``selectmen'' to be legal.
   Deputy Director William Kennedy of the Boston-based
Massachusetts Municipal Association agreed. When people perform
statutory duties, they sign with their statutory title, he said,
even if their town title is different.
   Kennedy added, however, that he doesn't know if that is
tradition or law.
</TEXT>
