<FILEID>AP-NR-05-24-88 2007EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-StockMarketReport     05-24 0578</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Stock Market Report,580</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Proxmire Chides White House On Stock Market Report, Promises Bill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chairman of the Senate Banking Committee
scolded Reagan administration officials Tuesday for offering
``pitiful'' solutions for the stock market's problems, and promised
to press ahead with his own bill.
   Committee Chairman William Proxmire, D-Wis., used a hearing
called by his panel to lecture the authors of the White House's
latest report on last fall's market crash.
   ``The progress that you have made is pitiful,'' he said of the
group's two months of work.
   ``This working group has been the regulatory equivalent of the
North Carolina Tar Heels basketball strategy called the four
corners offense,'' Proxmire said. ``Pass the ball around and run
out the clock. Never shoot, just stall and run out the clock.''
   The high-ranking administration officials who produced the
report, which was released May 16, advanced several mild steps for
soothing the nation's volatile markets and nervous investors.
   They included a call for an hour-long trading halt in the
nation's stock, futures and options markets if the Dow Jones
Industrial Average plunges by 250 points in a single day. Such a
decline has occurred only once: Last Oct. 19's 508-point drop,
which has triggered on ongoing look at the markets' volatility by
the government and Congress.
   Proxmire introduced legislation March 31 that would establish a
committee consisting of the chairmen of the Federal Reserve Board,
the Securities and Exchange Commission and the Commodity Futures
Trading Commission. The committee would oversee issues that affect
all of the nation's markets, such as coordinating margins _ or
downpayments _ exchanged in transactions, and setting up ``circuit
breakers'' to halt trading during emergencies.
   ``My aim ... is to make sure that there is an accountable entity
with both the responsibility and the expertise to make the
decisions on intermarket issues,'' Proxmire said.
   Currently, the CFTC oversees the futures markets, while the SEC
and the Fed share responsibility for the stock and options
exchanges.
   After the hearing, Proxmire told reporters he expected his
committee to send the legislation to the full Senate next month.
   With Congress' schedule abbreviated this year because of the
elections _ and with some lawmakers joining the administration in
opposing strong legislative action on the problem _ it seems
unlikely that any bill will become law in 1988.
   ``It makes it much harder to have the administration opposed,''
Proxmire conceded. ``The president has the veto, and the
administration has influence with many members of Congress.''
   Sentiment on the banking committee toward the need for
legislation seems split, and not along party lines.
   While Sen. Alfonse D'Amato, R-N.Y., said, ``We'd be darned fools
to say that all is well'' with the financial markets, Sen. John
Shelby D-Ala., said, ``A lot of us here ... don't believe you can
legislate investors' confidence.''
   Treasury Undersecretary George D. Gould, who headed the working
group, expressed frustration with lawmakers' criticisms, saying,
``As you know, I have spent my life in the markets, and I would
like a little credit for some of the insights of 35 years.''
   Also writing the report were Fed Chairman Alan Greenspan, CFTC
Chairwoman Wendy Gramm, and SEC Chairman David S. Ruder.
   Ruder has dissented from his colleagues on several points,
arguing that futures margins should be raised and that the SEC
should oversee futures trading. The SEC meets Thursday to fashion
legislative proposals that will be submitted to Congress by next
week.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880524-0195 </DOCNO>
