<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CocaineHeadache     05-24 0193</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cocaine Headache,0199</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lawsuit: Powder That Prompted Arrest Was Headache Remedy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A construction worker has sued Garland and three
of its police officers, alleging he was jailed nearly a month when
his headache powder was mistaken for cocaine.
   Michael Holloway, 37, was arrested on intoxication charges while
visiting his ex-wife in the Dallas suburb in April 1987. He was
charged with drug possession after police said the powder had
tested positive for cocaine, the lawsuit said.
   Holloway said the substance was actually BC powder, an
over-the-counter headache remedy.
   Holloway spent 25 days in the Garland jail before authorities
determined the powder had tested negative upon further examination,
the lawsuit said.
   ``Because of the damage to his reputation and the extreme fear,
frustration, and unshakeable memories of the entire experience,
plaintiff has been in a continual state of fear and depression,''
the lawsuit said.
   Garland Police Chief Jesse Youngblood said police procedures
were followed. An initial test identified the powder as cocaine,
and later testing with more sophisticated procedures determined the
material did not contain the drug.
   The lawsuit, filed Friday in state district court, does not
specify damages sought.
</TEXT>
