<1ST_LINE>r w AM-ObscenityProsecution     05-24 0387</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obscenity Prosecution,390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Suit Filed In Effort To Stop Prosecutions In Four States</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The operator of a mail-order pornography
business filed suit in federal court here Tuesday to stop the
Justice Department from prosecuting him on obscenity charges in
four states.
   Avram Freedberg, owner of Consumer's Marketing Group Ltd. of
Stamford Conn., is seeking an injunction to prevent the Justice
Department's national obscenity enforcement unit from bringing the
charges in federal courts in Mississippi, Indiana, Utah and
Delaware.
   The suit charges that the effort to prosecute Freedberg, his
wife, Rhoda, and others in the four jurisdictions is merely a
campaign to harass the firm and drive it out of business by forcing
it to incur large legal fees.
   ``Although shielded by the specious pretext that they are
enforcing federal obscenity statutes, defendants are unlawfully and
unconstitutionally preventing plaintiffs from enaging in a legal
occupation,'' said Freedberg's motion for a temporary restraining
order.
   ``Defendants simply disapprove of the content of plaintiff's
promotional materials, magazines, and videotapes, and are
unconstitutionally intimidating plaintiffs with multiple
(simultaneous or consecutive) obscenity prosecutions,'' the suit
said.
   The company has stopped nationwide sales and promotions of
sexually orieented material itemized in five grand jury subpoenas
served earlier this year, the lawsuit said.
   The threatened prosecutions have prompted a number of employees
to quit their jobs. The suit said that ``with no work force, CMG
will eventually cease doing business.''
   The planned prosecutions are part of Attorney General Edwin
Meese III's announced efforts to take legal action against
pornography distributors.
   A Justice Department official in Utah told Freedberg's attorneys
that he would be prosecuted for alleged obscenity violations in all
four districts and additional jurisdictions until a felony
conviction was obtained.
   If federal prosecutions were not successful, Freedberg would
face state obscenity charges as well, the suit said.
   Freedberg was offered an opportunity to plead guilty to two
felony counts in Utah to avoid prosecution elsewhere. Freedburg's
wife and company employees might not be prosecuted if Freedberg
pleaded guilty, but prosecutors would still seek a subtantial
prison term for his convictions, the suit said.
   The lawsuit also charged that Package Fulfillment Center, a
company that fills orders for Freedberg's firm, and its president,
Michael Norberto, have been named as a potential target of the
investigations.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
