<FILEID>AP-NR-05-24-88 2013EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SAfrica-Evictions     05-24 0544</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-SAfrica-Evictions,0567</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Says It Will Evict 1,800 Blacks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government said Tuesday it
will begin evicting 1,800 blacks next month from a settlement
adjoining the town President P.W. Botha once represented in
Parliament.
   Civil rights workers say the planned evictions from Lawaiicamp
``signify a return to the brutal forced removals of the past.''
   White officials say the 40-year-old black community is an
illegal, unsanitary squatter camp and its actions do not constitute
a forced removal.
   Lawaiicamp is on the outskirts of George, five miles from a
scenic stretch of Indian Ocean coastline east of Cape Town.
   Botha was elected to Parliament from the George constituency in
1948 and represented it until he became South Africa's president in
1984.
   The government wants to move Lawaiicamp residents to Sandkraal,
which is about a mile further from George and was established four
years ago to be the area's official black township.
   George's mayor, John Rogers, said at a news conference Tuesday
that Lawaiicamp residents had until May 31 to move voluntarily. The
town council plans to apply for eviction orders in court on June 1
and to demolish the 180 remaining Lawaiicamp homes once they are
vacated.
   Rogers said evicted families would be paid compensation and
provided with new homes. About 800 families have already moved from
Lawaiicamp to Sandkraal, and the government claims they enjoy
better services and amenities.
   The mayor said violence would not be used against the residents
resisting eviction but he did not explain how this could be assured
in the face of possible defiance.
   The current Parliament member for George, Hennie Smit, said the
matter ``is being handled in an understanding, sympathetic manner.''
   He said Lawaiicamp is illegal because it is on land designated
for use by people of mixed race. A new mixed-race township is to be
developed on the site.
   Last week, Law and Order Minister Adriaan Vlok accused
anti-apartheid organizations of encouraging Lawaiicamp residents to
resist removal.
   He said Anglican Archbishop Desmond Tutu and other activists
were ``playing with fire'' by stirring up emotions which could ``be
detrimental to public order.''
   In early 1986, the government tried to evict Lawaiicamp
residents but backed off because of legal challenges and stiff
resistance.
   This time, the government says it will not yield. Residents of
Lawaiicamp say they are determined to stay where they are.
   Prominent anti-apartheid clergymen are planning to protest the
government decision this Sunday at a prayer service in George.
Among those scheduled to attend is the Rev. Allen Boesak, a South
African who is president of the World Alliance of Reformed Churches.
   From 1950 to 1983, the government forcibly resettled an
estimated 3.5 million people, nearly all of them black. Botha said
in 1984 that there would be no more forced removals, but critics
say the policy continues under different names, such as ``slum
clearance'' and ``squatter control.''
   Botha said last year that he opposed forced removal ``unless it
is accompanied by the provision of better living conditions.''
   By law and custom, apartheid establishes a racially segregated
society in which the 26 million blacks have no vote in national
affairs. The 5 million whites control the economy and maintain
separate districts, schools and health services.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
