<2ND_LINE>AM-Grapefruit Lead,490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Advocacy Group Contends EPA Allows Too Much Lead in Grapefruit
Juice</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Environmental Protection Agency has
permitted lead concentrations in fresh Florida grapefruit juice 20
times what it permits in drinking water, according to an advocacy
group critical of the agency's pesticide decisions.
   The lead arises from the use of lead arsenate to accelerate the
ripening of grapefruit so farmers can ship them to market in
September and October. Normally, Florida grapefruit would not be
available until November.
   The last federal license to sell lead arsenate was surrendered
earlier this year by the manufacturer, Micro-Flo Co. of Lakeland,
Fla., rather than conduct more tests that EPA said were needed for
its 10-year-old review of arsenic-based pesticides.
   In return for surrendering the license, the company was
permitted to sell remaining inventories. Up to 100,000 pounds per
year have been used recently, enabling growers to earn almost $10
million a year in extra profits by sending fruit to market early,
according to EPA estimates.
   The National Coalition Against the Misuse of Pesticides said it
believed there was enough lead arsenate in Florida distribution
channels to serve growers for another two years.
   ``It is irresponsible for EPA to stand by and allow the
application of this material,'' Jay be treated
firmly, so that he cannot involve non-users and so that his own
drug use ceases.''
   The cry for legalization comes not because Americans want to
accept the costs of drug use but ``because some are afraid we
cannot win this fight and that the cost of maintaining the war
against drugs has become too great,'' Bennett said. ``In too many
places we now have what amounts to de facto legalization of drugs.
   ``If we now legalize drugs we should not deceive ourselves that
education and treatment programs will then be sufficient
effectively to minimize drug use and its consequences,'' Bennett
said. ``That simply won't work.
   ``Legalizing drugs would be so stark a moral surrender in the
war on drugs that it would tear the essential foundation out from
under drug education programs. They would not be effective. And we
cannot expect treatment programs to repair the damage.''
</TEXT>
