<1ST_LINE>r i AM-India-Sikhs     05-24 0259</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-India-Sikhs,0267</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sikh Gunmen Kill 10; Police Slay 4 Sikh Extremists</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sikh radicals killed 10 people in Punjab
state Tuesday, including six members of a Hindu family, and police
killed four Sikh gunmen, Indian news agencies reported.
   Press Trust of India said the Hindu family members were killed
after volunteer guards in Dhariwal village in the Jalandhar
district exchanged fire with six gunmen who arrived on motorcycles.
The village is about 50 miles southeast of Amritsar, the Sikh holy
city.
   One guard and two children were seriously wounded, the agency
said.
   Radical separatists have fought a campaign of murder and terror
since 1982 for a separate Sikh nation in Punjab, a rich
agricultural state in the northwest where the sect has a majority.
Thousands of people have been killed.
   A dispatch from United News of India said police killed four
Sikh separatists Tuesday in two encounters in the Faridkot and
Bhatinda districts.
   Among the victims was Chamkaur Singh, who was wanted by police
for several murders. A cash award of 50,000 rupees ($3,850) had
been posted for him.
   The other killings by Sikh gunmen occurred in the Amritsar,
Gurdashpur and Jalandhar districts.
   Police report at least 1,163 people killed by the extremists in
Punjab so far this year, more than the 1,030 slain in all of 1987.
   Sikhism was founded 500 years ago as an alternative to Hinduism
and Islam. Its adherents make up less than 2 percent of India's 800
million people and claim discrimination by Hindus, who account for
82 percent.
</TEXT>
