<2ND_LINE>AM-Eastern-Continental, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0657,440</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Federal Mediation Begins in Texas Air Labor Dispute</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after 5th graf bgng, `We don't,' to UPDATE
with comment by Continental employee group spokesman saying others
beside pilots participated in the protest</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federally mediated hearings opened Tuesday to
settle a bitter dispute between airline unions and Texas Air Corp.
over whether the company's two subsidiaries _ Continental and
Eastern airlines _ should be considered a single airline for
bargaining purposes.
   The issue is important for the unions because neither pilots nor
mechanics at Continental Airlines are unionized, while both groups
have militant union organizations at Eastern Airlines.
   Texas Air Corp. contends that while it owns both Eastern and
Continental, the subsidiaries remain independent air carriers and
should have separate dealings with labor.
   The first day of hearings before Roland Watkins, a hearing
officer for the National Mediation Board, began as about 120
Continental pilots staged a protest across the street from the
board's headquarters because they have not been allowed to
participate in the proceedings.
   ``We don't want to be railroaded by this,'' complained Rick
Swanson, who has been a Continental pilot for six years and is a
leader in a Continental employee group called ``Continental by
Choice.''
   A spokesman for the group, Carter Smith, said a total of about
400 pilots, flight attendants, reservation clerks, mechanics and
other Continental employees also participated in the various
demonstrations.
   The pilots later marched to the headquarters of the Air Line
Pilots Association where they also set up protest pickets. ALPA,
which represents 40,000 commercial pilots, has led the fight to get
the Continental and Eastern work force under a single bargaining
system.
   In Tuesday's testimony, the pilots union argued that Texas Air
``asserts centralized control'' over both airlines and ``exercises
close control over the management of both Eastern and Continental,
particularly with respect to labor relations.''
   It cited as examples in support of its argument Texas Air's
recent arrangement to provide $22.5 million to Eastern in event of
a strike. The union also noted other joint agreements between the
two airlines in the transferring of assets, the sharing of sales
forces and integration of its frequent flyer programs.
   Joseph Manson, an attorney for Texas Air Corp., sought
unsuccessfully at the beginning of the hearing to have the
proceedings stopped, arguing that the board had no jurisdiction
over the matter.
   ``The unions have one and only one purpose and that is to
destroy Eastern instead of addressing the real problems (at
Eastern)'' Manson said. He called the petition by ALPA and other
unions representing flight attendants and mechanics at Eastern
``another media event.''
   It's not known how long the proceedings before Watkins will
take, but the three-member board has reserved time into late June
for a series of hearings. The board is not likely to consider the
case until mid- or late summer.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
