<2ND_LINE>AM-Gay Rights,0261</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Council Approves Gay Rights Bill</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The City Council has approved a bill that
protects homosexuals from discrimination, ending a struggle that
lasted eight years.
   Mayor Kurt Schmoke, who supported the measure, has said he would
sign the bill when it reaches his desk.
   The bill was opposed by Roman Catholic Bishop William Borders.
   Similar bills have been enacted in New York, Atlanta,
Philadelphia and Washington, D.C.
   For the most part, the final debate on the measure lacked the
intensity and emotion that accompanied the council's earlier
dealings with the proposal.
   The thunderous applause that greeted the 12-7 vote was an
indication of the long struggle to adopt an ordinance to outlaw
discrimination against homosexuals in housing, employment,
education, health and welfare services.
   Similar bills were defeated in 1980 and 1985.
   ``I hope this is the last time we have to address human rights
in this city,'' said Councilwoman Vera Hall.
   Meanwhile, a controversial gay rights bill, which is entering
its 16th year before the Massachusetts Legislature, advanced
Tuesday on the narrowest of committee votes.
   The Senate Ways and Means Committee endorsed the bill to ban
discrimination on the basis of sexual orientation by a vote of 7-6.
   The bill now goes to the Senate's Steering and Policy Committee,
which held the bill for 42 days of its 45-day maximum limit last
year.
   The legislation passed the House and won a majority in the
Senate last year, but then got hung up in a committee.
</TEXT>
