<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel-Soviet     05-24 0385</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Soviet,0397</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Report Says Soviets Will Grant Visas To Israeli Diplomats</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union has agreed to grant visas to
Israeli diplomats for the first time in 21 years and will issue
them after next week's superpower summit in Moscow, three Israeli
news reports said Tuesday.
   Israel radio and television and the Maariv daily said Israeli
and Soviet diplomats reached the agreement at a weekend meeting in
Zurich, Switzerland.
   A Foreign Ministry official, reached by telephone, said of the
reports: ``They are not true.''
   But the official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, confirmed
that meetings took place in Zurich between Nimrod Novick, a Foreign
Ministry political adviser, and Vladimir Terrasov, deputy head of
the Soviet Foreign Ministry's Middle East Department.
   ``There was progress, but it's little and slow,'' the official
said of the meetings. He declined to elaborate.
   Moscow broke diplomatic ties with Israel during the 1967 Middle
East War.
   According to the reports, the Soviets agreed to allow five
Israeli diplomats to travel to Moscow to handle the issuing of
visas to Soviet Jewish emigrants who now are processed through the
Dutch Embassy in Moscow.
   None of the reports gave a date for the visit.
   The reports come at a time when Kremlin leaders are seeking a
greater role in the Middle East, including participation in a
proposed international conference on the Arab-Israeli conflict.
   Israeli leaders are divided over such a conference. Foreign
Minister Shimon Peres, head of the left-of-center Labor Party,
favors it. His coalition partner, Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir of
the right-wing Likud bloc, is opposed.
   Soviet leaders have improved relations with Israel in the last
two years by holding meetings with Israelis abroad and by
increasing the flow of Jewish emigration to the Jewish state.
   Last year, Israel permitted an eight-member Soviet consular
delegation to visit Israel. Some of these diplomats are still
conducting consular duties from the Finnish Embassy in Tel Aviv.
   Shamir indirectly referred to the contacts in remarks to
reporters Tuesday.
   ``I think there is no doubt Israel has all desire and reasons to
live in peace and maintain ties with the Soviet Union,'' Shamir
said. ``We always wanted friendly relations with the Soviet Union,
a superpower, because our (Jewish) brothers live there and we want
to discuss with the Russians their fate.''
</TEXT>
