<DOCNO> AP880524-0208 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-24-88 2050EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-MarinePaint     05-24 0228</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Marine Paint,230</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Passes Bill To Restrict Use Of Boat-Hull Paint</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House on Tuesday passed and sent to
President Reagan legislation to restrict the use of a popular
boat-hull paint that is effective against marine organisms like
barnacles but which poses environmental risks.
   The bill, approved by voice vote, would ban the use of paints
containing organic tin additives on non-aluminum hull vessels less
than 82 feet long. The most widely used additive is tributyltin, or
TBT.
   The measure would permit continued use of such paints on large
vessels and those with aluminum hulls so long as the organic tin
compounds are not released into the water at more than 4 micrograms
per square centimeter a day.
   Paints with organic tin are much more effective against
barnacles and marine algae than copper-based paints, meaning lower
maintenance costs for boat owners. Copper-based paints corrode
aluminum surfaces.
   Releases into the water from copper-based paints become
non-toxic almost immediately, but organic tin additives can remain
toxic for up to six months, according to the House Merchant Marine
and Fisheries Committee.
   Sen. John Chafee, R-R.I., says that England and France have
regulated organic tin marine paints because they have damaged
shellfish beds. He says that while their effects on humans are not
known, high levels of TBT have been found in chinook salmon in this
country.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
