<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Britain-IranArms     05-24 0320</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Iran Arms,0327</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>British Arms Dealers Convicted Of Trying To Swindle Iran</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three Britons who claimed they worked with former
White House aide Oliver North in the Iran-Contra arms deal were
convicted Tuesday of trying to swindle Iran with a fake consignment
of anti-tank missiles.
   A jury at the Old Bailey criminal court rejected their claim of
being part of the American operation and found them guilty of
conspiring to sell Iran 5,000 TOW anti-tank missiles that did not
exist.
   Michael Aspin, 50, the group's leader, was sentenced to six
years in prison. He testified in the 4{-month trial that the CIA
and U.S. Customs Special Investigations Office knew about the deal
for 34 million pounds ($63.6 million) worth of missiles.
   Eric Matson, 63, a retired army officer who later served as a
colonel in the United Arab Emirates, was sentenced to three years
in prison and insurance broker William Harper, 38, got two years. A
fourth defendent, businessman John Taylor, 56, was acquitted.
   The men were arrested after Swiss middlemen acting for the
Iranian buyers became suspicious and called police in 1986 after
having delivered several thousand dollars to Aspin.
   Aspin, who was convicted of gun-running to South Africa in 1982,
claimed he had two meetings with Lt. Col. North at London hotels in
February and September 1985 and said North promised to arrange the
supply of TOW missiles.
   North awaits trial on charges arising from a plan, exposed in
1986, to sell arms to Iran and divert funds from the sales to
Nicaraguan rebels. U.S. hostages in Lebanon were to be freed in
exchange for the arms sales to Iran, according to the plan.
   Judge John Alliott said in passing sentence the Britons had no
connection with Iran-Contra and concocted the story in an attempt
to conceal ``persistent and deliberate fraud.''
   He told Aspin: ``You are a rogue and the mainspring of this
conspiracy.''
</TEXT>
