<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic front-runner Michael Dukakis denounced
President Reagan's veto of a major trade bill Tuesday, saying it
was ``unconscionable'' to oppose requiring advance notice of plant
closings.
   ``Any administration that is willing to give General (Manuel)
Noriega 120 days notice and a plea bargain ought to be willing to
give the American worker 60 days notice before they are thrown out
on the street,'' Dukakis said.
   He was referring to the bill's advance-notice provision and to
reports that the administration is considering dropping drug
charges against the Panamanian leader in order to persuade him to
relinquish power.
   The Massachusetts governor spent Tuesday tending to state duties
in advance of a Wednesday trip to Washington, where campaign aides
said he would pick up endorsements from a dozen members of
Congress, including five senators and a handful of House members
from California. He will also meet with Sen. Albert Gore Jr., a
former presidential candidate who still has nearly 400 delegates.
   The new round of ``super delegate'' endorsements are part of
Dukakis' campaign strategy to line up enough delegates prior to the
June 7 primaries in California, New Jersey, New Mexico and Montana
to guarantee a mathematical lock on the nomination if he wins in
those states.
   Dukakis aides have said the Reagan trade-bill veto would give
him a strong economic issue to use in the expected fall campaign
against Vice President George Bush.
   Massachusetts has a state law that encourages companies to give
90-day advance notice of plant closings and major layoffs. It
includes sanctions against companies that refuse to comply.
   In a campaign statement, Dukakis tied Bush to the veto, saying
Reagan and Bush ``don't understand that for working families who
struggle to pay the mortgage, save for their children's education
and care for their elders, there is nothing more painful than
losing a job.''
   ``I think the president is making a very serious mistake. This
is a good trade bill. It's a responsible bill. It's been passed by
the Congress with broad bipartisan support. ... To veto this bill
because it will give working people and their families 60 days'
notice before they're laid off, seems to me to be unconscionable,''
he said.
   Also on Tuesday, Dukakis urged a legislative committee to
toughen state criminal sentencing guidelines and lengthen the
mandatory license suspension for motorists convicted of drunken
driving.
   The governor arranged to collect a dozen or more endorsements
from members of Congress on Wednesday as he sought to ensure enough
delegate support to clinch the nomination by the time the primary
season ends on June 7.
   Campaign and congressional aides, speaking on condition of
anonymity, said the list includes Sens. Quentin Burdick of North
Dakota, Wendell Ford of Kentucky, Dale Bumpers of Arkansas, John
Breaux of Louisiana and Harry Reid of Nevada. Several members of
the California House delegation also are expected to announce their
support, including Reps. Esteban Torres, Fortney H. ``Pete'' Stark,
Anthony C. Beilenson, Tom Lantos and Leon Panetta, as are a handful
of House members from other parts of the country.
   Officials also said Sen. George Mitchell of Maine is expected to
endorse Dukakis on Friday, perhaps with Rep. Joseph Brennan and
other Maine delegates.
   Also on Wednesday, Dukakis will meet privately with defeated
rival Gore, whose press spokesman, Mike Kopp, said the meeting was
scheduled at the request of Dukakis.
   ``There are no plans for an endorsement,'' Kopp said.
   Gore has nearly 400 delegates to the Democratic National
Convention, and he has tried to keep them even though he dropped
out of the presidential race in April following the New York
primary. More than 30 have defected in the past month, according to
an Associated Press count.
   The latest Associated Press delegate count has Dukakis with
1,668, leaving him 413 short of the 2,081 needed for nomination.
   Dukakis' remaining Democratic rival, Jesse Jackson, has
complained that Dukakis is unfairly padding his delegate lead with
super delegates _ party leaders and elected officials who by virtue
of their positions are delegates to the Democratic National
Convention.
   But Dukakis aides said they planned to step up their efforts to
get super delegate endorsements to make it certain that Dukakis
locks up the nomination with the final primaries, when 466
delegates will be chosen.
</TEXT>
