<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Pakistan-Missile     05-24 0353</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pakistan-Missile,350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pentagon Dismisses Report on Pakistan Missile Test</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Defense Department on Tuesday dismissed a
published report that Pakistan had test fired a missile capable of
carrying a nuclear warhead.
   ``I certainly don't have any evidence (of that), and all the
people I've talked to report likewise,'' said Dan Howard, the
Pentagon's chief spokesman, when asked about the report in The New
York Times.
   ``There is no indication, evidence or otherwise that the Paks
have done anything like that.''
   The Times reported Tuesday it had been told by a Pakistani
source with close ties to the government that a missile was
launched at a test range in the Thar Desert on April 25, and that
it was capable of reaching the Indian cities of Bombay and New
Delhi.
   The newspaper quoted the source as saying the missile was of
``home design'' but produced with the help of Chinese experts. It
said a Reagan administration official, who asked not to be
identified, confirmed that such a test firing had been conducted.
   Pakistan is widely reported to have the capability of building
nuclear weapons, or to be close to it. Such reports have been
circulating since late April, when India announced it had developed
a long-range missile.
   Neighboring India exploded an atomic device in 1974.
   Moslem Pakistan and Hindu India have fought each other three
times since they became separate nations in 1947.
   Howard reiterated the Reagan administration view that the
Pakistanis ``have not produced any nuclear weapons.''
   A senior Pakistani Defense Ministry official, meantime, speaking
in Islamabad on condition of anonymity, said of the Times report:
``I have no information whether or not such a missile exists.''
   The Times' story appeared as Pakistani Defense Secretary Syed
Ijlal Zaidi opened consultations with U.S. officials here by
visiting Defense Secretary Frank C. Carlucci at the Pentagon.
   Howard said he did not know if the topic of missile experiments
had surfaced during Tuesday's talks, which were said to focus on
U.S. military aid, military cooperation between the two countries
and a review of ``regional political perspectives.''
</TEXT>
