<1ST_LINE>r a AM-HomelessMothers     05-24 0466</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Homeless Mothers,0483</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Homeless Mothers Gather For Retreat</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOY GRAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Helen Geron considers herself resourceful.
As a homeless mother, she has to be.
   ``I take care of my children the best way I can,'' said Ms.
Geron, a mother of six and grandmother of two, and a participant in
a two-week retreat for members of the National Union of the
Homeless.
   ``I'm very resourceful,'' Ms. Geron said. ``I don't let nobody
walk over me. And my kids are that way too.''
   Ms. Geron traveled to Philadelphia from Albuquerque, N.M., last
week. She is one of about a dozen homeless mothers here for the
retreat, all members of the homeless union, an activist group with
chapters in 14 states.
   During the retreat, participants are making plans to for further
takeovers of abandoned housing, a protest tactic that the union has
used in the past.
   Ms. Geron and others attending the retreat said ``safety net''
programs have not helped them solve their problems.
   ``We don't want to be taken care of,'' Ms. Geron said. ``I am a
human being and I need to work.''
   The challenge of caring for children when you can barely care
for yourself is a taxing one, according to several of the mothers.
   ``It's a dual responsibility and a dual fight,'' said Sonya
Terry, 28, who gave birth to a son two months ago while she was
living in a shelter in Detroit.
   ``Michael is my only natural child on this earth,'' she said.
``And, I didn't have a place of my own _ a home for him. I went
through a period of being very depressed.''
   The women said they receive AFDC stipends, but find the money
inadequate for maintaining a family, especially if an eviction,
fire or other mishap leaves them without an apartment or house.
   ``I put the blame for being homeless on myself,'' said LeAnn
Hummel, a 32-year-old from Portland, Ore., whose children are 10
and 13. She said the emotional effect of being homeless knocked her
off balance for a time.
   ``Now my children have been kidnapped _ taken from me by their
father,'' she added. ``I don't know when I will ever see them
again.''
   Barbara Range, 34, said she too has lost custody of her child, a
10-year-old girl, after she first became homeless five years ago.
   ``I lost my self-esteem,'' she said. ``I victimized myself and
abused my child.''
   The life of a homeless woman is harsh even without having to
care for her children, Ms. Hummel said.
   ``There is this area in Portland where a lot of homeless people
hang out,'' she said. ``And the cops come around there and they
treat you like you are nothing. I've been hauled into jail five
times in four months.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
