<1ST_LINE>u i AM-GulfRdp     05-24 0594</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gulf Rdp,0612</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iran Claims Iraqis Bomb Village, Iraq Threatens New `War Of
Cities'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED BLANCHE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iraq threatened on Tuesday to resume
long-range missile attacks, which could set off another round of
the ``war of the cities'' that has killed thousands of people.
   Iraq said it would resume missile barrages if Iran did not stop
shelling border towns.
   ``The Iranians ... bear full responsibility if they attack our
cities,'' declared Abdul Jabar Mohsen, chief Iraqi military
spokesman. ``Such attacks will not go unpunished.''
   Iran claimed Iraqi warplanes bombed a northwestern border
village near Sardasht, killing one civilian and wounding 10. On
Monday, the Iranians threatened retaliation if Iraq continued
attacks on towns.
   Vernon A. Walters, U.S. ambassador to the United Nations, was
touring the region and met with Sultan Qaboos of Oman, which shares
control of the Strait of Hormuz with Iran. The strait is the only
sea route to and from the Persian Gulf.
   Baghdad's official Iraqi News Agency said Iraqi gunners shot
down an Iranian F-5 fighter-bomber Tuesday over Iraq's battered
southern port of Basra.
   In recent days Iran has been attacking Iraqi positions near
Basra, which has been the target of several Iranian thrusts across
the southern border since the war began in September 1980.
   The Iranians denied losing any of their dwindling supply of
U.S.-built F-5 jets and claimed their ground forces repulsed Iraqi
assaults in the central sector of the 730-mile border warfront.
   Action on the ground has increased recently, breaking a lull
that followed Iraq's recapture April 18 of its southern Faw
Peninsula, which Iran had held since February 1986.
   Tehran's official Islamic Republic News Agency, or IRNA, quoted
the commander for western Iran as saying more than 1,200 Iraqi
soldiers were killed or wounded in a battle Monday.
   It quoted the commander, whose name was not given, as saying the
Iranians repelled attacks by five Iraqi brigades on the border town
of Sumar, 80 miles northeast of Baghdad.
   Dispatches from IRNA claimed 89 civilians were killed and
hundreds wounded by Iraqi air raids and shelling since the last
round in the ``war of the cities'' ended April 21. It claimed 50
people were killed by a chemical attack May 20 on the northern town
of Paveh.
   IRNA also said 12 people were killed and 95 wounded when Iraqi
planes dropped chemical bombs last weekend on Ney, in the central
sector.
   Iraq says Iran has shelled Basra, the northern provincial
capital of Suleimaniyeh and other border towns 26 times since April
21. It has not given casualty figures.
   Thousands of civilians were killed in missile, air and artillery
attacks from Feb. 29 to April 21, the last major exchange in the
war on civilians that has been going on intermittently since 1984.
   Iran reported 1,700 civilians killed and 8,500 wounded but
diplomatic sources said the actual number of casualties probably
was double that. Iraq has not been exact, but reported hundreds of
civilian casualties.
   Walters visited Israel, Syria, Iraq and Kuwait before arriving
in Oman. He has reiterated U.S. determination to implement a U.N.
cease-fire resolution.
   He said American efforts include pushing for a follow-up
resolution that would impose an arms embargo on Iran if it does not
comply with the first measure.
   Iraq says it will abide by the resolution, which the Security
Council passed unanimously last July, if Iran does the same.
   Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini's regime says no truce is possible
until Iraq is designated the aggressor. Iraq invaded Iran in
September 1980 after several border skirmishes.
</TEXT>
