<1ST_LINE>r w AM-HouseGOP     05-24 0267</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-House GOP,260</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Republicans Cite Autocratic Democrats, More Frivolous Bills in
House</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican leaders complained Tuesday that the
House is becoming more autocratic and legislation less substantive
as Democratic leaders increasingly bypass the normal legislative
process.
   ``If this were a republic in Central America, we'd be talking
about sending aid to restore democracy,'' said Rep. Lynn Martin,
R-Ill.
   House Minority Leader Bob Michel, R-Ill., and other GOP leaders
released new statistics showing that while the total number of
bills has remained about the same in the past decade, more and more
of them are commemorative or other non-substantive measures.
   In the current two-year Congress, the 100th, more than 47
percent of all the bills passed have been commemoratives. In the
95th Congress, it was just 9.5 percent.
   At the same time, more and more bills are brought before the
House with restrictive debate rules that limit amendments. And
about 40 percent of all House bills are not processed by House
committees, compared with virtually all a decade ago.
   ``We see a less thoughtful process, sloppier laws, declining
productivity and an emphasis on the frivolous as against the
substantive,'' Michel said.
   Rep. Dick Cheney, R-Wyo., the chairman of the House Republican
Conference, pointed his remarks at Speaker Jim Wright, D-Texas.
   ``It's a speaker who will not let the House proceed unless he
can dictate the outcome,'' Cheney said.
   Wright repeatedly has fought Republican efforts to stymie
Democratic initiatives by imposing the restrictive procedures. The
Democrats say the procedures are needed because Republicans are not
willing to allow the majority party to act its will.
</TEXT>
