<HEAD>Two Plead in Howard Beach Case; Five Defendants Left</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY McSHANE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A defendant in the Howard Beach racial assault
case pleaded guilty Tuesday to riot charges shortly before a judge
unsealed documents revealing another youth had admitted the same
crime at a secret hearing last week.
   Salvatore DeSimone, 20, entered his plea at an open session in a
Queens Criminal Court conference room before jury selection for the
remaining five defendants in the case resumed Tuesday morning.
   DeSimone, accompanied by his parents and attorney Augustus
Agate, also pleaded guilty to a charge of criminal facilitation for
driving members of a white gang to a confrontation with three
blacks on Dec. 20, 1986. The unsealed transcripts showed
co-defendant Harry Buonocore pleaded guilty to a riot charge last
week.
   Michael Griffith, 23, was killed in the 1986 incident after he
was struck by a car on the Belt Parkway.
   Buonocore's plea was entered at a secret proceeding before state
Supreme Court Justice Thomas Demakos, who then issued a gag order
regarding the session. On Monday, a four-judge panel of the state
Appellate Division ruled unanimously in favor of a motion by The
New York Times to unseal the transcript of the May 19 proceeding.
   The panel said Demakos is prohibited from excluding the press
and public from any future plea proceedings in the case.
   Buonocore, 19, and DeSimone will receive youthful offender
status insuring neither will be jailed, under the terms of their
pleas. Both face five years probation and 200 hours of community
service on their pleas; DeSimone will be sentenced June 27.
   It was unclear whether Buonocore will have to testify against
the remaining defendants, but DeSimone's plea insures he will not
have to, said Agate.
   ``If he is subpoenaed, we have not waived our Fifth Amendment
rights. ... He does not have to testify in this trial,'' Agate
said. Buonocore's attorney, Edward M. Rappaport, was in court
Tuesday and unavailable to comment on whether his client would
testify.
   The two plea bargains surprised defendant John Saggese, who
reasserted his innocence in the case.
   ``I'm not guilty of riot. I don't think Sal is guilty,'' said
Saggese. ``I couldn't have done it. I don't think anyone should
have plea-bargained at all.''
   Saggese, James Povinelli, Thomas Farino and William Bollander
are charged with riot in the case. A fifth defendant, Thomas
Gucciardo, is additionally charged with attempted murder and two
assault counts for attacking another black man that night.
   Jury selection is expected to take several weeks.
</TEXT>
