<HEAD>Wife, Daughter Express Sorrow to Daronco Family</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WHITE PLAINS, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The woman whose father killed a
federal judge in Pelham and then shot himself to death says she
wants the judge's family ``to know I ache for them.''
   ``It's just so hard,'' said Carolee Koster, 38, in her parents'
mobile home in Pennsylvania. ``There are so many things all jumbled
together.''
   Miss Koster and her mother, Mary, spoke with Gannett Westchester
Newspapers on Monday.
   Mrs. Koster, 66, who was married to Charles Koster for 45 years,
echoed her daughter's feelings.
   ``I'm sorry for that family, as I'm sorry for this family,'' she
said.
   As the Kosters sat inside with the windows closed as the
temperature neared 90 degrees, they spoke of being trapped by the
events that began with Saturday's shooting, by both the unwelcome
attention and the horror of what had happened.
   ``We have to get out of here,'' Carolee Koster said.
   Authorities said her father, a former New York City policeman
embittered by U.S. District Judge Richard Daronco's ruling against
Miss Koster's sexual harassment and job discrimination suit,
mortally wounded the judge in his Pelham garden and then shot
himself in the temple. The men were found dead a few feet apart.
   Lester D. Weiss, who lives in a mobile home next door to the
Kosters, remembered Charles Koster as a friendly man who minded his
own business.
   ``We're a little shocked. He used to come out every morning when
I was out and say, `Good morning,''' he told reporters. ``He must
have had it all inside.''
   Tom Miller, whose brother Scott owns the trailer park, was also
shocked. ``It was just a surprise to me. He seemed like a nice guy.
Everybody has their limits. Something must have snapped _ all the
pressure and everything. Something must have happened.''
