<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Israel 1stLd-Writethru a0696 05-24 0662</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0696,0680</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shamir Wants Early Elections; Arab Killed</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: UPDATES throughout with Palestinian killed, other detail</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ALLYN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir said Tuesday that
elections should be held early to end divisions that cripple the
government during the Arab uprising.
   Soldiers shot another Palestinian dead in the Gaza Strip.
   Arab reports said soldiers shot and killed Saadi Sharhy, 52,
while searching his home in the Bureij refugee camp in the occupied
Gaza Strip. The army said he attacked a soldier, who opened fire.
   A nurse at the Ahli hospital in Gaza City said Sharhy was dead
on arrival with a gunshot wound in the chest. Speaking on condition
of anonymity, she quoted Sharhy's relatives as saying soldiers who
searched the home were accompanied by Israelis in civilian clothes.
   Army spokesmen said the trouble in Bureij occurred shortly
before 10 p.m., when a nightly five-hour curfew takes effect.
   At least 195 Arabs have been killed since violence began Dec. 8
among the 1.5 million Palestinians in the West Bank and Gaza Strip,
which Israel has occupied since capturing them from Jordan and
Egypt in the 1967 war. An Israeli soldier and a Jewish settler also
have been killed.
   Army and hospital officials said soldiers shot and wounded a
28-year-old Arab on Tuesday during disturbances in Beit Fakir, near
the West Bank city of Nablus.
   Shamir, who leads the right-wing Likud bloc, said he wanted to
move up elections set for November to prevent ``public
nervousness'' over splits within the coalition government.
   His partner and rival in the tenuous coalition government,
Foreign Minister Shimon Peres of the center-left Labor Party,
opposes early elections.
   Shamir, visiting Yoqneam in northern Israel, told reporters:
``We have four months until the elections. If it were possible to
cut it short, it would be worthwhile to gain time and to prevent
public nervousness.''
   Shamir's spokesman, Yossi Ahimeir, said the premier wants early
elections because the government is paralyzed by policy differences
between Shamir and Peres.
   ``The government is neutralized, cannot advance toward anything,
it cannot take any major decisions because Shimon Peres has put the
whole world against us, unless we give in to the international
conference idea and give up the occupied territories,'' Ahimeir
said.
   Peres advocates an international peace conference to help solve
the Arab-Israeli conflict. Shamir says such a forum would put
pressure on Israel to make territorial concessions.
   Likud representatives said they had planned to submit a bill to
the Knesset on Wednesday proposing elections in August but dropped
the plan when it did not gain enough support from other parties, a
Shamir aide said.
   Recent public opinion polls indicate Likud would be most likely
to form Israel's next government.
   The latest poll published May 13 by the daily Yediot Ahronot had
the Likud and other right-wing parties winning 61 seats in the
120-member Parliament.
   Observers including political scientist Yitzhak Galnoor of the
Hebrew University and pollster Hanoch Smith have said the polls
reflect a hawkish public mood stirred by the Palestinian rebellion.
   A military court in Nablus began the trial Tuesday of a
Palestinian woman, Muneira Daoud, who is accused of stoning and
seriously injuring a Jewish settler.
   According to the court, Mrs. Daoud's action prompted the settler
to fire his gun and accidentally kill an Israeli teen-ager in the
West Bank village of Beita during unrest April 6, Israeli news
reports said. The teen-ager, Tirza Porat, was part of a student
hiking group.
   Israeli news reports said soldiers smashed chairs and desks in
some Arab schools in the West Bank while using the buildings as
bases during the rebellion. The schools reopened Monday after a
closure of nearly four months.
   Olivier Rafowicz, a military spokesman, said: ``There was
serious damage in some of the schools, but we are taking care of
everything and repairing it.''
   He said soldiers used only 30 of more than 1,194 West Bank
school buildings.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
