<1ST_LINE>r a AM-AbortionRights     05-24 0389</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Abortion Rights,0397</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Abortion Rights Discussed At Abortion Federation Conference</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The number of abortions performed annually
since President Reagan's 1980 election has remained stable at
around 1.4 million, despite the administration's opposition, an
abortion rights advocate says.
   ``They've politicized the issue, but women still need abortions
and always will,'' Barbara Radford, executive director of the
National Abortion Federation, said in an interview Monday.
   The Washington, D.C.-based federation held its 12th annual
meeting in Minneapolis this week. The gathering attracted about 350
people who work in counseling centers, clinics and hospitals where
abortions are performed.
   Radford and others interviewed said that, even though polls show
a strong majority of Americans believe abortion should be legally
available, the issue is far from settled. One of the key elements
in the struggle, she said, is equal access to abortion for the
poor, young women and residents of rural areas.
   ``It's a common scenario,'' she said, speaking of the St.
Paul-Ramsey Medical Center where anti-abortion picketing was a
factor in the board voting in March to ban elective abortions. That
decision is on hold, however, pending review by the hospital's
parent board.
   Abortion rights advocates also are watching for a ruling from
the U.S. 8th Circuit Court of Appeals on Minnesota's 1981 law
requiring both parents of a minor girl to be notified before she
can obtain an abortion.
   The law, which also allows girls to seek a state judge's
approval instead of her parents', was found unconstitutional by
U.S. District Judge Donald Alsop five years after its passage and
is being reviewed by the full appeals panel.
   In other matters, convention delegates heard about a new oral
drug called RU 486 that acts to prevent a fertilized egg from
implanting in the uterus. The drug is expected to become
commercially available in France within a few weeks.
   It will be several years before American consumers will have
access to it, however, predicted Dr. Jane Hodgson of St. Paul,
because of more strict drug approval requirements by the U.S. Food
and Drug Administration and product liability risks facing
pharmaceutical firms in the United States.
   The drug, which women would take if they missed a menstrual
period and had reason to fear a pregnancy, has complications for a
relatively small percentage of patients involving bleeding and
ectopic pregnancies, Hodgson said.
</TEXT>
