<1ST_LINE>r a AM-FEMAOfficial     05-24 0547</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-FEMA Official,0565</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>FEMA Official Removed From Seabrook Project Duties As Requested</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN GALVIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The federal official who had refused to endorse
the evacuation plans for the Seabrook nuclear power plant was
granted his request Tuesday to be relieved of duties concerning the
controversial project.
   Edward Thomas, chief of the Federal Emergency Management
Agency's natural and technological hazards division in Boston, said
his reputation and career had been jeopardized by verbal attacks
against him launched by both Seabrook proponents and staffers on
the Nuclear Regulatory Commission.
   ``This is an issue of judgment that has been turned into an
issue of integrity,'' Thomas said in a telephone interview. ``The
facility administrators and the NRC can't accept that an honest man
can differ with their assessment, and I do.''
   There is an active campaign under way by the utility and some
NRC staff members to portray him as a liar, Thomas charged.
   Thomas entered the controversy surrounding the $5.4 billion
reactor in February, when his superiors overruled his objections to
the state of New Hampshire's proposed plan for an emergency
evacuation of Seabrook-area beaches.
   FEMA must approve a nuclear facility's evacuation plans before
the NRC will issue it an operating liscense.
   ``I'm not anti-nuke, but I think nuclear power needs regulation
and must be well-managed, because there is a potential for
catastrophe there,'' Thomas said. ``I'm not out to sink Seabrook.
I've reviewed and approved six nuclear power plants in New
England.''
   
   Thousands of people flock to beaches in the plant's vicinity
throughout the hot summer months, and Thomas said the evacuation
plan offered no way to help these people if there were an accident
at Seabrook.
   ``We end up with thousands of people who would be unable to be
protected,'' he said. ``People in sight of the plant would be with
no form of protection for hours.''
   A spokesman for FEMA in Washington, Russell Clanahan, said that
agency officials would be testifying about the reasons for FEMA's
reversal of Thomas' findings.
   Thomas said he and Henry Vickers, FEMA regional director, agree
that he cannot carry out his job and respond to his critics at the
same time. Vickers refused comment, but Thomas said he was relieved
of his responsibilities to the Seabrook project Tuesday.
   FEMA is still evaluating the number of personnel and amount of
resources that are provided for an emergency evacuation in the
state's plan. Before being granted his request to be relieved of
his Seabrook duties, Thomas was involved in that evaluation.
   He retains his duties related to emergency plans for the six
other nuclear power plants in New England.
   Thomas said he was disturbed by comments made by Seabrook's
attorney, Thomas Dignan. Thomas quoted the attorney as saying that
if FEMA didn't back down from its original reservations about New
Hampshire's plan, there would be ``blood all over the floor.''
   Thomas said it was a very personalized attack on him, and his
wife took it as a threat on her husband's life.
   Seabrook spokesman Ron Sher said the utility and Dignan would
have no comment on the matter.
   Thomas said that he will defend himself against allegations that
he is biased against Seabrook when called to testify about his
opposition to the proposed safety plan.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
