<FILEID>AP-NR-05-24-88 1912EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Iran-Contra     05-24 0585</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Iran-Contra,580</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Defendants Contend Their Congressional Testimony Can't Be Used In
Court</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lawyers for Oliver L. North and two
co-defendants in the Iran-Contra conspiracy case Tuesday disputed a
prosecution claim that hundreds of statements they made to Congress
were not covered by immunity grants.
   Independent counsel Lawrence E. Walsh was ``completely wrong on
the law'' by claiming that fired National Security Council aide
North, former national security adviser John M. Poindexter and arms
dealer Albert Hakim made numerous statements during last year's
Iran-Contra hearings that could be used as evidence against them,
the defense said in a brief filed in U.S. District Court.
   Walsh ``seeks to punish defendants for responding fully and in
good faith to congressional inquiries, when compelled to do so over
vehement objection, and for relaying to Congress and the nation
what occurred and why,'' the defense said.
   North, Poindexter and Hakim testified under limited grants of
immunity from prosecution. But Walsh contends that hundreds of
statements they made were not covered by so-called ``use'' immunity
because they were not in response to questions posed by the
Iran-Contra committees.
   Walsh offered not to use any of the congressional testimony
during the trial if the court decides other immunity issues in his
favor.
   The defense accused Walsh of trying ``to threaten the court with
a lengthy inquiry into immunized testimony, and then to use that
threat as leverage to strike a favorable bargain with the court.''
   ``This tactic is unseemly,'' the defense lawyers said in a joint
pleading.
   North, Poindexter and Hakim are accused along with retired Air
Force Maj. Gen. Richard V. Secord of conspiring to defraud the
government by diverting U.S.-Iran arms-sale profits to the
Nicaraguan rebels.
   Secord testified without an immunity grant from Congress and
therefore is not part of his co-defendants' attempt to overturn the
indictment on the ground that Walsh's investigation was tainted by
illegal use of immunized testimony.
   In its latest filing, the defense said, ``There is no claim that
defendants uttered a single word, during the course of their
congressional testimony, that was outside the subject matter of the
congressional inquiry.''
   North, Poindexter and Hakim did not waive their Fifth Amendment
privilege against self-incrimination when they ``explained their
answers; or sought to provide useful, related information to be
sure their answers were complete and accurate _ in short, the
`whole truth' they had sworn to provide.''
   The defense urged U.S. District Judge Gerhard A. Gesell to
reject Walsh's argument, which would require the court to perform
the difficult task of determining if each of the hundreds of
statements was protected by the immunity grant.
   These statements, the prosecution contends, includes
Poindexter's testimony that he approved the diversion of funds but
did not tell President Reagan so that he could give the president
deniability if the operation were later exposed.
   They also include Poindexter's statements that during Attorney
General Edwin Meese III's November 1986 investigation, Poindexter
destroyed a presidential intelligence finding authorizing CIA
involvement in one 1985 arms shipment to Iran.
   Walsh also claims that North's statements the he destroyed
documents in October and November 1986 could be used as evidence to
prove charges that North obstructed Meese's inquiry.
   In a separate filing Tuesday, Walsh's office said, ``It is clear
beyond doubt'' that North, Poindexter and Hakim waged a ``public
relations battle'' during their congressional testimony.
   ``In utter defiance of the questions put to them, they sought to
win with speeches and arguments,'' the prosecution brief said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
