<1ST_LINE>r i AM-CostaRica-Planes 1stLd-Writethru a0783 05-24 0523</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Costa Rica-Planes, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0783,0535</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nicaraguan Cargo Plane Overdue; Service Normal at Capital Airport</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New grafs 1-7 UPDATE with details on missing plane's crew,
cargo; company comment. Picks up 7th graf pvs, An official ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JUAN MALTES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN JOSE, Costa Rica (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Army helicopters scoured the
Caribbean for a Nicaraguan cargo plane with a crew of six that
failed to arrive on schedule Tuesday at Costa Rica's port city of
Limon.
   The incident came one day after a jetliner ran off the runway
and smashed through a fence while trying to take off at the San
Jose airport on a flight to Miami. All 22 passengers and crew fled
the Boeing 727-100 minutes before it burst into flames.
   Ten people were treated for minor injuries. The plane, of the
Costa Rican airline Lacsa, carried eight crew members and 14
passengers, including seven Americans.
   The cargo plane, belonging to the Nicaraguan government airline
Aeronica, was due at Limon at 6:48 a.m. (8:48 a.m. EDT) Tuesday.
   Aeronica headquarters in Managua said the flight was operating
with six crew members and was carrying 23,000 pounds of cargo. The
nature of the cargo was not disclosed.
   ``We can't say that it crashed, only that it is missing,''
Walter Gutierrez, the airline's deputy manager, said in an
interview. ``The reports we have are that the weather has worsened.
We don't know the cause of the disappearance of the aircraft.''
   Jose Antonio Guzman, the air controller at Juan Santamaria
Airport in San Jose, said the cargo plane started its trip in
Panama City and was to have gone on to Managua, Nicaragua, after
stopping at Limon.
   An official reached by telephone at the airport in Limon said
the missing plane was a four-engine DC-6.
   The official, who identified himself only as Brenes, said two
U.S. Army UH-1 helicopters based in Limon as part of an engineering
unit there since February were helping search for the plane. He
said two small planes and the Costa Rican coast guard also were
looking for it.
   The international airport at San Jose was operating normally
Tuesday, Guzman said.
   Lacsa Flight 628 had been scheduled to stop in Managua before
continuing to Miami on Monday.
   Officials said the jet left the terminal at 4:55 p.m., headed
down the runway and crashed through a fence surrounding the airport
after failing to take off. The plane came to a stop about 600 yards
beyond the fence on a grassy area, where it burst into flames. The
aircraft broke into three sections.
   ``Miraculously, there were no deaths,'' said Juan Manuel
Fernandez, financial vice president of Lacsa.
   ``Thanks to the skill of the pilots, they were able to evacuate
the passengers, just a few minutes before the plane burst into
flames.''
   Co-pilot Armando Rojas told reporters the passengers remained
calm.
   ``With nerves of steel we were able to evacuate all the
passengers,'' Rojas said. ``A few minutes later, maybe five
minutes, the plane burst into flames.''
   Fernandez told reporters the cause of the explosion was under
investigation by officials of Lacsa, Boeing and the Costa Rican
civil aviation agency.
</TEXT>
