<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Ethiopia-Rebels     05-24 0267</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Ethiopia-Rebels,0274</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ethiopian Rebels Claim Major Victory</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rebels in northern Ethiopia claimed
Tuesday they had repulsed an army offensive timed to coincide with
the current African summit in Addis Ababa, killing or wounding more
than 9,000 soldiers in 11 days.
   The Eritrean People's Liberation Front said the battle occurred
May 13-23 when the army tried to recapture Afabet, a town 70 miles
north of the provincial capital Asmara that fell to a rebel assault
in March. The claims were made on the clandestine Voice of the
Broad Masses of Eritrea radio.
   Ethiopia is the host for the Organization of African Unity
summit May 19-28, which also marks the organization's 25th
anniversary.
   According to the Eritrean rebels, President Mengistu Haile
Mariam's government ordered an army offensive in an attempt ``to
appear victorious during the OAU's jubilee celebrations.''
   They said their fighters thwarted a three-pronged drive from
government strongholds in Eritrea's eastern plains. The rebels
claimed 5,300 soldiers were killed, 3,800 wounded and 300 taken
prisoner, and said the 102nd Airborne Division was destroyed.
   Government forces also lost 33 tanks and 28 other vehicles and
rebels captured thousands of rifles, the radio said.
   Independent verification of claims in the northern civil war is
impossible because the Marxist government forbids travel to the
provinces of Eritrea and Tigre, both of which have active
separatist guerrilla movements.
   Ethiopia said Saturday the army had begun an offensive in both
provinces. It had been expected since rebel victories in March in
both provinces.
   Eritrean rebels have fought for 27 years. Those in Tigre went to
war in 1974.
</TEXT>
