<2ND_LINE>AM-Remains Returned,0266</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Remains of Two Marines Killed in Persian Gulf Returned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By THERESA HUMPHREY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DOVER AIR FORCE BASE, Del. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The remains of two Marines
whose helicopter was downed during last month's fighting with Iran
in the Persian Gulf were returned here Tuesday in a brief, solemn
ceremony.
   The remains of Capt. Kenneth W. Hill, 33, of Thomasville, N.C.,
and Capt. Stephen C. Leslie, 30, of New Bern, N.C., arrived on a
C-5A Galaxy from Rhein-Main Air Base in West Germany.
   While a 24-man honor guard stood at attention, the Marine Band
played ``Muffled Ruffles,'' ``Eternal Father'' and a slow rendition
of the ``Marine Hymn,'' while pallbearers carried the flag-draped
coffins to waiting hearses.
   Leslie's parents, Dr. Robert E. and Ruth T. Leslie, looked on,
as Brig. Gen. Richard L. Phillips stood by and extended his
condolences.
   Navy Chaplain Capt. Walter A. Hiskett prayed that their ``heroic
actions inspire us to uphold the traditions they bought with their
lives.''
   The remains are scheduled to leave Dover Wednesday morning for
burial at Arlington National Cemetery outside Washington.
   Hill and Leslie were flying a Marine Corps AH-1 Cobra helicopter
when it went down in the Persian Gulf on April 18, hit by gunfire
or a missile.
   The helicopter vanished on a night reconnaissance mission, a few
hours after U.S. and Iranian naval forces had fought a series of
day-long clashes in the southern Gulf.
   Dover has the largest military mortuary on the East Coast, and
prepares for burial the remains of military personnel killed
overseas.
</TEXT>
