<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Cuba-US     05-24 0273</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cuba-US,0278</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cuban Vice President Considers Bush, Dukakis</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cuba's vice president, Carlos Rafael
Rodriguez, said Tuesday that the era of ``Reaganism'' clearly is
over in the United States, the Cuban news agency Prensa Latina
reported.
   The dispatch from Havana, monitored in Mexico City, said
Rodriguez told local reporters that President Reagan's
``aggressiveness and his threats of using violence against Cuba,
Nicaragua, Panama, have no future in current conditions.''
   He said such policies are even less relevant ``when a certain
global agreement between the United States and the Soviet Union is
being glimpsed on humanity's most crucial problems,'' the dispatch
said.
   Prensa Latina quoted Rodriguez as also saying that many believe
that relations between communist Cuba and the United States can be
re-established only when there is a conservative administration in
Washington.
   ``Bush is that type of leader, but nothing indicates that he is
disposed to take such a decisive step,'' the Cuban vice president
was quoted as saying of Vice President George Bush, who now is
considered certain to be the Republican Party's presidential
nominee.
   Rodriguez said the front-running Democratic candidate for
president, Michael Dukakis, has announced a Latin American policy
that would be radically different from Reagan's and more similar to
development plans proposed by Presidents Franklin D. Roosevelt and
John F. Kennedy.
   ``The conditions are different, and for our part we are prepared
for dialogue, on the base of mutual respect, the elimination of the
(U.S.) blockade and the liquidation of the irritating thorn that we
have in our presence of the military base of Guantanamo on Cuban
territory,'' the Cuban official was quoted as saying.
</TEXT>
