<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     05-24 0570</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0586</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thunderstorms Sweep Southeast, Mostly Fair in West, Plains</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Thunderstorms swept across the Southeast Tuesday, spreading
rain, heavy winds and hail from the Gulf Coast to the Carolinas.
   A cold front also generated thunderstorms from New England to
the Ohio and Tennessee valleys.
   Rain hit southern Texas, south-central Colorado and northwest
Montana, while sunny or partly sunny skies prevailed over much of
the West, the northern and central Plains and the Great Lakes.
   Colder air on the edge of a low pressure system over western
Kentucky replaced warmer, more humid air over the Southeast and
generated showers and thunderstorms from Alabama to the Carolinas.
Showers and thunderstorms also were numerous from the central Gulf
Coast to Florida.
   St. Tammany Parish in extreme southeast Louisiana reported
2-inch hailstones. Golfball-sized hail pelted Claiborne, Ala.,
while Monroe County in northern Alabama was shelled with 1{-inch
hail.
   Nickel- and dime-sized hail peppered several parts of North
Carolina and strong storm winds destroyed a barn near Shelby. There
also was an unconfirmed report that a tornado touched down in Union
County, on the state's south-central border.
   A woman died of injuries received Monday when lightning knocked
a tree limb onto a truck she was driving in Gaston County, also on
North Carolina's south-central border.
   In the six hours ending at 2 p.m. EDT, Montgomery, Ala.,
received over three-quarters of an inch of rain, while just under
three-quarters of an inch was recorded at Cape Hatteras, N.C., and
at Rickenbacker Air Force Base, south of Columbus, Ohio.
   Further north, thunderstorms dropped dime-sized hail on
Springfield and Spencer, Mass., and gusts to 55 mph were reported
at Winthrop, Mass.
   Skies were mostly sunny across the northern and central Plains
and the upper Great Lakes with temperatures mostly in the 60s or
70s, except for some 40s and 50s in the northern parts of the Lakes
region.
   Some clouds developed this afternoon over southern Texas with
showers and thunderstorms developing over the lower Rio Grande
Valley. Conditions were warm and humid with readings in the low 90s.
   Partly cloudy skies were the rule from the Pacific Coast to
Nevada and other parts of the Southwest, with temperatures ranging
from the 50s and 60s in the Pacific Northwest to the mid to upper
90s in the deserts.
   At 3 p.m. EDT, temperatures ranged from 46 degrees at Marquette
and Sault Ste. Marie, Minn., to 98 degrees at Needles, Calif., and
Gila Bend, Ariz.
   Scattered showers and thunderstorms were forecast Wednesday for
northern New England, along the Atlantic Coast, and through much of
the Carolinas into the eastern Gulf Coast and across Florida, with
the heaviest concentration along the South Carolina coast and from
central Florida to southern Georgia. Rain was forecast for the
coasts of Washington and northwest Oregon. The rest of the nation
was expected to be dry with mostly sunny skies.
   Highs were predicted in the 60s along the northern and central
Pacific Coast, and from the Great Lakes and much of the Ohio Valley
to the Atlantic Coast, with highs only in the 50s in central
Pennsylvania, much of New York and Maine. Highs were forecast to be
in the 90s from the valleys of central California to the Rio Grande
Valley in Texas, with temperatures up to 105 degrees in the
Southwest deserts.
   The rest of the nation was expected to have highs in the 70s and
80s.
</TEXT>
