<1ST_LINE>r w AM-BRF-SchoolSuperintendent     05-24 0186</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF-School Superintendent,190</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Acting DC School Superintendent Gets Position Permanently</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Andrew Jenkins on Tuesday became the new
school superintendent for the school system in the nation's capital.
   Jenkins, a 27-year veteran of the District of Columbia school
system, who had been acting superintendent, was appointed to the
post permanently after a three-month search.
   ``I look forward to working with the board of education,''
Jenkins said, ``but most of all, I look forward to working for the
boys and girls and young men and young women of the school
district.''
   Jenkins, 50, had since 1981 been deputy superintendent to
Floretta D. McKenzie who left in February to start an education
consulting firm. The board had passed over Jenkins to hire McKenzie
from outside.
   ``I think Mr. Jenkins has made a very good contribution to
education in the District of Columbia,'' said city councilmember
Hilda Mason, who heads the council's Education and Libraries panel.
``I've known him since I served on the school board, and he'll be
able to continue what Ms. McKenzie started.''
   Jenkins was chosen over former Richmond school chief Richard
Hunter.
