<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Sudan-Rebels     05-24 0387</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sudan-Rebels,0401</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prime Minister Says He Has Offered Peace Proposal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KHARTOUM, Sudan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Sadek el-Mahdi says he has
presented Sudanese rebels with a proposal to end the country's
five-year civil war, a magazine reported Tuesday.
   In an interview with the weekly al-Ashiqa, el-Mahdi said he
outlined the peace plan in a message to John Garang, leader of the
Sudan People's Liberation Army.
   He gave no details of the plan, saying only that it was conveyed
by Foreign Minister Hussein Suleiman Abu-Saleh.
   The government meanwhile said its forces overran 12 rebel
positions in the Upper Nile province near the border with Ethiopia,
killing 300 rebels.
   Major General Abdul-Jalil al-Musharaf, commander of the fifth
infantry division in Kordofan, said that only three government
soldiers were killed in the fighting. Several rebels were taken
prisoner and a large amount of arms and ammunition were captured,
he said.
   He told the official Sudan news agency SUNA the military
operation was part of a plan to cripple rebel activities in South
Korddofan during the approaching rainy season.
   He did not say when exactly the fighting took place.
   Abu-Saleh, the foreign minister, is currently in Ethiopia's
capital, Addis Ababa, for a meeting of the Ministerial Council of
the Organization of African Unity, or OAU. He met on Monday with
President Mengistu Haile Mariam of Ethiopia, whom Sudan repeatedly
has charged with backing the Sudanese rebellion.
   It was not clear whether el-Mahdi's message to Garang was given
to Mengistu for relay or was delivered in some other way. Garang is
known to have a base of operations inside neighboring Ethiopia.
   El-Mahdi told al-Ashiqa that he would be prepared to meet with
Garang if the rebel leader responded favorably to the peace
proposal.
   El-Mahdi, due in Addis Ababa Wednesday for the OAU summit, said
he also will hold talks with Mengistu on bilateral relations.
   Since el-Mahdi took office in 1986, his government has held
several rounds of preliminary peace talks with the rebels in
Britain and Ethiopia. All the sessions failed.
   Garang is a former army colonel educated in the United States.
   His army began fighting five years ago in Sudan's three southern
provinces, where most people are Christian or animist. They demand
autonomy and economic reforms from the government, which is
dominated by the Moslems of the predominantly Arab north.
</TEXT>
