<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Salvador     05-24 0421</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Salvador,0437</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Turns Down Rebel Proposal for Another Round of Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANNIE CABRERA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Jose Napoleon Duarte
and members of the major political parties on Tuesday rejected a
proposal by leftist rebels to hold a new round of peace talks next
week.
   Rafael Moran Castaneda, who belongs to the National Conciliation
Party, said that ``it is not the opportune moment'' to hold
discussions with the guerrillas' Farabundo Marti National
Liberation Front and its political ally, the Democratic
Revolutionary Front.
   He said the political parties need to resolve a dispute over
control of the National Assembly that has prevented installation of
the 60-member congress elected March 20.
   ``This situation must first be overcome in order to be able to
give a show of unity,'' Moran Castaneda said.
   Col. Carlos Figueroa, a member of the rightist Republican
Nationalist Alliance or Arena, said, ``We have decided that first
the assembly has to be formed, and that is where we are going to
work out the peace proposal.''
   The rebels earlier this month offered to resume talks to try to
end the 8{-year war with the U.S.-supported government. An
estimated 65,000 people, the majority of them civilians, have died
in the civil war.
   The guerrilla front is a coalition of five rebel armies. It is
closely allied with the Democratic Revolutionary Front, a loose
federation of leftist parties, groups and student and peasant
unions.
   The rebels called for Monsignor Arturo Rivera Damas, the Roman
Catholic archbishop of San Salvador, to mediate the talks.
   Government and rebel representatives last met Oct. 20 in San
Salvador. Two rounds of talks held in 1984 ended in a stalemate.
   Duarte and representatives of the armed forces and major
political parties began a series of meetings last week aimed at
working out a peace proposal to offer the rebels.
   Moran Castaneda said those meetings will continue.
   The crisis in the legislature centers on who controls the
majority of deputies.
   Thirty deputies of Arena took their seats May 1 and claim to
have constituted the assembly.
   Duarte's Christian Democrats contend that Arena lacks the
majority necessary to install the legislature. The Christian
Democrats were resoundingly defeated in the legislative election,
losing their parliamentary majority.
   The Christian Democrats and the Conciliation party, who claim 30
deputies between them, have formed an informal alliance to block
Arena's control of the legislature.
   One of the Christian Democrats' 23 deputies is claimed by Arena,
which charges the seat was stolen through electoral fraud.
</TEXT>
