<1ST_LINE>r i AM-NewCaledonia     05-24 0422</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-New Caledonia,0433</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soldiers Kills Melanesian</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NOUMEA, New Caledonia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A French soldier on patrol shot and
killed a Melanesian Tuesday on the east coast of this French
Pacific territory, officials said.
   Because of the shooting, a meeting between leaders of the
separatist Kanak Socialist National Liberation Front and a special
government commission from Paris was postponed.
   Officials said the shooting happened about 2:30 a.m. (11:30 a.m.
Monday) near the village of Touho, about 210 miles northeast of
Noumea.
   A statement from the army said the soldiers saw a light, then
discovered two Melanesians, one carrying a weapon. When the other
one made a move toward his pocket, ``a soldier, feeling threatened,
opened fire and mortally wounded one of the two men,'' the army
said.
   New Caledonia, 1,000 miles east of Australia, has been the scene
of sporadic violence since November 1984. The latest upsurge began
in April when Melanesian separatists attacked a police station on
the island of Ouvea, killed four policemen and abducted two dozen
others.
   On May 5, French security forces stormed the cave where the
hostages were being held, killing 19 Melanesians and freeing the
captives. Two soldiers died.
   Last week, Premier Michel Rocard sent a special six-member
mission to New Caledonia to re-establish a dialogue with residents.
   ``No dialogue, no negotiation can take place as long as a state
of war imposed by the armed forces continues,'' said a statement
from the Kanak front's politburo after the meeting was postponed.
   The army said it was investigating the shooting death.
   Native Melanesians, or Kanaks, represent about 43 percent of New
Caledonia's 145,000 residents, and most of them favor independence.
The rest of the population is made up of European settlers, Asians
and Polynesians, most of whom prefer to remain French.
   Meanwhile, in Paris, there was continued controversy over the
May 5 assault on the cave, which the Socialists claim was carried
out under political pressure from the conservative government then
in power to enhance the presidential election prospects of Premier
Jacques Chirac.
   Chirac lost to President Francois Mitterrand, a Socialist.
   Over the weekend, the newspaper Le Monde published excerpts from
a confidential report written by Maj. Philippe Legorjus, head of a
French anti-terrorist squad that made the assault. Le Monde said
Legorjus was critical of government officials for rejecting
negotiations in favor of military action.
   Bernard Pons, the former minister for overseas territories who
was in charge of the operation, said Tuesday the account was
``twisted and deformed,'' and asked that the complete report be
published.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
