<DOCNO> AP880524-0251 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-24-88 2254EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a BC-Theater     05-24 0467</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Theater,0478</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>A Revival of `Romeo and Juliet' Opens Off-Broadway</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: No PMs planned.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL KUCHWARA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Drama Critic</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The ``Romeo and Juliet'' which opened Tuesday at
off-Broadway's Public Theater may not be the most riveting of
revivals, but its lack of excitement can't be blamed on the actors
who play Shakespeare's star-crossed lovers.
   Peter MacNicol and Cynthia Nixon bring a passion to their roles,
a conviction and sense of purpose that is missing from the rest of
this diffuse production, mismanaged by director Les Waters.
   The pint-sized MacNicol, who would seem to be an unlikely
leading man, brandishes a boyish enthusiasm in keeping with Romeo's
impulsiveness. He's quick-tempered, argumentative and ardent in his
pursuit of Juliet. The play's inevitable tragedy seems logical
given the actions of this most emotional of Romeos.
   Miss Nixon is a radiant Juliet. She matches MacNicol in
intensity. What's more, her voice is better equipped to handle the
poetry, and she gives the language its due.
   When the two lovers are on stage together, the play exerts
interest if not a complete fascination. Unfortunately, there's the
rest of Verona and all those feuding Montagues and Captulets to
watch and worry about.
   What Waters has assembled is a polyglot cast and he imposed no
discernible sense of style. The accents range from Brooklyn to
Dublin and points in between. The acting at times seems more
suitable for ``West Side Story'' or, in one case of disastrous
overplaying, ``La Cage aux folles.''
   The actors are at sea. Those who sink include an affected
Courtney B. Vance who flounces his way through the role of
Mercutio; Milo O'Shea who turns Friar Lawrence into a cardboard
Barry Fitzgerald; Anne Meara who substitutes grimaces for emotion,
and W.B. Brydon's Capulet who bullies and bellows his way through
the play, spraying the other actors and everyone sitting in the
first row.
   The actors who succeed, particularly Peter Francis James as
Benvolio and Bradley Whitford as Paris, do so because their
performances are low-key and serve the story, not themselves.
   Heidi Landesman has designed an odd setting, a white, high-tech
balcony that wouldn't look out of place in a Soho loft. It cuts
across a large crumbling red column that suggests a decaying and
corrupt Renaissance society. The two ideas don't quite mesh.
   The exuberant sword fights were devised by B.H. Barry, and they
are models of stage fencing, particularly Romeo's unnerving battle
with Tybalt.
   ``Romeo and Juliet'' is the third production in the Public
Theater's Shakespeare marathon. The theater will present all 36 of
Shakespeare's plays during a six-year period.
   In quality, Waters' production falls somewhere between the
Public's exotic and entertaining ``Midsummer Night's Dream'' and
its dismal, all-star ``Julius Caesar.'' This ``Romeo and Juliet''
can be savored for its lovers only.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880524-0252 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-24-88 2254EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SriLanka     05-24 0266</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sri Lanka,0273</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tamil Rebels Kill Eight Indian Soldiers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tamil rebels killed eight Indian
soldiers in northern Sri Lanka and suffered 20 to 25 casualties
themselves, Indian diplomats said Tuesday.
   The diplomats cannot be identified under briefing rules.
   They said six Indian soldiers, including an officer, were killed
and all the Tamil casualties occurred when the Indians raided a
rebel hideout on Monday near Mullaitivu town, 120 miles northeast
of Colombo.
   They did not know how many of the 20-25 Tamils were killed and
how many wounded.
   A bomb explosion on Tuesday killed two Indian soldiers and
wounded two at Palali village, 12 miles northeast of Jaffna town,
the diplomats said.
   The deaths raised to at least 441 the number of Indian troops
killed in Sri Lanka since October, when the troops began an
offensive against Tamil rebels.
   More than 50,000 Indian troops are in Sri Lanka under an accord
signed in July 1987 by India and Sri Lanka to end the Tamil
separatist guerrilla war for a homeland in the north and east of
the Indian Ocean island nation.
   The peace pact has been rejected by the most powerful of the
Tamil groups, the Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam.
   The agreement grants some autonomy to the Tamil minority in
exchange for a surrender of arms by the rebels.
   Tamils, who are mostly Hindus, make up for 18 percent of Sri
Lanka's 16 million people. The Sinhalese, who are Buddhists,
account for about 75 percent.
   The Tamil say the Sinhalese, who control the government and the
military, discriminate against them.
</TEXT>
