<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Mexico-Police     05-24 0342</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mexico-Police,0350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ten Top Police Dismissed; Prosecutor Says Corruption Won't Be
Tolerated</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SOLL SUSSMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jorge Obrador Capellini began work Tuesday as
Mexico City's acting police chief following the dismissal of 10 top
police commanders due to allegations of a torture death.
   The Federal District attorney general, Renato Sales Gasque, said
at Obrador Capellini's swearing in ceremony late Monday, ``We will
not tolerate acts of corruption nor any act that could affect the
credibility that the community must have in the judicial police of
this city.''
   Earlier Monday the firing of Jesus Miyazawa, director of the
city's judicial police; five deputy directors and four commanders
was announced in connection with an investigation into the death of
a police official in the adjoining state of Mexico.
   The government news agency Notimex quoted Sales Gasque as saying
the dismissals occurred because of acts ``against the dignity of a
person.'' It said the attorney general would give details at a news
conference this week.
   Authorities said Pablo Estanislao Aguilar Alcala, a judicial
police commander in the state of Mexico, was tortured to death last
week, possibly in a revenge killing by members of the Mexico City
judicial police.
   A statement from the attorney general's office said, ``What
happened compels (Sales Gasque) to take this decision, with the aim
moreover of thoroughly restructuring the department of the judicial
police of (Mexico City).''
   The Federal District makes up the core of the Mexico City
metropolitan area of more than 18 million people. It is surrounded
on three sides by the state of Mexico. Many of the area's teeming
slums and rapidly growing suburbs are in that jurisdiction.
   The liberal daily La Jornada said in a front-page editorial
Tuesday that ``the abyss of police criminality causes vertigo'' and
that a full investigation would find that the case prompting the
dismissal was not the only incident of wrongdoing.
   President Miguel de la Madrid, who completes his six-year term
this year, has made ``moral renewal'' in government a cornerstone
of his administration.
</TEXT>
