<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Mexico-Fire 4thLd-Writethru a0832 05-24 0687</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mexico-Fire, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0832,0707</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fire at Oil Tank Farm Forces Mass Evacuation; Danger Ends Later</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New material and editing, UPDATING with possible cause,
residents return home. Adds byline, LaserPhoto number. No pickup</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto ELP1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAM ROSSIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHIHUAHUA, Mexico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fire broke out Tuesday at an oil tank
farm and threatened to ignite millions of gallons of gasoline
before it was brought under control. At least 20,000 Mexicans fled
their homes and one estimate said 200,000 were evacuated.
   A spiral of fire and smoke soared more than 150 feet above the
oil-products storage area of the government oil monopoly Pemex in
the northern residential area of Chihuahua, a state capital in
northern Mexico with 550,000 people.
   But the only casualties reported were a few firefighters with
``light burns.'' Authorities reported that the blaze began at 10:10
a.m. (12:12 p.m. EDT) and was brought under control about eight
hours later.
   At about 8 p.m., residents were told they could return home,
said Francisco Cortez Coronado, a Pemex spokesman.
   He added, ``The causes (for the explosion and fire) are not real
clear. They are still investigating. What we do know is that two
men were soldering to repair a line at the base of the tank and
that the top part exploded.''
   Alfonso Sanchez Gallo, the Chihuahua state government's chief
spokesman, said in a telephone interview Tuesday evening,
``Everything is perfectly controlled and there is no risk that the
fire might spread to other tanks.''
   Flames continued to shoot up and thick black smoke poured from
the 39-foot- high steel tank more than nine hours after the
explosion. The top of the tank collapsed inward from the fierce
heat.
   There were scorch marks from the fire on a tank 30 yards away.
   The government news agency Notimex said the burning tank, with a
capacity of 1,260,000 gallons, contained an extremely light
petroleum while 14 other tanks, with a capacity of 1,040,000
gallons each, held gasoline. Four were ``very close'' to the
burning tank, it said.
   ``There was an explosion but it was very muffled, and then the
fire started,'' said plant foreman Arturo Rubio.
   The initial report from Pemex headquarters in Mexico City said
the blast came at 11:20 a.m. (1:20 p.m. EDT), but Cortez Coronado
later said it was 10:10 a.m.
   The site lies in a densely populated area, about eight miles
north of the city center.
   Estimates varied widely as to how many residents were affected.
   Reporters at the newspaper Novedades de Chihuahua said about
20,000 people left their homes.
   Notimex quoted local fire department commander Mario Perez as
saying soldiers, police and volunteers evacuated more than 100,000
people from a two-mile radius around the plant.
   Later, Notimex gave its own estimate of 200,000 people evacuated.
   Luis Alonso Hernandez, 26, a worker at the plant, said, ``You
could see the flames and black smoke from miles away. And there
were all kinds of accidents in the road. The whole city was
running.''
   Spokesman Sanchez Gallo said officials were concerned that
shooting flames would touch off a nearby gasoline tank, adding ``It
was a question of cooling off the other tank.''
   He reported that the 300 firefighters were draining gasoline
from the 14 other tanks and, ``There is no risk that the fire might
spread to neighboring tanks, since they are being chilled with
strong sprays of cold water.''
   Red Cross radio dispatcher Olga Rojo said efforts to control the
blaze were initially hampered by a scarcity of water. Much of
northern Mexico is suffering from drought this season.
   Chihuahua lies 233 miles south of the Texas border at El Paso.
It is the capital of sprawling Chihuahua state, the largest of
Mexico's 31 states.
   Notimex said plans had called for the storage tanks to be
relocated some months ago, but new facilities have not been
completed. It said area residents had been protesting Pemex's
presence there.
   On Nov. 19, 1984, more than 500 people were killed at an
explosion of storage tanks owned by Pemex in San Juan Ixhuatepec, a
working class neighborhood on the northern outskirts of Mexico City.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
