<HEAD>Cleanup Continues, Neighborhood Returning to Normal After Blaze</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 11,000 people evacuated after a
fire destroyed a metal plating building containing vats of deadly
cyanide were allowed back homes Tuesday.
   No toxic cloud formed and no injuries were reported as a result
of the fire that broke out early Monday at Builder's Hardware
Finishers Inc., a metal plating company that stored 26,000 gallons
of chemicals, including cyanide.
   Authorities evacuated a 14-square-block area around the facility
in northeast Los Angeles until a private disposal company removed
the chemicals under the watch of federal Environmental Protection
Agency officials.
   Emergency shelters were set up at various locations, including a
Red Cross refuge under the bleachers at Dodger Stadium. The last 29
people there munched on doughnuts at dawn and were bused home.
   Schools in the area reopened Tuesday and the neighborhood was
``pretty well back to normal,'' said police Sgt. Charles Willig.
</TEXT>
