<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Nicaragua-Talks     05-24 0471</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nicaragua-Talks,0486</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ortega Insists Peace Talks Be Held In Managua</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FILADELFO ALEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Daniel Ortega late Tuesday
renewed his demand that peace talks scheduled to begin Wednesday
with the Contra rebels take place in Managua.
   The U.S.-backed rebels said they intended to meet with
negotiators of the leftist Sandinista government in the small
village of Sapoa on the Costa Rican border.
   But Ortega said that holding the discussions in Sapoa ``would be
to put the conversations at the brink of breaking off.'' The two
sides signed a preliminary peace plan in the village on March 23.
   Cardinal Miguel Obando y Bravo, the archbishop of Managua who
has been an observer in the talks, said, ``I believe that the
meeting is doubtful'' because the two sides are deadlocked on the
site.
   He said Joao Baena Soares, secretary-general of the Organization
of American States, who has mediated the discussions, called off
his trip to Managua because of the disagreement.
   ``A regrettable impasse has arisen in the conversations,''
Obando y Bravo said.
   Ortega said Baena Soares ``is ready to come to Nicaragua as soon
as it is confirmed that the meeting will take place in Managua.''
   The Contras have resisted holding the three days of talks in
Managua.
   They have complained that during two previous sessions, the
government kept them cooped up in a hotel near the airport on the
outskirts of Managua and refused to let them move about freely in
the capital and meet with domestic opposition groups.
   But Ortega said Tuesday that the Contras would be allowed to
meet with officials of opposition political parties, the Roman
Catholic Church and the opposition newspaper La Prensa. Moreover,
he said, their relatives could visit them at the hotel.
   To meet in Sapoa, the president said, would mark ``a setback in
political terms.''
   ``It would be to accept that all that has been achieved since
the first contacts (late last year) can be lost,'' he said.
   The two sides have been trying since the initial peace agreement
was arranged to work out details for a permanent cease-fire. They
agreed on a 60-day truce to give them time to negotiate a lasting
cease-fire.
   Ortega announced Monday that he would extend unilaterally the
temporary truce, due to run out on May 30, an additional 30 days.
   The peace talks are designed to bring an end to the more than
six years of war between the Sandinistas and the Contras. Ortega
has said the fighting has killed 26,500 people and caused $3
billion in damage to the economy.
   In Washington Tuesday, an aide to House Speaker Jim Wright,
D-Texas, said the Contras planned to offer to lay down their arms
on Sept. 1 as part of a comprehensive peace accord to be presented
to the Nicaraguan government Wednesday.
</TEXT>
