<1ST_LINE>u a AM-KidnappingOrdeal 2ndLd-Writethru a0748 05-24 0629</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Kidnapping Ordeal, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0748,0642</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Couple Charged With Kidnapping, Drugging, Robbing Elderly Woman</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 2 grafs for 5th graf, `Her niece ...' to CORRECT that
sheriff's deputy sted private detective found Mrs. Knight; picks up
6th graf pvs, `I didn't ...' DELETES grafs 10-11, `Barr declined
... kind of vague.' and 17, `Mrs. Knight ...,' and SUBS 18th graf,
``I didn't ...'' to conform.
^By JOHN A. BOLT</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In February 1986, a young couple kidnapped
Lucille Knight and took her to a town hundreds of miles from her
home, federal authorities say.
   The young couple allegedly kept Mrs. Knight passive by feeding
her drugs while they stole her retirement checks and stripped her
assets. They ended up bilking her of more than $100,000, according
to an indictment.
   ``They destroyed everything I had,'' Mrs. Knight, 83, said
Tuesday. ``All I brought back was a car.''
   Mrs. Knight was finally rescued after four months when her
brother, who was also a captive, slipped a letter to a mail carrier.
   Her niece contacted the Catoosa County Sheriff's Department, and
Larry Black, then chief of detectives, said Tuesday he went to the
home and took Mrs. Knight back to the county jail where she was
reunited with her relatives.
   Black, who has since left full-time law enforcement, said he
notified the FBI of the incident.
   ``I didn't report it,'' said Mrs. Knight, although her neighbors
knew what had happened. Mrs. Knight said she wasn't frightened, but
she didn't trust Louisiana law enforcement authorities.
   Terry Lee Barrett, 29, and Alice Virginia Barrett, 31, were not
arrested until Saturday in New Orleans, and U.S. Attorney Robert
Barr said Tuesday the couple is being held on $100,000 bond.
   The Barretts were indicted here May 10 on kidnapping, fraud and
conspiracy charges for allegedly abducting Mrs. Knight from her
trailer park home in Hammond, La., about 40 miles northwest of New
Orleans.
   The indictment, unsealed after the arrests, alleges the Barretts
took Mrs. Knight to a house in Ringgold, Ga., a suburb of
Chattanooga, Tenn., more than 500 miles from Hammond.
   The Barretts allegedly administered Valium, Quaaludes, Percodan
and laxatives while they stole her retirement and Social Security
checks and stripped Mrs. Knight's bank accounts and investments.
   ``They kept me doped up most all the time I was there,'' said
Mrs. Knight in a telephone interview from Hammond. ``I couldn't
stand up; I couldn't walk; I couldn't do anything.''
   The indictment said the couple stole $101,875.72. If convicted,
they could be sentenced to life in prison and fined $2 million.
Barr said they will be arraigned within the next few days.
   Mrs. Knight said Tuesday that her brother, who has since died,
was also held.
   She said she met the Barretts in Hammond through her brother,
and she was rescued when she wrote a note to her niece and her
brother slipped it to a mail carrier.
   ``I didn't know they had taken everything I had'' until Black
took her from the Barretts' clutches, said Mrs. Knight. She
returned to Hammond and has been living there ever since, and said
she has suffered no lingering effects from the drugs.
   She lives on Social Security and retirement checks from
California, where she was a hospital worker.
   Mrs. Knight said she and her husband moved from Oxnard, Calif.,
to Louisiana in 1977, but he died two years later and ``I got stuck
here. I don't need to be here at all. I need to be on the West
Coast.
   ``I just live around here wondering from day to day what's going
to happen to me. I try to stay in my trailer and go when I have to
go, (but) I have nowhere to go, nowhere I want to go.''
</TEXT>
