<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A ranking official said Tuesday the Communist
Party may limit leaders to two five-year terms, ending the
perpetual tenure that cements personal power, but he did not
indicate it would apply to Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   ``This is a big step in the development of intraparty
democracy,'' said Karl Vayno, party chief for the republic of
Estonia.
   Gorbachev has said he favors restrictions on tenure. Terms for
party leaders now are unlimited and longevity is a tool officials
at the local, retional and nation levels use to build power and
privilege.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sailors searching a swamp near the
airport in the seaside city of Cartagena on Tuesday captured a
hijacker who commandeered a jet across the Americas and demanded
$100,000 and an audience with Mother Teresa.
   The navy said Gonzalo Carreno Nieto was found hiding in mangrove
roots about 300 yards from a Cartagena airport runway, still
clutching the toy grenade he had used to hijack an Avianca airlines
Boeing 727 on Monday morning while on a domestic flight from the
drug capital of Medellin to Bogota.
   The hijack began shortly after 9 a.m. when Carreno diverted the
plane back to Medellin, where he freed all 128 passengers and three
flight attendants. He then ordered the cockpit crew into the sky on
a trip that took the aircraft to Panama, where it was refueled,
then to the island of Aruba off Venezuela and back to Colombia when
the pilot persuaded him they couldn't make it to Cuba.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The natural protein interferon, combined with
standard chemotherapy drugs, shows promise in controlling multiple
myeloma, a lethal form of bone cancer, researchers said Tuesday.
   ``We finally have a leg up on arresting the natural progression
of the disease and producing patients who are alive at five years,
which has been a rarity,'' said Dr. Martin M. Oken of the
University of Minnesota.
   His research is part of a new effort by scientists to find a
role for interferon by combining it with the drugs that have long
been used to attack cancer.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic Lt. Gov. Leo McCarthy is
trailing in the polls and in fund raising, but he has one thing in
his favor as he seeks to unseat Republican Sen. Pete Wilson this
year _ ``The Jinx.''
   For more than 30 years, no one has been re-elected to the Senate
seat Wilson holds. Incumbents have died, stepped down or been
defeated and descended into political oblivion. By contrast,
Democrat Alan Cranston is flourishing in his fourth term holding
down the state's other seat.
   ``Everybody talks about `The Jinx,''' said Craig Schmidt, a
Wilson aide. ``But this is the year `The Jinx' will be broken.''
Wilson, not surprisingly, agrees: ``I think it's nonsense, a myth.
We're going to prove it's not true.'
</TEXT>
