<FILEID>AP-NR-05-24-88 1129EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a e PM-APonTV-HealaNation Adv25   05-24 0833</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AP on TV-Heal a Nation, Adv 25,0848</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv25</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Wed PMs, May 25, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>TV Movie Depicts Fight to Build Vietnam Veterans Memorial</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It wasn't ego or politics that led Jan Scruggs
to build a memorial to the Vietnam veterans in Washington.
   It was a chance meeting with another veteran at a fast-food
restaurant not long after they had come home. Both had known
another soldier who was killed in Vietnam. Scruggs was haunted by
the fact that neither could remember the soldier's name.
   The scene is part of the movie ``To Heal a Nation'' which NBC
will air this Sunday, appropriately enough on Memorial Day weekend.
It is a different kind of Vietnam movie, about Scruggs' battle to
win a memorial to those who fought an unpopular war.
   Scruggs is played by Eric Roberts, a 1985 Oscar nominee for the
movie ``Runaway Train.'' The movie is based on the book Scruggs
wrote with Joel Swerdlow.
   Since its dedication on Veterans Day 1982, ``the wall,'' as it
is known, has become one of the most popular monuments in
Washington, attracting up to 20,000 visitors a day.
   The unconventional design of the memorial was highly
controversial when it was unveiled _ a low black granite V cut
below ground level that draws visitors into it, then reflects their
images in the shiny surface etched with the names of those who died.
   In the movie, Scruggs receives a letter from a youngster whose
father died in the conflict. The boy encloses $5 his father gave
him to buy a hamburger the day he left. The $5, the letter says, is
to put his name on the memorial.
   ``The names,'' says Scruggs. ``It's got to have all the names.''
   A couple of years later, fellow Vietnam veteran and attorney Bob
Doubek (Scott Paulin) walks into a Pentagon office and tells a
records clerk he needs some information on casualties from the
Vietnam War. Fine, the clerk says. Which ones? ``All of them,''
Doubek says.
   The 58,156 names inscribed on the wall set the Vietnam Veterans
Memorial apart from other monuments, and the names made it
non-political. It is as much anti-war statement as a tribute.
   Scruggs was able to see that need for a symbol that would draw
the nation together. As he says in the movie, ``This is not a
monument. It's a memorial.''
   The movie, directed by Michael Pressman and written by Lionel
Chetwynd, depicts the process that forced Scruggs to break with
some of his fellow veterans and allow a non-military panel to
select an appropriate design. The result was the stark wall
envisioned by 21-year-old student Maya Ying Lin, selected from
1,421 proposals.
   Influential backers of the memorial, including H. Ross Perot,
would not acquiesce until the Memorial Fund agreed to add a
traditional statue of three battle-weary GIs. It is a powerful work
on its own and stands on a rise in front of the memorial.
   ``To Heal a Nation'' is Scruggs' story. A former Army ``grunt,''
he enlisted former officers with fancy law degrees to cut through
the red tape and political resistance that confronted his vision.
But it was Scruggs' determination that got the memorial built _ in
record time, and there on the Mall by the Lincoln Memorial, not off
in some out-of-the-way spot by the side of a highway that the
government tried to steer him to.
   Since Scruggs is the center of the drama, Roberts' performance
is the centerpiece of the movie, and he infuses Scruggs with an
enthusiasm that transcends a sometimes plodding tale.
   Glynnis O'Connor plays Scruggs' wife, Becky, who at first thinks
he should just forget the war and get on with his life, but comes
to realize that he can never get on with his future until this
project reconciles him with his past. Marshall Colt plays John
Wheeler, the lawyer who heads up the Vietnam Veterans Memorial Fund.
   Sen. Charles ``Mac'' Mathias, R-Md., is played by Laurence
Luckinbill as a thoughtful, effective lawmaker who understands not
just the veterans' need for the memorial, but the nation's as well.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Elsewhere in television:
   FAMILY UNTIED _ Next season, its last, will see NBC's ``Family
Ties'' branch out by having Alex (Michael J. Fox) and Mallory
(Justine Bateman) move to New York, says NBC Entertainment
President Brandon Tartikoff. ...
   `NIGHTLINE' ON PBS _ The ``Nightline'' broadcasts from Jerusalem
can be seen June 1 on PBS in a condensed, 2{-hour program
introduced by former NBC diplomatic correspondent Marvin Kalb in
conversation with ``Nightline'' anchor Ted Koppel. The unusual
collaboration between commercial network and public television was
the brainchild of WGBH, the PBS station in Boston. The
``Nightline'' programs ran on ABC the week of April 25. Included on
PBS will be highlights of the unprecedented ``town-hall meeting''
Koppel conducted with Palestinians and Israelis on a panel before a
mixed audience of several hundred.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Wed PMs, May 25</NOTE>
