<FILEID>AP-NR-05-24-88 1130EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a e PM-TV-Molly Adv25   05-24 0777</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-TV-Molly, Adv 25,0794</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv25</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Wed PMs, May 25</NOTE>
<HEAD>Continuing Saga of `Molly' and the Ratings</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jay Tarses, who has lost a string of critically
praised comedies to the network programmer's axe, says he'll
probably quit TV if his last remaining show, ``The Days and Nights
of Molly Dodd,'' is canned by NBC.
   ``Molly'' moves tonight to a new time period, on Wednesdays, in
a last-ditch effort to avoid cancellation.
   Tarses had learned only recently that ABC had canceled his other
show, ``The `Slap' Maxwell Story.'' Earlier, NBC announced a fall
schedule with no mention of ``Molly Dodd,'' leaving faint hope it
will return after this six-week run is over.
   ABC's decision didn't particularly surprise Tarses, who wasn't
happy with the way ``Slap'' was going. But, he said, ```Molly'
shocks me. I can't deal with it. Whenever I think about it, it just
puzzles me so much, I just don't get it. We keep passing whatever
tests there are, and it doesn't seem to matter to Mr. T.''
   Mr. T is Brandon Tartikoff, president of NBC Entertainment. He
maintains that ``Molly Dodd,'' is ``an interesting show'' but not
necessarily a ``commercial'' show.
   Tarses says that since NBC has become the No. 1 network, ratings
are more important than anything else.
   ``They have `No. 1' parties over there,'' he joked. ``They put
on their devil outfits and dance around a bonfire and throw people
with college educations into a pit or something.''
   ``Molly'' made its debut in the spring of 1987 and got high
ratings. But it was off the air for a year before NBC could find a
new time period for it. It went back in March in the hit-laden
Thursday-night lineup, but Tartikoff yanked it after a few weeks
because it didn't rank in the top 10, only the top 13. ``Night
Court,'' the show it replaced temporarily, had ranked in the top 10.
   In a news conference last week after announcing the fall
schedule, Tartikoff held out some slight hope for the show.
   ``Wednesday night at 9 o'clock, if it were to deliver the same
kind of shares that it was getting on Thursday night, dropping some
10 and 12 points off of `Cheers,' that would be a hit for us,''
said Tartikoff.
   ``If it gets a 25 share off of 37 on Thursday night, that is
what I consider viewer rejection of the show ... and giving up too
many rating points on a night when we could dominate by simply
putting `Night Court' back there.''
   ``Molly'' will lead into ``Cheers'' tonight, but then will be
paired with another half-hour comedy, ``Sara,'' a long-canceled
series that starred Geena Davis and Bronson Pinchot as lawyers.
Both have gone on to other projects.
   Tarses thinks it unlikely ``Molly'' will get the 16.0 rating it
had been getting on Thursday nights after it moves to Wednesday,
where the previous show in the time period, the hour-long ``Highway
to Heaven,'' was getting much lower ratings.
   The rating is a percentage of 88.6 million U.S. homes with
televisions, and it largely determines how much the network can
charge for a commercial.
   ``He (Tartikoff) seems to be so concerned with statistics and so
concerned with being No. 1 and pulverizing the opposition, he may
be disregarding some barometers that are very clear,'' said Tarses.
``That there are shows of quality that do have an audience, maybe
not a 35-share audience, but a bunch of people who are being
deprived of some television shows because of numbers that I don't
believe are really true.''
   Tartikoff last week held out slim hope for ``Molly'': ``If there
is that loyal core that will follow this show almost anywhere, if
they show up anywhere close to the numbers it had on Thursday
night, this could be, God forbid for Jay Tarses, he might actually
have a commercial show on his hands. I don't know what he'd do with
it.''
   Tarses has had a run of heartbreaks, such as ``Open All Night''
and ``Buffalo Bill,'' which heco-created with Tom Patchett. Now
``Slap'' is gone, and ``Molly'' may be, too.
   ``I don't want to go through this any more,'' Tarses said. ``I
did good work. `Molly' and `Slap' were good shows. We've spent a
lot of time, a lot of care, and the result is that in the end you
have rejection, and I've been there before with shows that were
good, too. I don't know how many times I have to go through it.
There are other things I could do in this business.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Wed PMs, May 25</NOTE>
