<FILEID>AP-NR-05-24-88 2338EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a PM-BusinessMirror Adv25   05-24 0585</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Mirror, Adv 25,0600</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 25</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release PMs Wednesday May 25</NOTE>
<HEAD>Quality and Service: Promise or Practice?</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also on financial wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The two most commonly used words in business
advertising probably are quality and service. In practice they
might be among the most neglected.
   This dichotomy still shows in surveys of American corporate
practices, even though the consequences are well understood by
management and labor, having caused them serious problems in the
past.
   Further evidence comes in an analysis of 105 responses to a
survey of Fortune 500 companies by Organizational Dynamics Inc., a
management consulting and training company based in Burlington,
Mass.
   The survey found executives are virtually unanimous in their
belief that responsibility for quality must be shared by everyone
in the company. Almost all agreed that ``everyone in the company
affects customer satisfaction.''
   The questioning continued, leading to this finding:
   In the typical company surveyed, just 25 percent of workers were
involved in quality improvement activities. Only 17 percent of the
respondents said their company involves more than half its
employees.
   The results underscore what many quality improvement specialists
have been saying for years, that one of the major quality defects
of American industry is the failure to follow through on corporate
goals.
   The problem isn't one of recognition. Almost every executive
will explain that quality and service are foremost among corporate
goals. Awareness probably has never been higher. The consequences
of poor quality are known.
   In fact, the current emphasis on quality arises directly from
the painful experience American industry had with poor quality
during the 1960s, when U.S. companies began losing entire markets
to the Japanese, who embraced quality.
   Oddly, much of the quality control practiced by the Japanese
emerged from the U.S. experience, and from Americans who had raised
it to the level of a science, including W. Edwards Deming and
Armand V. Feigenbaum.
   Oddly, some major American corporations intentionally let
quality to deteriorate, contending it was more cost-effective to
allow flawed products to leave the factory, to be fixed later by
service departments.
   It didn't work, largely because after-sale service was likewise
flawed. That is, the quality of service was as bad as the quality
of the product, and customers quickly became aware of it. Why not?
They sensed they were being exploited.
   Much of the subsequent recovery of U.S. industry, now showing up
as a resurgence of manufacturing, productivity gains, improved
trade statistics and healthier profits, is a consequence of efforts
to improve quality and service.
   But survey after survey shows that the notion of quality and
service is more deeply imbedded than the practice. Everyone cheers
for improvements, but not nearly as many go to work after the
cheering stops.
   In the Organizational Dynamics survey, respondents agreed that
quality and service control are matters that involve employees at
all levels, but only one-third said they shared customer
satisfaction data with all employees.
   As one of the foremost authorities on quality control, Philip B.
Crosby, has stated often _ he even wrote a book about it _
``quality is free.''
   It may not cost even a penny to begin with, he says, but if it
costs anything at all the cost comes back many times in higher
sales.
   Underlying his assumption is faith in human beings to do
superior work if given the direction and the motivation, and if
given a return on their efforts to contribute.
   End Adv PMs Wednesday May 25
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880524-0265 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-24-88 2341EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a p AM-Bush'sRetreat Adv30   05-24 0956</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush's Retreat, Adv 30,0979</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv30</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Mon AMs, May 30, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Tourist Town Proud and Protective of Vice President</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JERRY HARKAVY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KENNEBUNKPORT, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   On a cloudy, midweek afternoon, car
after car slows to a crawl as the occupants crane their necks to
catch a glimpse of this resort town's most famous landmark _ the
vacation retreat of George Bush.
   No matter that the vice president wasn't home or that the
oceanfront dwelling was virtually obscured by fog.
   The drive-bys and gawkers on Ocean Avenue are bound to multiply
this summer as tourists ignore the no-parking signs and pull to the
side of the narrow two-lane road to snap photographs of the home of
the prospective Republican nominee for president.
   Less than two miles away, ``help wanted'' signs festoon the
stores in and around Dock Square as Kennebunkport awakens from its
off-season slumber to begin what may be remembered as its last
summer of relative obscurity.
   By next year at this time, the southern Maine town might occupy
a niche in history as the favored retreat of a sitting president,
joining the ranks of such far-flung places as Plains, Ga., San
Clemente, Calif., and Hyannis, Mass., that were transformed into
news datelines recognized worldwide.
   Already, townspeople are pondering what a Bush victory in
November would mean to this town of 4,500, whose population
balloons to more than 25,000 in the summer.
   ``That's what we're asking ourselves mostly _ what if? And
sometimes the answers that come out are pretty scary,'' said Police
Chief John A. Prescott, whose concerns focus on the flow of traffic
past the vice president's compound at Walker's Point, named for
Bush's maternal grandfather.
   More than 18,000 cars a day spill into Dock Square in the middle
of the summer, according to the state's latest traffic count. ``So
if you figure half those cars went down Ocean Avenue, that's 9,000
cars. And if even 10 percent of those cars stop and park where they
shouldn't, that really fouls things up,'' the chief said.
   To ease potential traffic tie-ups, Prescott recently proposed
that Ocean Avenue be made one-way, but town selectmen scuttled the
suggestion after a public hearing last month.
   The chief also expresses concern about the likelihood of larger
and more frequent protest demonstrations outside the Bush home _
there have been only a handful during his tenure as vice president
_ and the prospect of television vans blocking traffic when he's in
town.
   Bush's election would surely increase the size of the press
corps that follows him to Kennebunkport, making it harder than ever
to get a hotel room at the height of the season.
   A subject of perennial speculation is whether local lobster
fishermen would still be allowed to tend their traps within
shouting distance of Bush's property while he is in town.
   Some have suggested that security would actually diminish if the
Secret Service declared the waters off-limits; lobstermen who
frequent the cove know each other and are traditionally wary of
strangers who wander into territory they regard as their own.
   Residents, town officials and merchants appear proud and
protective of Bush, characterizing him as a good friend and
neighbor whose family's roots here date back to the turn of the
century.
   By all accounts, he keeps a low profile and tries to cause no
disruption by his presence. Townspeople, in turn, respect his
privacy and avoid attempts at commercial exploitation.
   Bush generally spends three weeks each summer in Kennebunkport,
playing golf and tennis and fishing for mackerel or bluefish from
his speedboat docked in the Kennebunk River. He patronizes local
stores and restaurants, attends nearby churches and occasionally
participates in community activities; last year he delivered the
speech at the high school commencement, and in years past he has
appeared in Dock Square for the town's Memorial Day parade.
   Townspeople question whether a Bush victory in November could
generate bigger midsummer crowds than the ones that already swarm
through the downtown area, past the clothing boutiques, art
galleries, upscale restaurants and souvenir shops.
   ``In summertime we're very near gridlock anyway, and how much
more effect it can have is questionable,'' said Roland F. Drew,
chairman of the board of selectmen and a longtime friend of the
vice president.
   ``The place is a zoo in the summertime anyway,'' agreed Howard
Noyes, proprietor of a sandwich shop and gift store known as The
Old Salt's Pantry.
   Kennebunkport, home of such stately old hotels as the Colony and
the Shawmut Inn, has attracted well-heeled tourists from Boston and
New York since the late 1800s while maintaining a dual identity as
a fishing port.
   In the past 15 years, however, the biggest growth has been
tourism, with commercial development fanning out from Dock Square
while real estate values have skyrocketed virtually everywhere.
   Tourists won't find George Bush T-shirts, key chains or other
novelty items for sale in his home town. A cursory stroll through
the business district turned up just one article with his name on
it _ a picture postcard of the Walker's Point home.
   But there are no other Bush-related items amid the racks of
Kennebunkport sweatshirts and shelves of lobster and seagull
mementos that line Nathan Shmalo's store.
   ``People don't want to do anything tacky to hurt him or his
candidacy. We don't want to turn him into a gimmick or a
sideshow,'' Shmalo said.
   Although townspeople take pride in Bush's achievements,
selectman Drew doubts Kennebunkport would ever erect a road sign or
billboard to trumpet his presence.
   ``Lord no! I think he'd be furious,'' Drew said. ``I would hope
we'd never do anything like that. We're not that kind of town.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Mon AMs, May 30</NOTE>
</DOC>
