<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 2 Takes,0549</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court let stand a ruling that put
millions of so-called fixed annuities under the jurisdiction of
federal securities laws.
   Under the lower court ruling, fixed annuities paying fluctuating
interest rates could be regulated the same as stocks and bonds.
   In other business-related actions Monday, the high court agreed
to study the power of states to regulate natural gas production and
refused to unravel a merger between units of Eastman Kodak Co. and
Fuqua Industries Inc.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita received a draft of
a five-year economic plan, promoting an increase in domestic
consumption and investment.
   The plan will be debated in Takeshita's Cabinet in coming weeks
and its broad outlines are expected to be confirmed as the
directions of Japan's economy through 1992.
   The draft, unveiled Monday, calls for a wide range of measures
to open and deregulate Japan's markets to foreign competition,
improved quality of life for the 122 million Japanese and more
Japanese aid to poor countries.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Loans to customers of the insolvent Federal
Land Bank in Jackson, Miss., are expected to resume quickly under a
receiver's supervision, the chief regulator of the Farm Credit
System said.
   The doors of the billion-dollar lending cooperative were closed
Friday after heavy losses. The land bank serves 90 local lending
associations in Alabama, Mississippi and Louisiana.
   Since the bank itself is not permitted to make loans, other
institutions will make loans through it, Frank W. Naylor Jr.,
chairman of the Farm Credit Administration, said Monday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stress is easing on the nation's farm
banks and many now are flush with cash as signs emerge of a rebound
in loan demand, the Federal Reserve Bank of Chicago reported.
   The new report released Monday is further confirmation of the
improved financial health of the banks that survived the severe
farm recession of the mid-1980s.
   Within the Chicago Federal Reserve District, the percentage of
banks with undesirably high ratios of loans to deposits has dropped
to 4 percent as of the first quarter of this year, down from 58
percent in the first quarter of 1979.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Builders started 16 percent fewer new housing
units in the first quarter than in the same period of 1987, pushing
the total to its lowest point in 5{ years, a business information
group reported.
   A nationwide survey released Monday by the F.W. Dodge division
of McGraw-Hill Information Systems Co. found that 318,967 units
were started in the first three months of the year, down from
381,292 units in the 1987 period.
   The last time a quarterly total was lower was in 1982, when
298,307 units were started in the third quarter, the company said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan will nominate Boston banking
executive John P. LaWare to be a member of the Federal Reserve's
board of governors.
   If confirmed by the Senate, he would succeed Henry C. Wallich.
His nomination was announced Monday.
   Since 1978, LaWare has been chairman and director of Shawmut
National Corp. and Shawmut Bank in Boston.
</TEXT>
