<1ST_LINE>r f PM-OilPrices     05-24 0241</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Oil Prices,0249</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oil Prices Slip In Dull Trading</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Recent reports of growing inventories and
weaker-than-expected demand continue to depress oil futures prices.
   In Monday trading on the New York Mercantile Exchange, contracts
for July delivery of West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark U.S.
crude oil, closed at $17.35 per 42-gallon barrel, down 35 cents
from Friday.
   Among refined products for June delivery, wholesale unleaded
gasoline settled at 51.44 cents a gallon, down 0.92 cent, while
wholesale heating oil closed at 46.91 cents a gallon, down 0.80
cent.
   Jayne Ball, an analyst at the Dean Witter Reynolds Inc.
securities firm, said prices fell because ``OPEC's production is
still up there, while there's some speculation that demand is not
as good as a lot of people thought,'' she said.
   She cited a Wall Street Journal article in Monday's editions
that quoted a European consulting firm as putting OPEC's production
at 200,000 barrels a day above projected demand for its crude in
the second half of this year.
   The report came on top of other recent indications that domestic
inventories have risen, contrary to previous expectations, putting
a damper on prices.
   Accordingly, Monday's futures trading was dull, as traders
continued to await the ministerial meeting of the 13-nation
Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries, due to begin on June
8.
   OPEC officials are expected to try again to find a way to limit
their production in order to support prices.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880524-0275 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-24-88 0140EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-FarmBanks Bjt   05-24 0651</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Farm Banks, Bjt,0665</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fed: Stress Eases On Farm Banks; Bankers Have Ample Funds For
Loans</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN P. ROSENFELD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Farmers stepped up loan repayments in
early 1988 while loan demand remained weak, leaving Midwest farm
banks flush with cash, the Federal Reserve Bank of Chicago reports.
   The new report released Monday is the latest confirmation of
reduced financial stress among banks that survived the severe farm
recession of the mid-1980s.
   A survey of 525 bankers in the Chicago Fed's five-state district
said 46 percent of those questioned reported farm loan repayment
rates in the first quarter exceeded the pace of a year earlier, and
only 2 percent reported slower repayments.
   In addition, the percentage of district banks with undesirably
high ratios of loans to deposits has dropped to 4 percent as of the
first quarter of this year. That's down from 58 percent in the
first quarter of 1979 _ a period of soaring land values and
double-digit inflation when bankers were almost stumbling over one
another to make farm loans.
   ``With faster paydowns on existing farm loans and sluggish new
loan demand, agricultural bankers continue to have ample funds for
lending and relatively low loan-to-deposit ratios,'' said Chicago
Fed economist Gary Benjamin. ``About 42 percent of the bankers
reported that the availability of funds for farm loans in the first
quarter exceeded the year-earlier level while less than 5 percent
reported a decline.''
   An index of loan demand in the Chicago Fed's district, based on
the bankers' responses to the survey, remained weak in the first
quarter, but still was the highest in nearly three years, Benjamin
reported.
   ``The weakness has reflected several factors, including large
government farm program payments, curtailed crop plantings and,
until recently, declines in farm production expenses and cuts in
capital expenditures,'' Benjamin said. ``Although still weak, there
is some evidence that loan demand is starting to strengthen.''
   In the first quarter, for example, 28 percent of the bankers
noted that loan demand was up and 26 percent reported a decline.
Looking at the current quarter, however, 29 percent said they
expected farm lending to be up from a year earlier, while just 19
percent said they expected a decline.
   Benjamin cited several emerging trends for the expected growth
in farm lending.
   ``Crop acreage, after declining in recent years, is likely to
hold steady in 1988,'' he said. ``Government payments to farmers
are trending down. And farm sector cash production expenses, after
declining 15 percent over the last three years, may edge up in 1988
due to higher input prices.''
   Benjamin also reported that ``the stress in farm loan portfolios
at banks has abated considerably.''
   Bad farm loans that commercial banks nationwide charged off
against earnings last year plunged about 55 percent to $530
million, compared with about $1.2 billion in 1986, $1.3 billion in
1985 and $900 million in 1984, when such information first became
available as the farm crisis was deepening.
   Within the Chicago Fed's district _ which includes Iowa,
Illinois, Indiana, Wisconsin and Michigan _ banks' net charge-offs
for farm loans fell last year to about $110 million from $350
million in 1986, nearly $400 million in 1985 and about $200 million
in 1984, Benjamin said in his report on credit conditions.
   Benjamin said estimates of outstanding farm debt nationwide were
between $141 billion and $143 billion at the end of last year, down
from $155 billion in 1986. That's more than 25 percent below the
peak of almost $193 billion in 1983.
   Benjamin also says preliminary estimates based on reports by
lenders indicate that banks moved ahead of the troubled Farm Credit
System last year to become the leading lender serving farmers.
Nationwide, banks held nearly $40.7 billion of outstanding farm
debt at the end of last year, compared with the approximately $39.4
billion held by institutions within the Farm Credit System.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
