<DOCNO> AP880524-0276 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-24-88 0144EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Soviet-Computers Bjt   05-24 0459</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Computers, Bjt,0474</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Computer Company Announces Joint Venture With Soviets</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SUNNYVALE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With only 50,000 personal computers in
the Soviet Union, a deal for that country to buy thousands of
U.S.-designed systems could signal a coming boom for other
companies in California's Silicon Valley.
   ``The potential business could be enormous, not only with this
particular agreement, but for other companies that have computer
products needed by the Soviets,'' provided trade doors between the
two countries stay open, said Cliff Lindsey of Dataquest Inc., a
market research firm in San Jose, Calif.
   Advanced Transducer Devices of Sunnyvale announced Monday it had
reached an agreement with the Soviet Union to assemble and sell
thousands of U.S.-designed personal computers in the U.S.S.R.
   ``The Soviets are coming to the West now to find a whole range
of products for the civilian side of their economy,'' said Michael
O'Rourke, Advanced Transducer's vice president of international
sales.
   With a population of more than 300 million, the Soviet Union
only has about 50,000 personal computers, Advanced Transducer
estimates. The United States, with a population of around 250
million, has 30 million PCs.
   The joint venture between Advanced Transducer and V@O
Electronorgtechnica, a Soviet electronics trading company, is
believed to be the first involving computers, Advanced Transducer
said.
   Advanced Transducer, which makes components for personal
computers, said the joint venture expects to sell at least 4,000
PCs to the Soviets in the first year. The computers would be for
use in Soviet schools, factories and offices, and not the military,
O'Rourke said.
   Soviet officials say their school system alone needs 100,000
personal computers a year, Advanced Transducer said.
   Under the five-year agreement, which must be approved by both
the U.S. and Soviet governments, Advanced Transducer and V@O
Electronorgtechnica, or Elorg, will form a joint venture called
Elorgsoft International. Elorgsoft International will operate as a
government-sanctioned corporation in the Soviet Union.
   Advanced Transducer, a subsidiary of Televideo Systems Inc.,
will begin the joint venture by assembling IBM-compatible PCs in
Sunnyvale. Later on, they will be assembled and sold in the Soviet
Union.
   The company expects to have the first 20 personal computers in
the Soviet Union by late June and hopes the joint venture can begin
assembling the units in that country by the end of the year.
   Elorg and Advanced Transducer reached the agreement about a week
ago after several months of talks, O'Rourke said. A ribbon-cutting
ceremony is planned in Moscow next month to officially announce the
agreement and the opening of a service, training and distribution
center for the joint venture there.
   Talks began last October when American Trading Corp., a New
York-based Soviet import-export company affiliated with Elorg,
approached Advanced Transducer with a proposal for a joint venture,
O'Rourke said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880524-0277 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-24-88 0246EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-MurrayOhio Bjt   05-24 0619</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Murray Ohio, Bjt,0638</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>AB Electrolux Raises Bid for Murray Ohio After Judge Clears Way</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL RAWLINS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   AB Electrolux of Sweden, freed by a
federal judge to pursue a takeover of Murray Ohio Manufacturing
Co., moved immediately to raise its bid from $182 million to $197
million.
   AB Electrolux, a giant appliance maker, said Monday it was
boosting its offer for Murray Ohio by $4, to $52 a share. Murray
Ohio manufactures lawn mowers and bicycles at a plant in
Lawrenceburg, Tenn.
   Murray Ohio stock closed at $51.125 a share Monday on the New
York Stock Exchange, more than double its price last Dec. 31.
   In a letter to Murray Ohio's directors, who turned down the
earlier $182 million offer, AB Electrolux President Anders Scharp
wrote from Stockholm, ``We are not `hostile outsiders.' We are as
familiar as our major brand names, Frigidaire, Tappan and Eureka in
American homes, and Poulan and Weed-Eater in American back yards.''
   AB Electrolux, which has no connection with U.S. vacuum cleaner
manufacturer Electrolux Inc. of Marietta, Ga., operates a Tappan
kitchen range plant at Springfield, Tenn., north of Nashville.
   Scharp said AB Electrolux had no intention to move Murray Ohio's
production from Lawrenceburg, ``nor would it make any economic
sense for Murray's production to be consolidated or transferred to
our other facilities.'' The letter was made public in New York.
   Nonetheless, Murray Ohio officials mustered their 3,000
employees at a night meeting in Lawrenceburg to discuss the court
ruling.
   After the meeting, John L. Duncan, president and chief executive
officer of Murray Ohio, said he did not know details of AB
Electrolux's increased bid.
   ``We understand that they're going to make an offer and we'll
deal with that when it comes,'' Duncan said.
   Murray Ohio's lawyers said they would appeal the decision by
U.S. District Judge Thomas A. Wiseman. Notice was filed to appeal
Wiseman's dissolution of a temporary injunction against AB
Electrolux to the 6th U.S. Circuit Court in Cincinnati.
   The Murray Ohio employees and others among the 11,000 residents
of Lawrenceburg have formed a ``Just Say Nej'' committee to oppose
the takeover. ``Nej'' is Swedish for ``No.''
   Wiseman ruled after last week's hearing on Murray Ohio's request
to block AB Electrolux from proceeding with its bid.
   ``I know of no law permitting the court to enjoin the transfer
of stock. We have in this country respect for private property,''
he said.
   Wiseman said he also found ``absolutely no evidence'' that
confidential information on Murray Ohio was made available to AB
Electrolux by the New York law firm of Sullivan & Cromwell, which
once advised Murray Ohio how to defend itself against a takeover.
   ``All the information appeared in an (magazine) article that was
readily available to any professional investigator,'' Wiseman said
in his ruling from the bench.
   In New York, Wiseman's ruling prompted Sullivan & Cromwell's
John L. Warden to issue a statement saying, ``We are gratified that
the court's decision ... on the evidence confirmed the position we
have taken since this matter began.''
   In a statement Monday, AB Electrolux said its tender offer would
be financed from its working capital and would be subject to
shareholder approval ``only if AB Electrolux is not satisfied that
the Ohio Control Share Act is inapplicable to the offer.''
   The Ohio Control Share Act is an anti-takeover law, and the AB
Electrolux statement said it would seek a ruling from federal
courts in Ohio that the act is inapplicable.
   Murray Ohio began in Ohio in 1919 manufacturing running boards
for automobiles. When running boards disappeared, the company
switched to wheeled toys, moving its headquarters to Brentwood,
Tenn., and opening its Lawrenceburg plant in 1955.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
