<FILEID>AP-NR-05-24-88 0827EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-AppleShipments     05-24 0347</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Apple Shipments,0359</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Record 1987 Washington Apple Sales</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NICHOLAS K. GERANIOS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>YAKIMA, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With more than two months left in their
marketing season, Washington growers reporte record sales of the
nation's largest apple crop.
   Through May 20, Washington growers shipped 56.5 million boxes of
apples, compared with the old record of 55 million boxes for all of
last year, according to the Wenatchee Valley Traffic Association.
Each box weighs 42 pounds.
   The shipping figures are good news for an industry trying to
market a record bumper group, but the good news is tempered by
stagnant prices.
   ``We're ahead of where we need to be at this time of year,''
said association manager Bill Dewitt in a telephone interview
Monday.
   There is no sign that sales are slackening.
   In the past five weeks, sales are nearly 40 percent above the
same period in 1987, according to the Washington Apple Commission,
which spent more than $1.6 million in television and radio ads over
the past two months.
   This apple crop, which represents roughly half the nation's
supermarket supply, is easily the largest in state history,
although the estimate has been cut to 67.4 million boxes from an
original projection of 72 million boxes because of the loss of poor
quality fruit during storage, Dewitt said.
   Overseas sales are way up this year, with 11.1 million boxes
shipped to foreign countries through May 20, compared with 5.2
million boxes at that time in 1987, Dewitt said. Most shipments are
to Taiwan, Hong Kong, Singapore, Thailand and Malaysia,
traditionally good customers.
   Exports are helped by the low prices this year, Dewitt said.
   Prices range from $7 a box for Washington Fancy grade apples to
$10 to $14 a box for Washington Extra Fancy, $2 to $3 lower than
last year, Dewitt said. It can cost about $9.50 to grow, pack and
ship a box of apples, so many of the state's 5,000 growers are
still losing money or breaking even.
   Apples are the state's largest cash crop, worth $489 million to
growers in 1986.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
