<DOCNO> AP880524-0282 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-24-88 0836EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-SpiceMerger     05-24 0610</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Spice Merger,0628</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>McCormick & Co. Inc. Ends Bid To Acquire West Coast Competitor</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   McCormick & Co. Inc. announced it would end its
proposed $56 million takeover of a West Coast competitor after the
Federal Trade Commission unanimously voted to challenge the bid in
court.
   Monday's announcement effectively ends the Hunt Valley spice
maker's four-month pursuit of regulatory approval for its proposed
acquisition of the Spice Islands line of spices, herbs and vinegars
from Specialty Brands Inc., of San Francisco.
   The announcement came just hours after the FTC said it had
authorized its staff to seek a preliminary injunction blocking the
sale because of its potential to ``substantially reduce competition
in the production and sales of spices.''
   ``As a result of the FTC's obvious opposition, McCormick &
Specialty Brands have decided not to pursue the merger,'' Mac
Barrett, McCormick spokesman, told The (Baltimore) Sun. ``We're
disappointed.''
   Executives at Specialty Brands did not return phone calls Monday.
   The FTC, which typically reviews how proposed mergers will
affect market share, barriers to entry and competition in a given
industry, has sought to block only seven proposed mergers in the
past year, said spokeswoman Susan Ticknor.
   The takeover would have given McCormick, already the world's
largest spice producer, the brand name of one of its best-known
rivals in the $850 million condiments business.
   McCormick's proposed purchase price of $56 million for the West
Coast concern was a considerable premium over Spice Islands' 1987
sales of $30 million.
   When the proposed deal was announced in late January, some
industry analysts speculated that it might raise antitrust
questions because of McCormick's huge share of the market,
estimated to be more than twice that of Durkee, its largest
domestic competitor.
   The acquisition of Spice Islands, which holds an estimated 30
percent of the fast-growing $100 million gourmet side of the
business, would have given McCormick an 80 percent share of that
segment, industry analysts say.
   ``The FTC is hanging tough on this one because they believe it
would create too much concentration in a hotly contested business.
Everybody's fighting for market share,'' said David S. Leibowitz,
an analyst who follows McCormick for American Securities in New
York.
   Others, however, expressed surprise at the FTC's ardor in
blocking McCormick's acquisition of a company whose 1987 sales
totaled only $30 million.
   ``It's surprising that the commission would attempt to block a
transaction that is relatively small compared with all the
multi-billion dollar deals we've seen lately,'' said Barry Ziegler,
an analyst at Tucker, Anthony & Co. in New York. ``It seems like a
lot of effort over a relatively small matter.''
   Late last month, a federal judge granted the FTC's request to
stop the proposed deal on the grounds that McCormick hadn't
provided enough information for the agency to determine how the
transaction would affect competition in the spice and seasonings
business.
   Prior to that decision, McCormick sued the agency, maintaining
that the company had supplied more than 120,000 pages of documents
and provided the depositions of key executives.
   Earlier this month, McCormick acquiesced to the FTC's demand for
more information and dropped its suit. But Monday, two days before
its deadline to render a decision, on the merger, the FTC said it
would challenge McCormick in court if it persisted with the
transaction.
   Given the length of time that has passed since the proposal
first was announced and the possible legal battle with federal
regulators, McCormick decided to abandon its bid. ``After the
months involved in getting us to this point and the FTC's decision
to oppose the transaction, we decided the best course of action is
to drop the merger,'' Barrett said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
