<1ST_LINE>u f PM-TreasuryBills     05-24 0175</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Treasury Bills,0181</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Interest Rates on Short-Term T-Bills Hit Post-Crash High</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Interest rates on short-term Treasury
securities rose in the latest auction to the highest level since
the October stock market crash.
   The Treasury Department on Monday sold $6.4 billion in
three-month bills at an average discount rate of 6.34 percent, up
from 6.28 percent last week. Another $6.4 billion was sold in
six-month bills at an average discount rate of 6.71 percent, up
from 6.50 percent last week.
   The rates were the highest since Oct. 19, when three-month bills
sold for 6.84 percent and six-month bills averaged 7.21 percent.
   The new discount rates understate the actual return to investors
_ 6.53 percent for three-month bills with a $10,000 bill selling
for $9,839.70 and 7.04 percent for a six-month bill selling for
$9,658.90.
   In a separate report, the Federal Reserve said the average yield
for one-year Treasury bills, the most popular index for making
changes in adjustable rate mortgages rose to 7.40 percent last week
from 7.33 percent the previous week.
</TEXT>
