<1ST_LINE>u f PM-StockMarketReport 1stLd-Writethru a0455 05-24 0550</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Stock Market Report, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0455,0559</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senator Says Report Ignores Problems Raising Capital</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 5 grafs new with meeting beginning; Picks up 6th graf
pvs, The study.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The newest White House report on the stock
market collapse does nothing to soothe Wall Street's problems and
is merely an effort to prevent legislative action this year, the
chairman of the Senate Banking Committee said today.
   The chairman, Sen. William Proxmire, D-Wis., told the four
high-level federal officials who wrote the report that their study
was ``pitiful'' during a hearing on its recommendations.
   ``This working group has been the regulatory equivalent of the
North Carolina Tar Heels basketball strategy called the
four-corners offense,'' Proxmire said. ``Pass the ball around to
run out the clock. Never shoot, just stall and run out the clock.''
   Proxmire has been critical of the study since its release May
16. On Monday, he said on the Senate floor that in the seven months
since Oct. 19 _ the day the Dow Jones Industrial Average dropped a
record 508 points _ American corporations have raised only $1.5
billion. During the same period between 1986 and 1987, those
businesses raised $10.7 billion, he said.
   Proxmire said the unpredictable, fluctuating performance of the
stock market since October has scared many investors away and made
it diffcult for companies to raise needed investment money. The
recommendations in the report, which was overseen by the Treasury
Department, did not address that problem, Proxmire said.
   The study was written by Treasury Undersecretary George D.
Gould, Commodity Futures Trading Commission Chairwoman Wendy Gramm,
Securities and Exchange Commission Chairman David S. Ruder and
Federal Reserve Board Chairman Alan Greenspan.
   The report's recommendations have drawn fire on Capitol Hill
from lawmakers who have complained that it failed to recommend
decisive action to deal with the ills of the nation's financial
markets.
   It contained no proposals to restrict types of program trading,
the computer-driven transactions some critics have blamed for the
market's continued volatility. It ignored critics who say the
margins _ or up-front payments _ for stock index futures
transactions on the Chicago commodities markets are too low and
thus encourage speculation that causes wild bounces in prices on
the market in New York.
   In addition, it paid no notice to a recommendation by an earlier
White House task force that one federal agency _ likely the Fed _
be put in charge of all issues that affect the nation's stock,
futures and options markets. That jurisdiction is now split among
the Fed, CFTC and SEC.
   The Gould group's most striking recommendation was for an
hour-long trading halt across all financial markets if the Dow ever
drops by 250 points in a single day. A second, two-hour closing
would occur if the widely-watched index plummets by 400 points.
   The Dow has dropped as many as 250 points only once _ last Oct.
19. The working group's members say setting the trigger at such a
high point would keep it out of the market's normal workings and
ensure that it comes into play only in emergencies.
   The report also recommended changes in the clearing, credit and
settlement mechanisms that the markets use to complete the
exchanges of money and paperwork that accompany each day's
transactions.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880524-0288 </DOCNO>
