<2ND_LINE>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0342</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Grain, Soybean Futures Open Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures opened higher today on
the Chicago Board of Trade as dry-weather concerns returned to the
markets.
   Weekend rains caused the grain markets to sell off Monday. But
with dry conditions returning to the Midwest, prices were expected
to resume their climb, analysts said.
   ``Again, it's all weather-related,'' said Richard Loewy, senior
grain and oilseed analyst with Prudential-Bache Securities Inc. in
New York. ``The meteorologists are basically saying it's going to
be warm and dry the next several days with very little chance of
getting any moisture.''
   In a six-to-10-day forecast issued late Monday, the National
Weather Service called for conditions in the Corn Belt to be warmer
and drier than normal through the first half of next week.
   Also Monday, the Agriculture Department reported soybean
planting was 62 percent complete as of Sunday. Corn planting was 95
percent finished.
   The USDA also reported a slight decline in the condition of
winter wheat crops.
   In early trading, wheat was 1} cents to 2} cents higher with the
contract for delivery in July at $3.45 a bushel; corn was 1{ cents
to 2\ cents higher with July at $2.17\ a bushel; oats were } cent
to 1\ cents higher with July at $1.72 a bushel; soybeans were {
cent lower to 7{ cents higher with July at $7.63 a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were mostly lower in early trading on
the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .05 cent to .43 cent lower with June at 72.22
cents a pound; feeder cattle were .50 cent lower to .05 cent higher
with May at 80.95 cents a pound; hogs were .05 cent to .47 cent
lower with June at 53.15 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were
.20 cent to .28 cent lower with July at 53.75 cents a pound.
   Cattle and hog futures settled lower on Monday. Frozen pork
bellies were higher.
