<FILEID>AP-NR-05-24-88 2324EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a f BC-Singapore-Labor Adv28-29   05-24 0881</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Singapore-Labor, Adv 28-29,0908</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 28</NOTE>
<NOTE>$adv 29</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions May 28-29 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Singapore's Booming Economy Squeezed By Labor Shortage</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KENNETH L. WHITING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SINGAPORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Caught between patriotism and protectionism,
officials are reluctantly allowing sales clerks from other
countries to work behind the counters in Singapore department
stores.
   On the one hand, officials don't want their booming economy to
suffer from a lack of labor. But they are equally determined not to
let the country depend indefinitely on low-skilled foreign workers.
   No quick solution is in sight.
   In announcing the budget recently, Finance Minister Richard Hu
noted that a ``controlled revolving pool of foreign workers on
short-term work permits'' would be allowed to continue beyond 1992.
   ``The demand for foreign workers has been increasing rapidly.
More than half of the 48,000 jobs created in the manufacturing
sector last year were filled by foreign workers. In the last three
months, manufacturing companies have been recruiting about 2,500
foreign workers each month,'' Hu said.
   Bolstered by strong overseas demand and foreign investment, the
economy has bounced back from a recession three years ago. But a
limited labor pool in this city-state of 2.6 million people is now
regarded as a threat to continued growth.
   Help-wanted ads cram the newspapers. Signs offering walk-in
interviews are posted outside dozens of factories. With workers
able to pick and choose, job-hopping is common, especially in the
electronics industry.
   Economic expansion generated a net increase of 66,000 new jobs
last year, according to Ministry of Trade and Industry figures. The
economy grew by 8.8 percent, compared to 1.8 percent in 1986.
Unemployment was 2.8 percent at the end of 1987, against 4.6
percent at the beginning of last year.
   The boom is exemplified by Seagate Technology, the largest
single private employer. The U.S. disk-drive manufacturer started
operations here six years ago with 50 workers and now employs
13,000.
   The United States decided in January that Singapore, known along
with Hong Kong, Taiwan and South Korea as the fast-growing ``four
dragons'' of Asia, is no longer a developing country in need of
special trade preferences. Duty-free access to the U.S. market for
the exports of all four is to be ended.
   Established department stores complained earlier this year of a
shortage of about 2,000 sales clerks. Newly-opened stores were able
to lure away such personnel from older retailers by offering high
starting salaries. Older merchants could not match the money
because of a wage freeze imposed during the recession. They
appealed for government help.
   Labor Minister Lee Yock Suan told parliament recently that
labor-starved storekeepers could now hire foreigners providing they
had the equivalent of a high school education.
   One chain of eight stores advertised in neighboring Malaysia for
counter staff, so far with indifferent results. The Malaysian
economy is also thriving, absorbing much of the labor Singapore
stores and factories seek, and at least one retailer suggests that
the educational qualification is too stringent.
   Until the stores got help, alien ``work permit holders'' could
be hired only in construction, manufacturing, hotels and as
domestic servants. These jobs are often spurned by increasingly
affluent Singaporeans, who enjoy the highest standard of living in
Asia after the Japanese.
   The government once argued that guest workers in these fields
were manageable because terms of service were clear cut. They were
usually housed in dormitories by their employers and automatically
sent home when contracts ended. It was assumed that retail clerks
would be scattered throughout the island and might try to remain
after their contracts expired.
   The total work force is 1.2 million. About 40 percent of the
estimated 140,000 foreign laborers are employed as domestic help,
three-quarters of the from the Philippines.
   White-collar foreigners, including executives, bankers,
engineers and teachers, are classified separately. Those with
special skills are being avidly sought.
   Lee said the policy on foreign workers was ``already very
liberal'' and would not be eased further. As a small country,
Singapore cannot afford to let the unskilled flow in, Lee said.
   He estimated that for every 1 percent of growth, the economy
needs 10,000 foreign workers. For 10 percent growth, it means
100,000 foreign workers, which could not be allowed, Lee said.
   No more than 50 percent of a company's staff can be from outside
the country. To restrain demand further, the government collects a
special tax from employers of foreign workers.
   Lee suggested that private companies do not try hard enough to
attract available locals, including housewives, those willing to
work part-time and older people.
   There are 745,799 Singaporeans listed as economically inactive,
many of whom left the work force at the traditional retirement age
of 55.
   ``With sufficient inducements and job opportunities, many
housewives could be attracted back to the labor markets. The easy
way out is for employers to lobby for access to more foreign
workers,'' Lee said.
   Of particular concern to trade union leaders is a pool of older
workers who lost relatively well-paid jobs in the recession and who
are unsuited to the openings now available or unwilling to accept
them.
   Meantime, the government acknowledges the labor crunch by
allowing workers to be recruited from China although Singapore has
no diplomatic ties with Beijing and remains rigorously
anti-communist.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Weekend Editions May 28-29</NOTE>
