<2ND_LINE>AM-PC Clones,0143</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Supplier Of Chips For PC Clones Doesn't Need IBM License</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chips and Technologies Inc., a key source of
chips for personal computer clones, said Tuesday it has reached an
understanding with IBM that it does not need a license from the
computer giant for its current business.
   International Business Machines Corp. indicated it will focus on
requiring licenses of companies that actually make the personal
computer clones, said Gordon Campbell, the chairman and chief
executive of Chips and Technologies.
   The San Jose, Calif.-based company said IBM has assured it that
if a license is required in the future, one will be available on
IBM's normal terms and conditions.
   Chips and Technologies recently announced a set of chips
designed for computers compatible with IBM's new Personal System-2
line of personal computers.
</TEXT>
