<1ST_LINE>r f AM-WometcoPurchase     05-24 0227</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Wometco Purchase,0236</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cablevision To Buy Wometco Cable, Exec Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cablevision Industries, one of the largest cable
television companies in the country, said it will buy Miami-based
Wometco Cable TV in a tax-free exchange of common stock in a deal
valued at $725 million, Wometco's president said Tuesday.
   Wometco is a privately owned cable television company with
subscribers in North and South Carolina, West Virginia, Louisiana,
Oklahoma and Georgia.
   Its controlling stockholders are affiliated with the Robert M.
Bass Group, Inc., of Fort Worth, Texas.
   Cablevision will acquire 311,000 subscribers, according to
Wometco President Milton Lewis.
   Cablevision, based in Liberty, N.Y., will also assume Wometco's
debt and its preferred stock, currently estimated at more than $700
million, Lewis said.
   Alan Gerry, chairman and chief executive officer of Cablevision
Industries, said the transaction will take place on Dec. 1, 1988,
providing Cablevision with a total of more than 900,000 subscribers.
   Before the exchange of stock is completed, Wometco will give to
its present stockholders a Wometco subsidiary which operates cable
television systems for about 140,000 subscribers in the Atlanta,
Ga. suburbs.
   Wometco was acquired by the Bass Group and the Taft Broadcasting
Company from Kohlberg, Kravis, Roberts & Co. in December 1986 for
about $620 million. The Bass Group bought the 50 percent of the
cable operation that Taft had owned in October 1987.
</TEXT>
