<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stocks rose today as a surge of dividend-related
trading caused business to heat up from the previous session, which
was the slowest since last Thanksgiving.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials climbed 12.60 points to
1,954.08 with two hours of trading to go.
   Gainers outnumbered losers about 3 to 2 in the overall tally of
New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 791 issues up, 544 down
and 546 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 107.25 million shares as of 2
p.m. on Wall Street.
   In economic news, the Commerce Department said orders to U.S.
factories for ``big ticket'' durable goods rose 0.8 percent in
April, boosted by a jump in orders for military communications
equipment.
   The third consecutive monthly increase, which fell in line with
expectations, followed gains of 0.9 percent in March and 0.1
percent in February. It confirmed most analysts' views that the
economy is growing robustly.
   Business remained slow aside from dividend-related trading.
   ``Most of the institutions seem to be totally paralyzed,'' said
Hugh Johnson, chief investment officer for First Albany Corp. in
Albany, N.Y.
   Murray Ohio Manufacturing Co. leaped 7} to 59. A federal judge
ruled Monday that Sweden's AB Electrolux could proceed with its bid
for Murray, and Electrolux raised its bid for the company to $52 a
share, or $197 million.
   On the American Stock Exchange, BDM International was up 3| at
34\. Ford Aerospace Corp. said today it was buying the defense
contractor for $34.75 a share, or about $425 million.
   Utilities dominated the list of most actively traded NYSE issues
as traders sought to buy the stocks to capture their dividends.
Northeast Utilities, which accounted for more than 23 million
shares, was down [ at 19{. Kansas Power & Light was up [ at 24[.
   Among blue-chip stocks, Boeing was up 1{ at 53\, Citicorp was up
] at 22[, Texaco was down \ at 45~ and American Telephone &
Telegraph was up [ at 26{.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks was
up 0.71 to 142.92. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was down 0.35 at 290.33.
   On Monday, the volume on the floor of the Big Board came to
102.64 million shares for the full session, the smallest total
since 86.36 million were traded in a post-Thanksgiving session last
Nov. 27.
