<2ND_LINE>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0255</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soybean Futures Close Limit Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some soybean futures closed up the
30-cents-a-bushel daily limit Tuesday on the Chicago Board of Trade
and grain futures also advanced sharply on renewed concern about
dry weather.
   Monday's sharp price declines were only a temporary setback and
the weekend rains that caused them only a brief respite from the
unusually warm, dry conditions that will continue to dominate
springtime weather in the Midwest, according to Tuesday's forecasts.
   ``The meteorologists lowered their forecasts of rain between now
and next Monday and everybody jumped back on the bandwagon,'' said
Jerry Gidel, an analyst in Chicago with G.H. Miller & Co.
   The National Weather Service, in a six-to-10-day outlook issued
late Monday, called for warmer and drier than nomal conditions in
the Corn Belt through the first half of next week.
   Also Monday, the Agriculture Department reported soybean
planting was 62 percent complete as of Sunday. Corn planting was 95
percent finished.
   The soybean market is especially sensitive to weather factors
amid dwindling stockpiles and fears of tight supplies.
   At the close, wheat was 4} cents to 18 cents higher with the
contract for delivery in July at $3.47{ a bushel; corn was 4 cents
to 5\ cents higher with July at $2.19{ a bushel; oats were 4 cents
to 4\ cents higher with July at $1.75 a bushel; soybeans were 11{
cents to 30 cents higher with July at $7.82 a bushel.
</TEXT>
