<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Philips-Mediagenic     05-24 0228</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Philips-Mediagenic,0238</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Finds Mediagenic Infringed On Philips Patent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal appeals court has upheld a finding of
patent infringement involving video games sold by Mediagenic Inc.,
the former Activision Inc.
   North American Philips Corp., the patent licensee, announced
Tuesday the Court of Appeals for the Federal Circuit in Washington
had found the patent valid and infringed by all 11 of Mediagenic's
video game cartridges involved in the litigation.
   Mediagenic will petition the appellate court for a rehearing and
if denied will consider an appeal to the Supreme Court, Bruce
Davis, chief executive of the Menlo Park, Calif.-based company,
said in an interview.
   The patent, which dates to the 1960s, was licensed exclusively
to North American Philips by Sanders Associates, North American
Philips said.
   Other video game companies that have signed patent licenses with
North American Philips include Mattel Inc. and Atari Corp., said
Joseph Briody, the company's corporate patent counsel. He said the
company is suing Nintendo of America Inc. and expects that suit to
go to trial in October.
   Briody said North American Philips has generally sought paid-up
licenses rather than payment of damages from the video game makers.
He said the appellate court's decision was May 9.
   North American Philips, a subsidiary of the Dutch electronics
giant NV Philips, sells products under labels such as Magnavox,
Norelco, Philips and Sylvania.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880524-0301 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-24-88 1613EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-WallStreetClosing     05-24 0132</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street Closing,0143</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stocks rebounded modestly today as the volume of
trading picked up because of a surge of dividend-related trading.
   Business remained slow aside from trading by investors seeking
to capture the dividends of utilities in quick turnovers.
   Institutional investors that ordinarily account for a large
share of the trading were standing aside because of continued
concerns about high interest rates.
   ``Most of the institutions seem to be totally paralyzed,'' said
Hugh Johnson, chief investment officer for First Albany Corp. in
Albany, N.Y.
   In economic news, the Commerce Department said orders to U.S.
factories for ``big ticket'' durable goods rose 0.8 percent in
April, boosted by a jump in orders for military communications
equipment.
   The third consecutive monthly increase was in line with
expectations.
</TEXT>
