<FILEID>AP-NR-05-24-88 1658EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     05-24 0525</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dollar-Gold,0543</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar, Gold Prices Mostly Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar fell against most major currencies
Tuesday in thin, uneventful trading.
   Gold prices finished slightly lower in most markets. Republic
National Bank in New York quoted a late bid for gold of $459.20 a
troy ounce as of 4 p.m. EDT, compared with Monday's late bid of
$460.30.
   A lack of market-affecting news kept the dollar trading in a
narrow range. The only significant move came when the dollar broke
through the 124-level against the Japanese yen.
   But unsubstantiated rumors that the Federal Reserve stepped in
to support the currency helped push the dollar back up again, said
Stephen Flanagan, an assistant vice president at Manufacturers
Hanover Trust Co.
   Traders also noted an international meeting of chief foreign
exchange dealers and managers in Hawaii this week may also be
having a dampening effect on activity.
   ``It possibly is leaving some junior dealers manning the boards,
and they may or may not have instructions to get too involved,''
said Ron Sapiro, head trader at Continental Illinois National Bank
& Trust Co. in Chicago.
   The dollar closed lower earlier in Europe, where dealers said
business was very quiet.
   ``Nobody knows what to do,'' said one dealer at an American bank
in London. ``The big money is just sitting in cash deposits. People
aren't moving it around.''
   In Tokyo, the dollar fell 0.55 yen to a closing 124.25. In later
London trading, the dollar was quoted at 124 yen. In New York, the
dollar closed at 124.175 yen, down from 124.515 yen on Monday.
   In London, the British pound edged up to $1.8680 from $1.8675.
But in New York it cost $1.86725 to buy one pound, less expensive
than Monday's $1.86875.
   Britain's top Treasury official, Chancellor of the Exchequer
Nigel Lawson, reiterated Tuesday Britain should ensure it
maintained a stable pound while keeping the brakes on inflation.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late Monday's
rates, included: 1.70065 West German marks, down from 1.70175;
1.4196 Swiss francs, up from 1.4166; 5.7420 French francs, down
from 5.7560; 1,262.025 Italian lire, down from 1.263.50, and 1.2417
Canadian dollars, down from 1.24245.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Monday's
prices, included: 1.7000 West German marks, down from 1.7030;
1.4150 Swiss francs, down from 1.4198; 5.7395 French francs, down
from 5.7570; 1.9030 Dutch guilders, down from 1.9075; 1,261.80
Italian lire, down from 1,263.75; and 1.2412 Canadian dollars, down
from 1.2427.
   Gold bullion fell in London to a late bid of $457.75 a troy
ounce, compared with late Monday's $459.60. In Zurich, the metal
closed at a bid $458. Zurich markets were closed Monday for a
religious holiday celebrated in much of Europe. Friday's bid was
$455.50.
   On New York's Commodity Exchange, gold closed at $460.60 a troy
ounce, down from $462.20 on Monday.
   Earlier in Hong Kong, gold fell 22 cents to close at a bid
$460.91.
   Silver finished at $6.754 a troy ounce on New York's Comex, up
from $6.738 on Monday. In London the metal traded at a late bid of
$6.71 a troy ounce, little changed from late Monday's $6.70.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
