<1ST_LINE>u f AM-CommodityRdp     05-24 0791</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Commodity Rdp,0822</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soybeans Resume Rally, Post Near-Limit Gains</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The soybean futures market shook off the dampening effects of
last weekend's rains and resumed its dry-weather rally Tuesday,
with prices on some contracts advancing nearly the
30-cents-a-bushel daily limit.
   Grain futures also gained on the Chicago Board of Trade.
   On other markets, copper futures prices fell sharply while
precious metals were mixed; cocoa futures soared; livestock and
meat were mostly lower; energy futures were mixed; and stock-index
futures advanced.
   Monday's steep drop in soybean futures prices was only a
temporary setback and the weekend rains that caused it were only a
brief respite from the unusally warm, dry conditions that will
continue to dominate springtime weather in the Midwest, according
to Tuesday's forecasts.
   ``The meteorologists lowered their forecasts of rain between now
and next Monday and everybody jumped back on the bandwagon,'' said
Jerry Gidel, an analyst in Chicago with G.H. Miller & Co.
   The soybean market is especially sensitive to weather factors
amid dwindling stockpiles and fears of tight supplies if this
year's crop does poorly.
   In addition weather-related speculative buying, the soybean
complex got a boost from India's purchase of 20,000 metric tons of
U.S. soybean oil and hedge-type buying of soybean meal futures by
commercial grain processors, Gidel said.
   The grains basically followed the soybeans, but corn also
benefitted from a government report of increased export demand and
wheat was buoyed by an Agriculture Department report of dry-weather
damage to the winter wheat crop.
   Wheat settled 4} cents to 18 cents higher with the contract for
delivery in July at $3.47{ a bushel; corn was 4\ cents to 5\ cents
higher with July at $2.19\ a bushel; oats were 3} cents to 4{ cents
higher with July at $1.75 a bushel; soybeans were 12 cents to 29{
cents higher with July at $7.83{ a bushel.
   Copper futures prices sank on the Commodity Exchange in New York
in response to steady increases in London Metal Exchange stocks of
the metal, analysts said.
   Tight supplies have been the main feature of the copper market
for more than a year, and the recent gain of more 12,000 tons on
the London exchange indicates supplies of deliverable copper are
growing, said John O'Connell, metals analyst with Refco Inc. in New
York.
   ``The LME is now at 58,000 tons. That's a big jump,'' he said.
   Copper settled 2.2 cents to 4.1 cents lower with May at 98 cents
a pound.
   Gold futures settled slightly lower while silver advanced a bit
on the Commodity Exchange.
   Gold settled 10 cents to $1.70 lower with June at $461.10 a troy
ounce; silver was 1.5 cents to 1.6 cents higher with May at $6.754
a troy ounce.
   Cocoa futures soared to 3{-month highs on New York's Coffee,
Sugar & Cocoa Exchange.
   Analysts cited strong technical factors and rumors that the
Brazilian cocoa crop would be poorer than expected.
   Cocoa settled $35 to $40 higher with July at $1,710 per ton.
   Most cattle futures retreated on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange
on bearish technical factors and expectations of falling cash
prices due to slack demand for beef, analysts said.
   ``Retailers have been very lackluster in terms of buying volume
to fill their needs for the post-Memorial Day period, and it seems
like packers are also trying to buy cattle for a little less,''
said Charles Richardson, an analyst in Denver with Lind-Waldock &
Co.
   Hog futures were mixed while frozen pork bellies retreated in
reaction to a weaker tone in the cash market, Richardson said.
   Live cattle settled .40 cent lower to .05 cent higher with June
at 72.35 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .80 cent lower to .10
cent higher with May at 81 cents a pound; hogs were .22 cent lower
to .20 cent higher with June at 53.40 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were .25 cent to .40 cent lower with July at 53.70 cents a
pound.
   Oil futures prices closed mixed in light trading on the New York
Mercantile Exchange ahead of the afternoon release of the American
Petroleum Institute's weekly inventory figures.
   The report showed a buildup of both gasoline and crude oil
stocks and a drop in supplies of distillates, which include heating
oil.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 7 cents lower to 5
cents higher with July at $17.40 a barrel; heating oil was .20 cent
to .40 cent higher with June at 47.31 cents a gallon; unleaded
gasoline was .20 cent to .41 cent higher with June at 51.85 cents a
gallon.
   Stock-index futures posted substantial gains on the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange, where the contract for June delivery of the
Standard & Poor's 500 index settled 3.65 points higher at 254.25.
</TEXT>
