<1ST_LINE>u f AM-AT&T-Telerate     05-24 0313</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-AT&T-Telerate,0326</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reuters Asks Justice Review of AT&T-Telerate Joint Venture</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Justice Department is reviewing claims by
Reuters Information Service Inc. that American Telephone &
Telegraph Co.'s plans for a joint venture with Telerate Inc. would
violate an antitrust court order.
   Reuters says the venture to offer a foreign exchange
transactional service would violate the consent decree that broke
up the Bell system, which prohibits AT&T from entering the
electronic-publishing business until August 1989 at the earliest.
   ``There is no question that the transactional service
contemplated by the joint venture constitutes `electronic
publishing'' within the meaning of the consent decree, said a
letter Reuters sent to the Justice Department's antitrust division.
A copy of the letter was obtained by The Associated Press.
   Reuters' parent company, Reuters Holdings PLC, operates an
electronic foreign-exchange service similar to the ventured planned
by AT&T and Telerate. Reuters' service allows traders to confer
electronically using computers, said Reuters spokesman Robert Cooke.
   Cooke said he could not comment on the letter.
   A Justice Department spokesman confirmed the letter dated May 10
was received, but antitrust attorney Nancy Garrison declined to
comment. The antitrust division enforces the consent decree.
   AT&T spokeswoman Mary Ward said the company is ``in complete
compliance'' with the consent decree.
   John Jessop, executive vice president of Telerate, said the two
companies plan to develop a service that allows foreign exchange
traders to trade electronically with each other, ``and that's not
getting into the information business.''
   ``We're getting on with our business and we think Reuters should
do the same,'' Jessop said. ``We're a little surprised that a
company with a dominant market position in transactional services
should seek government help in fending off competition.''
   Telerate, 56 percent owned by Dow Jones & Co., operates a global
financial information network.
   AT&T is the nation's largest long-distance company.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880524-0308 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-24-88 1843EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Texaco-Icahn     05-24 0338</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Texaco-Icahn,0351</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Texaco and Takeover Strategist Maneuver For More Negotiating Time</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Texaco Inc. and its largest shareholder gave
themselves the option of three extra days to negotiate Tuesday as
part of an effort to reach a truce in their feud over the troubled
oil giant's future.
   Takeover strategist Carl C. Icahn, who owns 14.8 percent of
Texaco's stock, has threatened a shareholder fight to elect his
associates to the board at the company's annual meeting next month.
   Icahn has stated previously that Texaco, the nation's No. 3 oil
company is worth more to shareholders broken up and sold. The
management has pledged to sell at least $5 billion worth of assets
as part of a profound restructuring plan. The two sides have been
intensely negotiating for the past few weeks.
   Texaco said late Tuesday that to help further discussions, it
and Icahn had agreed to a mechanism under which the annual meeting
could be postponed from June 7 to June 17. Both sides had
previously agreed to postpone the meeting to June 14 if necessary
so the new arrangement gave them three additional days.
   A receptionist at Icahn's New York office said he was out of the
office and unreachable for comment.
   Sources familiar with the Texaco-Icahn negotiations, who spoke
on the condition they not be identified, said the option to further
delay the annual meeting did not necessarily mean there was any
significant movement in the position of either side. There had been
speculation an agreement was near.
   ``It signifies that each side would like to stop the clock from
ticking and have three free days without the encumbrance of time,''
said one source.
   Texaco shares, which have been falling since the truce talks
began, declined $1.50 Tuesday to $46.12{ in heavy volume in New
York Stock Exchange composite trading.
   The Icahn negotiations are the latest chapter in Texaco's effort
to function normally following a protracted legal battle with
Pennzoil Co., which left Texaco mired in bankruptcy court for
nearly a year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880524-0309 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-24-88 2052EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-FordDivisions     05-24 0224</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Ford Divisions,0232</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ford Splits Electrical-Electronics Division into Two New Divisions</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ford Motor Co. said Tuesday it is splitting its
Electrical and Electronics Division into two separate divisions,
one for automotive electronics and one for electrical and
fuel-handling systems.
   ``The application of electronics in Ford cars and trucks is
expected to grow significantly in importance in the next few
years,'' said O.B. Marx III, Ford's Diversified Products Operations
director for automotive components.
   ``At the same time we have major programs under way in
electrical and fuel-handling operations. So we chose to separate
the electro-mechanical functions from electronics products,'' Marx
said.
   Frank E. Macher, general manager of the Electrical and
Electronics Division, becomes general manager of the new
Electronics Division. Robert J. Womac, director of corporate
strategy for the old division, becomes general manager of the
Electrical and Fuel Handling Division, Ford said.
   The 14,800-worker Electronics Division handles all electronics
technology and products including powertrain controls, audio
systems, instruments and electronically controlled equipment such
as anti-lock brakes.
   The 6,084-worker Electrical and Fuel Handling Division is
responsible for equipment such as alternators, starters, fuel
pumps, small motors and ignition products.
   The Electronics division has plants in Pennsylvania, Mexico,
Ontario, Great Britain and Brazil. The Electrical and Fuel Handling
Division has Michigan plants in Rawsonville and Ypsilanti and a
plant in Bedford, Ind.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880524-0310 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-24-88 1937EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-SantaFe     05-24 0535</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Santa Fe,0554</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Santa Fe Reports Strong First Four Months</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: four months for earnings period is cq.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SALLY STREFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOPEKA, Kan. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Santa Fe Railroad had one of its best
four-month periods in recent history from January through April,
earning more than double what it made in the same period of 1987,
company officials said Tuesday.
   That made the railroad the star performer of Santa Fe Southern
Pacific Corp., a Chicago-based holding company, officials said at
the corporation's annual shareholders' meeting here.
   Improvements in the railroad's income resulted from a 22 percent
increase in carloads and increased efficiency, officials said.
   Overall, Santa Fe Southern had net income of $395.8 million, or
$2.52 per share, compared with $71 million, or 45 cents per share,
for the same period last year.
   The latest period's results included a $335.9 million gain from
the sale of assets. It also included a $35 million charge from the
company's restructuring program.
   Earnings from continuing operations were flat at $59.9 million,
or 38 cents per share, compared with $60.6 million, or 38 cents per
share, a year earlier.
   The company did not announce revenue figures.
   Also Tuesday, the company's board of directors elected Robert D.
Krebs to replace the retiring John S. Reed as chairman. Krebs also
will continue serving as president and chief executive officer.
   Officials told shareholders the sale of assets during the first
four months helped erase some of the debt Santa Fe incurred from a
one-time special dividend of $30 per share paid to shareholders
earlier this year.
   At Tuesday's sometimes contentious meeting, several shareholders
were critical of the special dividend, saying they would take a
large tax loss this year because of the way it was structured.
   Shareholders also voted to recommend overturning a ``poison
pill'' anti-takeover defense instituted by the corporation's
management. However, Krebs said both he and Reed, who remains on
the board of directors, would vote against following shareholders'
advice.
   The poison pill would be triggered if any shareholder's stake
exceeds 20 percent. If that happened, other Santa Fe shareholders
would be permitted to buy new stock at half price.
   Two major shareholders, Olympia & York and Henley Group Inc.,
have criticized the pill in the past. Both companies have attempted
to take over Santa Fe Southern during the past year.
   Krebs pointed out that those companies represented a majority of
the shareholders who voted against the pill Tuesday.
   Richard Foley, a Santa Fe employee and shareholder from Tucson,
Ariz., who supported the proposal to overturn the pill, said, ``The
measure passed today requires that Santa Fe management make a
decision to listen to the shareholders, or refuse to allow their
shareholders a voice in ownership.''
   Foley also criticized the board of directors' decision to sell
the Southern Pacific Transportation Co. to the Denver-based Rio
Grande Industries Inc.
   Meanwhile, at a news conference after the meeting, John Swartz,
president of the railroad, said the company's restructuring is
ahead of schedule.
   Under the restructuring announced in June 1987, Santa Fe
Railroad reduced its divisions from 11 to six, with one of the new
and enlarged divisions headquartered in Kansas City, Kan., and the
other in Newton, Kan.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
