<1ST_LINE>u f AM-DiamondStar     05-24 0278</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Diamond Star,0288</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mitsubishi to Switch Sedan Production from Illinois Plant to Japan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NORMAL, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Production of a four-door compact sedan
originally planned to begin next year at the new Diamond Star
Motors plant in Normal will begin instead this summer in Japan, a
newspaper reported Tuesday.
   The Bloomington Pantagraph said Mitsubishi Motors Corp. will
start building the sedans in Japan and marketing them in the United
States, a year before the Diamond Star facility is scheduled to
make them.
   Diamond Star begins production this September of a two-door,
front-wheel-drive sports coupe at its new $650 million plant. The
company is a joint venture of Chrysler Corp. and Mitsubishi.
   G. Glenn Gardner, chairman of Diamond Star, said his plant may
produce only the sports coupe if demand is high enough. If Diamond
Star begins building sedans, as planned, Mitsubishi will continue
to produce them in Japan as well.
   ``The plant here has its hands full launching the sports car,''
Gardner said Monday. ``We wanted to concentrate on that.''
   The sports car will be sold at prices starting at less than
$10,000.
   Chrysler will market the vehicle as the Plymouth Laser.
Mitsubishi Motor Sales of America, which has 205 dealerships in the
United States, also will distribute the car but has not announced
its name.
   Eventually, the 2 million-square-foot assembly plant will
produce 240,000 cars annually and employ 2,900 workers.
   The sedan will replace the Mitsubishi Mirage and the Chrysler
Colt models. Mitsubishi will market the sedan as the Mirage while
the Chrysler version will be marketed by its Jeep-Eagle division as
the Summit.
   Gardner said it will be priced in the $8,000 to $9,000 range.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
