<FILEID>AP-NR-05-24-88 2134EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-FordAerospace-BDM     05-24 0537</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Ford Aerospace-BDM,0558</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ford Aerospace Buying BDM International for $425 Million</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JANET BRAUNSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ford Aerospace Corp. said Tuesday it is buying
BDM International Inc., a defense services company, for about $425
million.
   In buying BDM, Ford Aerospace will get access to expertise used
by government defense, security and intelligence agencies, said
Eliot Benson, vice president and research director at Ferris and
Co. Inc. in Washington, D.C.
   BDM, based in McLean, Va., has participated in projects
including mobile basing for intercontinental missiles and the
application of space-oriented strategic defense technology _
President Reagan's Star Wars program.
   BDM, in turn, will benefit from Ford Aerospace's deep cash
pockets in competing for government contracts, which account for
more than 90 percent of BDM's revenue, Benson said.
   ``It's getting harder for companies to make money in the defense
business. There is severe competition for a pie that's not
growing,'' he said. After years of increased defense spending,
``we're seeing constraints ... making it more difficult for these
defense companies to grow and leading to more acquisitions.''
   Ford Aerospace, a wholly-owned subsidiary of Ford Motor Co.,
will pay $34.75 apiece for all Class A and Class B common shares of
BDM.
   BDM was founded in 1959 by Drs. Joseph V. Braddock, Bernard J.
Dunn and Daniel F. McDonald.
   The three founders have granted Ford Aerospace an irrevocable
option to purchase their Class B shares, representing 80.7 percent
of the voting power of all BDM stock.
   The agreement ``virtually assures that Ford will be able to
complete the acquisition,'' said James Hughes, BDM's general
counsel.
   Ford Aerospace will begin a tender offer for all BDM common
shares by May 31, the company said.
   ``This transaction is part of Ford Aerospace's strategy to
solidify its base and expand its business in the command, control,
communications and intelligence field,'' Ford Aerospace President
Donald B. Rassier said.
   ``It is hard to imagine a better fit of talents, technologies
and businesses, ... than Ford Aerospace and BDM,'' he said.
   BDM has 3,700 employees at 14 technology centers and 36 other
offices in the United States and foreign countries. It earned $5.3
million, or 44 cents a share, on revenue of $73 million in the
first quarter of 1988.
   In 1987, BDM earned $19.7 million, or $1.66 a share, on revenue
of $314 million. Benson said BDM has reported 18 consecutive years
of increased earnings.
   ``We have been assured a good measure of autonomy and clearly,
the combination is an exciting one in terms of future growth and
development,'' said Earle C. Williams, BDM president and chief
executive officer.
   In 1987, BDM was awarded government contracts worth about $400
million, while Ford Aerospace garnered government contracts worth
$1.3 billion, Ford spokesman Eugene Koch said.
   Ford does not release separate earnings data for its
subsidiaries.
   BDM provides professional and technical services in national
defense and security, communications, systems integration, energy,
logistics, space, information systems, manufacturing technology and
other areas.
   Ford Aerospace is involved in command, control, communications
and intelligence systems, tactical weapons systems, space systems
including communications and sensing satellites, and engineering
services.
   It has headquarters in California and Washington, D.C., and
major operations in California, Colorado, Maryland, Texas and
Virginia.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
